1
00:00:44,333 --> 00:00:46,582
- We're coming to the end.
- [crew] The end of what?

2
00:00:46,583 --> 00:00:48,874
The end of the movie.
The end of the shoot.

3
00:00:48,875 --> 00:00:50,999
- There's always the next one.
- Are you listening?

4
00:00:51,000 --> 00:00:54,499
I started getting dry eyeballs.
From nowhere.

5
00:00:54,500 --> 00:00:58,874
Like there was grit or something
constantly in them.

6
00:00:58,875 --> 00:01:01,665
{\an8}And there was an oculist here.
The one who does the lenses.

7
00:01:01,666 --> 00:01:02,915
{\an8}[crew 2] Hey, sorry.

8
00:01:02,916 --> 00:01:04,999
{\an8}Skip needs to do a check.
He thinks it might have slipped.

9
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:06,707
[sound recordist]
Silk shirt's causing problems.

10
00:01:06,708 --> 00:01:10,165
I'm not going to let this be a thing.
I said, "What do I need to do?"

11
00:01:10,166 --> 00:01:12,249
[sound recordist] Could you say
something, please, Jay?

12
00:01:12,250 --> 00:01:14,457
- [Jay] I love you.
- A little bit more, please.

13
00:01:14,458 --> 00:01:18,832
{\an8}[Jay] Ten, nine, eight, seven.
[accented] Tuesday, Thursday, Wednesday.

14
00:01:18,833 --> 00:01:21,915
- [sound recordist] Jay, you're the best.
- [Jay] There must be somebody better.

15
00:01:21,916 --> 00:01:24,332
We're seeing the whole
wide world on this one, folks.

16
00:01:24,333 --> 00:01:26,999
He gave me these drops,
and it totally went away.

17
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:28,665
Disappeared, the dryness.

18
00:01:28,666 --> 00:01:31,374
You've gotta be ahead of the game.
Two steps ahead.

19
00:01:31,375 --> 00:01:33,249
I just made a decision. I'm not gonna...

20
00:01:33,250 --> 00:01:37,374
Right now, your anxiety's at a ten,
so of course you feel like quitting.

21
00:01:37,375 --> 00:01:39,124
Because I'm your dad, that's how I know.

22
00:01:39,125 --> 00:01:41,790
Your hair feels great.
Have you been using that conditioner?

23
00:01:41,791 --> 00:01:45,165
- This is the worst part, the anticipation.
- Let me check your pant leg.

24
00:01:45,166 --> 00:01:48,790
[PA] I'm sorry to interrupt, Hailey would
like to see you in the bloodier coat.

25
00:01:48,791 --> 00:01:51,665
[actress] Did you have the peppers
or the ravioli? I should've had ravioli.

26
00:01:51,666 --> 00:01:52,874
[Jay] I just had my shake.

27
00:01:52,875 --> 00:01:54,915
[actress] Who'd want to be young?

28
00:01:54,916 --> 00:01:58,165
- [crew 3] Find a place to hide, people!
- [Jay] Can we do it with the dog?

29
00:01:58,166 --> 00:02:00,290
[crew 4] Jay wants the dog.
Can we bring the dog?

30
00:02:00,291 --> 00:02:02,165
[crew 5] That dog makes
more money than any of us.

31
00:02:02,166 --> 00:02:04,040
[crew 3] Can we see a light drizzle?

32
00:02:04,041 --> 00:02:06,124
That's a drizzle? It's more like a deluge.

33
00:02:06,125 --> 00:02:07,915
[crew 5] Believe me, that's the drizzle.

34
00:02:07,916 --> 00:02:10,999
[man on cellphone] I have watched
you bloom throughout this tournament.

35
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:13,457
And you really found your second serve.

36
00:02:13,458 --> 00:02:18,374
You think Coco doesn't get butterflies?
Doesn't dread? Doesn't call her dad?

37
00:02:18,375 --> 00:02:20,707
- [Jay] This is me in the bloodier coat.
- Bloodier is better.

38
00:02:20,708 --> 00:02:21,957
- I got your espresso.
- [Jay] Thanks.

39
00:02:21,958 --> 00:02:23,957
Don't let me have
more than a sip after 4.

40
00:02:23,958 --> 00:02:26,040
You wouldn't know.
I see coffee, I drink it.

41
00:02:26,041 --> 00:02:28,040
...it'll be the last movie for all of us.

42
00:02:28,041 --> 00:02:30,165
They'll turn out the lights,
and that'll be that.

43
00:02:30,166 --> 00:02:32,665
Of course you should
have called me, puppy.

44
00:02:32,666 --> 00:02:34,374
Don't beat yourself up about that.

45
00:02:34,375 --> 00:02:36,499
You're just getting yourself
from all angles now.

46
00:02:36,500 --> 00:02:38,040
[crew 6] I had a double in the 5K.

47
00:02:38,041 --> 00:02:40,500
[cellphone man]
Guilt is a secondary emotion.

48
00:02:41,291 --> 00:02:42,999
- Thanks, Clay.
- Always a pleasure, Jay.

49
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:45,832
[cellphone man] I did not have any bread
today, no. That was your brother.

50
00:02:45,833 --> 00:02:47,999
[director] What are you thinking?
We got a couple good ones.

51
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:50,540
[Jay] It should just be how it happens.
Let what happens happen.

52
00:02:50,541 --> 00:02:52,832
- [director] You want to do another?
- [Jay] Let's see what happens.

53
00:02:52,833 --> 00:02:55,500
[crew 3] Okay, quiet, please!
This will be for a take.

54
00:02:56,000 --> 00:02:58,082
- Roll sound.
- [sound crew] Rolling.

55
00:02:58,083 --> 00:02:59,540
[sound crew 2] Sound speed.

56
00:02:59,541 --> 00:03:01,665
- [director] Quiet, please.
- [sound crew] 138 Echo, take 11.

57
00:03:01,666 --> 00:03:04,249
[cellphone man] Hold on, sweetheart.
I'm just gonna watch this take.

58
00:03:04,250 --> 00:03:05,791
[director] And... action!

59
00:03:07,041 --> 00:03:09,458
I don't want to be here anymore, Jerry.

60
00:03:10,666 --> 00:03:12,791
I want to leave this party.

61
00:03:14,500 --> 00:03:16,457
You know-- He's in too soon.
Can we go again?

62
00:03:16,458 --> 00:03:17,915
- Delay Jerry just a beat.
- [director] Cut!

63
00:03:17,916 --> 00:03:20,124
- Don't cut. Keep rolling, please.
- [director] Keep rolling.

64
00:03:20,125 --> 00:03:21,790
More of the anchovy paste on my--

65
00:03:21,791 --> 00:03:23,665
- [director] Room quiet, please.
- Thanks.

66
00:03:23,666 --> 00:03:25,958
- Okay. All right.
- [sound crew 2] Guys, I'm rolling.

67
00:03:27,083 --> 00:03:28,791
[rain pattering]

68
00:03:30,208 --> 00:03:31,125
[director] Action.

69
00:03:35,083 --> 00:03:37,458
I don't want to be here anymore, Jerry.

70
00:03:38,083 --> 00:03:39,000
[exhales]

71
00:03:39,500 --> 00:03:41,125
I want to leave the party.

72
00:03:43,333 --> 00:03:44,416
In a way...

73
00:03:45,958 --> 00:03:47,290
I already died.

74
00:03:47,291 --> 00:03:50,374
[sirens wailing in distance]

75
00:03:50,375 --> 00:03:51,666
I'm lucky.

76
00:03:54,083 --> 00:03:57,540
- My time passed while I was still alive.
- [thunder rumbles]

77
00:03:57,541 --> 00:04:00,250
[grunts] I got to see it
end before it ended.

78
00:04:03,041 --> 00:04:05,041
[thunder, sirens continue]

79
00:04:07,708 --> 00:04:10,458
That's a crazy thing. When you die...

80
00:04:13,125 --> 00:04:15,125
everything you thought you were...

81
00:04:17,208 --> 00:04:18,250
isn't true.

82
00:04:20,833 --> 00:04:22,000
[dog whines softly]

83
00:04:25,083 --> 00:04:26,500
You're a good dog.

84
00:04:28,916 --> 00:04:30,166
[gun clatters on pavement]

85
00:04:31,083 --> 00:04:32,999
[director] And... cut. Great!

86
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:34,832
- Can we go again?
- [director] Really?

87
00:04:34,833 --> 00:04:37,165
I'd like another one.
I mean, I think I can do it better.

88
00:04:37,166 --> 00:04:38,790
- [crew 3] Quiet, please!
- [people shushing]

89
00:04:38,791 --> 00:04:40,416
Different. I don't know.

90
00:04:41,458 --> 00:04:43,582
- But if you're happy--
- Very happy.

91
00:04:43,583 --> 00:04:45,290
- Okay.
- If you have an idea...

92
00:04:45,291 --> 00:04:47,540
I thought I had an idea.
But you're happy?

93
00:04:47,541 --> 00:04:50,207
I'm ecstatic.
But of course you can have one more.

94
00:04:50,208 --> 00:04:52,332
- You feel good?
- I really do.

95
00:04:52,333 --> 00:04:54,457
- Okay.
- I liked a couple of the early ones too.

96
00:04:54,458 --> 00:04:55,500
Cool.

97
00:04:57,250 --> 00:04:59,416
- Good?
- [exhales, chuckles]

98
00:05:00,083 --> 00:05:01,458
[exhales]

99
00:05:02,333 --> 00:05:03,207
Good.

100
00:05:03,208 --> 00:05:05,832
[crew 3] And that is
a picture wrap on Jay Kelly!

101
00:05:05,833 --> 00:05:06,915
[crew cheering]

102
00:05:06,916 --> 00:05:09,540
And a wrap on <i>Eight Men From Now!</i>

103
00:05:09,541 --> 00:05:11,665
[applause, cheering]

104
00:05:11,666 --> 00:05:14,125
[uplifting orchestral music playing]

105
00:05:15,291 --> 00:05:16,832
Well done, man. It's gonna be a good one.

106
00:05:16,833 --> 00:05:18,833
It's a total honor.
Thank you for trusting me.

107
00:05:19,333 --> 00:05:22,874
We made the tennis finals, Vivienne.
That's something to celebrate.

108
00:05:22,875 --> 00:05:26,832
So get your rest, because
the Greenbergs are tough opponents.

109
00:05:26,833 --> 00:05:30,582
But my money is on you and me, kiddo.

110
00:05:30,583 --> 00:05:31,790
I love you, Vivi.

111
00:05:31,791 --> 00:05:35,790
- José! Pops! You guys are awesome!
- Thank you so much. Thank you.

112
00:05:35,791 --> 00:05:38,374
- Skip, you guys never get the credit.
- [Skip] That means the world.

113
00:05:38,375 --> 00:05:41,082
- Let me call you back, sweetheart.
- [crew 8] I appreciate the gift.

114
00:05:41,083 --> 00:05:42,040
Okay, guys. Guys.

115
00:05:42,041 --> 00:05:45,083
Everybody, thank you all so much.
You did a great job.

116
00:05:45,708 --> 00:05:47,957
A couple of timely reminders.
We got the Omega event

117
00:05:47,958 --> 00:05:50,249
tomorrow morning, 11 a.m. pick up.
Candy will--

118
00:05:50,250 --> 00:05:51,332
Will be there at 9.

119
00:05:51,333 --> 00:05:52,457
- Were you watching?
- Yes.

120
00:05:52,458 --> 00:05:55,165
- You didn't say anything.
- You get annoyed if I give an opinion.

121
00:05:55,166 --> 00:05:57,082
If you don't say anything,
then I assume you hated it.

122
00:05:57,083 --> 00:05:59,749
It was brilliant,
I think take seven was the one.

123
00:05:59,750 --> 00:06:00,915
Why seven?

124
00:06:00,916 --> 00:06:03,124
- I'm not getting into this.
- Into what?

125
00:06:03,125 --> 00:06:05,457
You always get this way
whenever we wrap a movie.

126
00:06:05,458 --> 00:06:07,416
Emotional, and then you blame me.

127
00:06:08,333 --> 00:06:11,207
Maybe it was seven.
I guess they could always cut to the dog.

128
00:06:11,208 --> 00:06:12,832
That dog was great.

129
00:06:12,833 --> 00:06:15,749
What's it like, Jay,
to experience your own death?

130
00:06:15,750 --> 00:06:17,582
- I didn't really die.
- No, I know that.

131
00:06:17,583 --> 00:06:19,749
But how do you perform
something you've never done?

132
00:06:19,750 --> 00:06:22,499
- Pretend, Candy.
- I don't know if I'd want that ability.

133
00:06:22,500 --> 00:06:25,540
Guys, thank you all for working so hard
and being so great.

134
00:06:25,541 --> 00:06:28,082
- Couldn't do it without you.
- [crew 8] Thank you for having us, Jay.

135
00:06:28,083 --> 00:06:30,208
- You're the best.
- [Jay] I am the best.

136
00:06:31,500 --> 00:06:34,499
Why is there always a slice of cheesecake
in every room I'm in?

137
00:06:34,500 --> 00:06:37,957
It's in your rider, along with the fruit
and all the different kinds of water.

138
00:06:37,958 --> 00:06:41,165
How is it in my rider
when I don't even like cheesecake?

139
00:06:41,166 --> 00:06:42,249
You once said you liked it.

140
00:06:42,250 --> 00:06:44,457
- I never did.
- You did. You just don't remember.

141
00:06:44,458 --> 00:06:47,499
If anything, my rider should say
"no cheesecake." Never cheesecake.

142
00:06:47,500 --> 00:06:51,249
And... dinner with Daisy tomorrow.

143
00:06:51,250 --> 00:06:54,749
- Chef Mario is doing the special tamales.
- Oh, good.

144
00:06:54,750 --> 00:06:58,415
Also, Antonio from
the Tuscan Arts Festival called again.

145
00:06:58,416 --> 00:07:01,249
- They need an answer about the tribute.
- I said no.

146
00:07:01,250 --> 00:07:02,207
And I told them no.

147
00:07:02,208 --> 00:07:04,582
- But they're very persistent.
- And it's still no.

148
00:07:04,583 --> 00:07:07,040
I just mention it
because they're quite reputable.

149
00:07:07,041 --> 00:07:08,624
Not on your life.

150
00:07:08,625 --> 00:07:11,165
- It was gonna be tight anyways.
- No tributes. Ever.

151
00:07:11,166 --> 00:07:13,333
We start shooting
in a couple weeks. Okay.

152
00:07:18,708 --> 00:07:20,708
[entourage chattering]

153
00:07:32,333 --> 00:07:35,207
That was the point when I realized
I was more intelligent than you.

154
00:07:35,208 --> 00:07:36,499
[Jay] What does that mean?

155
00:07:36,500 --> 00:07:38,166
- I know more than you.
- [Jay] Do you?

156
00:07:39,500 --> 00:07:41,750
- No, you don't.
- Yes, I do.

157
00:07:42,583 --> 00:07:44,457
- About what?
- About everything.

158
00:07:44,458 --> 00:07:46,207
What is the capital of Croatia?

159
00:07:46,208 --> 00:07:49,290
I barely know
the fucking capital of California.

160
00:07:49,291 --> 00:07:50,790
Who was Agamemnon's wife?

161
00:07:50,791 --> 00:07:53,999
See, now, these are just facts.
Anybody can know facts.

162
00:07:54,000 --> 00:07:57,749
I know more about emotional stuff.
You have to live a life for that.

163
00:07:57,750 --> 00:08:00,665
I'm more emotionally intelligent.

164
00:08:00,666 --> 00:08:02,583
Don't you want me to be
smarter than you?

165
00:08:03,083 --> 00:08:05,374
- Isn't that the whole point of this?
- Yeah.

166
00:08:05,375 --> 00:08:08,541
- Don't you think it's a bit early?
- I can't help the timing.

167
00:08:09,500 --> 00:08:11,665
- It looks good.
- Oh, yeah?

168
00:08:11,666 --> 00:08:12,582
You can't tell.

169
00:08:12,583 --> 00:08:14,957
Yeah, she did a good job.
She left a little gray in.

170
00:08:14,958 --> 00:08:17,415
- They usually make it too black.
- It's not...

171
00:08:17,416 --> 00:08:19,457
No, no, it's just right.

172
00:08:19,458 --> 00:08:21,749
You should go fully gray,
if you want my opinion.

173
00:08:21,750 --> 00:08:23,832
Yeah, but not just yet.

174
00:08:23,833 --> 00:08:27,582
All right, well, I'm going to go
meet Moses and Rio.

175
00:08:27,583 --> 00:08:28,665
I love you.

176
00:08:28,666 --> 00:08:34,082
Hey, aren't we having dinner tonight?
Mario's doing the tamales.

177
00:08:34,083 --> 00:08:35,375
Did we say that?

178
00:08:39,458 --> 00:08:40,458
All right.

179
00:08:41,166 --> 00:08:45,665
Go on. Be with your friends.
There'll be other dinners.

180
00:08:45,666 --> 00:08:49,207
I wrapped this last one.
I start the Louis Brothers movie

181
00:08:49,208 --> 00:08:52,500
right here on the lots.
I'll be around for the summer.

182
00:08:53,083 --> 00:08:56,582
I'm going to Europe with Rio and Moses
and some friends. I told you that.

183
00:08:56,583 --> 00:08:59,458
- I thought that was in July.
- No, it was always June.

184
00:08:59,958 --> 00:09:03,750
I'm leaving on Saturday for Paris,
and we're making our way to Tuscany.

185
00:09:04,250 --> 00:09:07,207
Saturday? I mean... That's...

186
00:09:07,208 --> 00:09:10,500
Saturday. That's-- It's too soon.

187
00:09:11,000 --> 00:09:14,290
I got two weeks off.
We won't have had time to hang out.

188
00:09:14,291 --> 00:09:17,375
- This is your last summer.
- That's why I want to see my friends.

189
00:09:17,958 --> 00:09:20,582
It'll be so lonely here without you.

190
00:09:20,583 --> 00:09:24,500
- No, it won't. You're never alone.
- Really? I think I'm always alone.

191
00:09:25,333 --> 00:09:26,541
- Thanks, Silvano.
- You're welcome.

192
00:09:28,291 --> 00:09:30,000
Eh. All right.

193
00:09:30,708 --> 00:09:31,541
Mm.

194
00:09:33,166 --> 00:09:34,250
How about if I joined?

195
00:09:34,833 --> 00:09:37,874
Well, we're going to this really great
jazz festival in Paris

196
00:09:37,875 --> 00:09:40,374
which has a lot of people,
so you can't do that.

197
00:09:40,375 --> 00:09:42,957
And then we're taking a train
with no first class to Pienza,

198
00:09:42,958 --> 00:09:45,665
which you also can't do.
And we're sleeping in tents.

199
00:09:45,666 --> 00:09:46,958
Which... I mean, come on.

200
00:09:47,541 --> 00:09:49,957
- I basically grew up in a tent.
- But not anymore.

201
00:09:49,958 --> 00:09:52,207
Well, the muscle memory's still there.

202
00:09:52,208 --> 00:09:54,124
Okay, well, that's good. I gotta go.

203
00:09:54,125 --> 00:09:57,332
- Hey, Ronnie.
- [Ron] Daisy. [kisses]

204
00:09:57,333 --> 00:09:59,874
Vivienne's been posting about the tennis.
You guys are adorable.

205
00:09:59,875 --> 00:10:02,499
Oh. We made the finals.
We're so excited.

206
00:10:02,500 --> 00:10:04,083
You got a friend now, Dad.

207
00:10:05,333 --> 00:10:06,500
Want a tamale?

208
00:10:08,083 --> 00:10:09,540
Peter Schneider died.

209
00:10:09,541 --> 00:10:10,957
Fuck, I gotta call him.

210
00:10:10,958 --> 00:10:13,957
No, I just found out and came here.

211
00:10:13,958 --> 00:10:15,208
He died.

212
00:10:17,208 --> 00:10:18,041
Really?

213
00:10:19,375 --> 00:10:20,458
I'm sorry.

214
00:10:21,708 --> 00:10:23,708
I know how much you loved him.

215
00:10:32,208 --> 00:10:34,166
His message is still on my phone.

216
00:10:37,916 --> 00:10:39,707
When was the last time you saw him?

217
00:10:39,708 --> 00:10:42,041
I don't know. Maybe six months ago.

218
00:10:50,291 --> 00:10:52,458
Sweetheart,
I'm going to make you a sandwich.

219
00:10:53,208 --> 00:10:55,375
[Jay] <i>I'm glad to see you, Peter.
I've missed you.</i>

220
00:10:56,041 --> 00:10:57,582
Where do you keep the knives?

221
00:10:57,583 --> 00:10:59,624
That magnet thing
over by the cutting board.

222
00:10:59,625 --> 00:11:01,124
- Oh, yes.
- Barbara, I'm sorry.

223
00:11:01,125 --> 00:11:04,375
- We made a mess after you already cleaned.
- [Barbara] That's okay, Jay.

224
00:11:05,375 --> 00:11:06,208
You know, Pop...

225
00:11:07,625 --> 00:11:10,000
Lately, I feel like
my life doesn't really...

226
00:11:10,833 --> 00:11:11,875
feel real.

227
00:11:13,291 --> 00:11:15,166
Maybe a better way of putting it is

228
00:11:15,791 --> 00:11:17,250
that my life doesn't really...

229
00:11:18,333 --> 00:11:19,290
feel real.

230
00:11:19,291 --> 00:11:21,874
I heard about your breakup
with the hand model.

231
00:11:21,875 --> 00:11:24,458
- Breakups are like deaths, aren't they?
- [Jay] Mm.

232
00:11:24,958 --> 00:11:27,166
- Mayonnaise?
- Refrigerator, on the shelf.

233
00:11:28,458 --> 00:11:29,291
[Peter] Oh, yes.

234
00:11:30,875 --> 00:11:32,041
How are the girls?

235
00:11:32,625 --> 00:11:34,707
Daisy graduates this spring,

236
00:11:34,708 --> 00:11:37,332
and then she's at Johns Hopkins

237
00:11:37,333 --> 00:11:39,790
for biochemistry, if you can believe it.

238
00:11:39,791 --> 00:11:42,041
- She's a brilliant girl.
- Then...

239
00:11:42,666 --> 00:11:44,415
Jess is in San Diego.

240
00:11:44,416 --> 00:11:45,666
That's...

241
00:11:46,541 --> 00:11:48,166
I don't know what to do there.

242
00:11:49,208 --> 00:11:51,374
You'll figure it out.
Do you have olive oil?

243
00:11:51,375 --> 00:11:52,500
Yep, over there.

244
00:11:53,791 --> 00:11:56,665
I've been thinking a lot
about <i>Cranberry Street.</i>

245
00:11:56,666 --> 00:12:00,457
We had such fun shooting that, didn't we?

246
00:12:00,458 --> 00:12:02,457
[Peter] We were always laughing.

247
00:12:02,458 --> 00:12:05,374
D'you know it's the 35th anniversary
coming up?

248
00:12:05,375 --> 00:12:07,958
Jess was born the next year.
That's how I know that.

249
00:12:08,916 --> 00:12:10,832
All my memories are movies.

250
00:12:10,833 --> 00:12:12,541
That's what movies are for us.

251
00:12:13,416 --> 00:12:17,500
Pieces of time. [chuckles]

252
00:12:18,000 --> 00:12:20,415
- Do you have pickles?
- In the pantry.

253
00:12:20,416 --> 00:12:21,625
I think.

254
00:12:23,333 --> 00:12:24,582
Oh, yes, here they are.

255
00:12:24,583 --> 00:12:27,707
- Check the expiration.
- Pickles don't expire, my love.

256
00:12:27,708 --> 00:12:29,625
[Jay] They definitely do.

257
00:12:30,250 --> 00:12:31,541
[Peter] They're fine.

258
00:12:32,291 --> 00:12:34,332
Thirty-five years. Is that possible?

259
00:12:34,333 --> 00:12:35,749
It's all possible, son.

260
00:12:35,750 --> 00:12:37,374
There was such magic on that one.

261
00:12:37,375 --> 00:12:39,915
I was spoiled.
I thought they'd all be like that.

262
00:12:39,916 --> 00:12:42,582
- They're not.
- So few are.

263
00:12:42,583 --> 00:12:44,958
I'm glad you've been thinking about us.

264
00:12:45,666 --> 00:12:48,624
I have a picture
I'd like for us to do together.

265
00:12:48,625 --> 00:12:50,749
It's the prostitute picture
I told you about.

266
00:12:50,750 --> 00:12:52,749
- Oh, yeah?
- Oh, yes.

267
00:12:52,750 --> 00:12:56,915
Well, I'm shooting a movie now,
and then I'm doing one right after.

268
00:12:56,916 --> 00:12:59,999
Do you know those kids,
the Louis Brothers?

269
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:01,124
They're big fans of yours.

270
00:13:01,125 --> 00:13:03,499
I didn't take to their picture.
Too much MTV cutting.

271
00:13:03,500 --> 00:13:06,665
- I don't know how much I'd be available.
- I can wait for you, darling.

272
00:13:06,666 --> 00:13:08,749
Peter, I told you it's just not for me.

273
00:13:08,750 --> 00:13:10,749
I did a rewrite
with my assistant, Shelley.

274
00:13:10,750 --> 00:13:12,915
I think you met her
at that idiot's premiere.

275
00:13:12,916 --> 00:13:15,207
We made it more contemporary.
They have cell phones.

276
00:13:15,208 --> 00:13:17,540
It's not a territory
that I want to explore.

277
00:13:17,541 --> 00:13:19,415
I thought I'd ask Daphne to play the wife.

278
00:13:19,416 --> 00:13:22,624
- She is retired.
- If you could just attach yourself.

279
00:13:22,625 --> 00:13:24,457
My lawyer says we need a name.

280
00:13:24,458 --> 00:13:26,291
I can't do that.

281
00:13:28,333 --> 00:13:29,625
I'll be honest with you, son.

282
00:13:31,708 --> 00:13:33,166
I need the money.

283
00:13:33,750 --> 00:13:36,415
- I'll give you the money.
- But I need to make another picture.

284
00:13:36,416 --> 00:13:38,457
I want to do two, right in a row.

285
00:13:38,458 --> 00:13:39,708
Back-to-back.

286
00:13:40,500 --> 00:13:42,250
You know what dear Truffaut said.

287
00:13:42,750 --> 00:13:45,749
[French accent]
"Sometimes quantity is impressive."

288
00:13:45,750 --> 00:13:48,207
Art is personal, Pop. You know that.

289
00:13:48,208 --> 00:13:49,166
[Peter] I understand.

290
00:13:50,708 --> 00:13:52,333
But if you could just lend your name.

291
00:13:53,416 --> 00:13:54,416
I can't.

292
00:13:56,000 --> 00:13:57,041
I'm sorry.

293
00:14:04,166 --> 00:14:05,125
It's delicious.

294
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:09,333
Pickles don't expire.

295
00:14:12,500 --> 00:14:14,166
My dad was never there.

296
00:14:15,708 --> 00:14:18,666
In the '70s and '80s,
he was always on movie sets.

297
00:14:19,291 --> 00:14:20,957
And when he started to struggle,

298
00:14:20,958 --> 00:14:24,624
after he made a couple of
what many of you in Hollywood would call

299
00:14:24,625 --> 00:14:26,749
"bombs" or "turkeys,"

300
00:14:26,750 --> 00:14:30,250
or, forgive me, I'm not in the business.
I don't know the language.

301
00:14:31,208 --> 00:14:36,291
"Flops" that are now considered
cult classics by Gen Z.

302
00:14:37,125 --> 00:14:41,083
After the industry turned its back on him
after his third bankruptcy,

303
00:14:41,583 --> 00:14:43,415
after he was forced to sell
his beloved mansion,

304
00:14:43,416 --> 00:14:45,124
Casa del Oro in Bel Air,

305
00:14:45,125 --> 00:14:47,291
and move into the one-bedroom in Encino,

306
00:14:48,416 --> 00:14:50,291
he was always trying to raise money,

307
00:14:51,375 --> 00:14:53,166
dreaming of the next picture.

308
00:14:54,250 --> 00:14:57,375
As he lay dying,
he turned to me, and he said,

309
00:14:58,125 --> 00:15:00,000
"I know how the movie ends.

310
00:15:04,083 --> 00:15:05,457
It's about love."

311
00:15:05,458 --> 00:15:06,915
[people chattering]

312
00:15:06,916 --> 00:15:08,582
[woman] You don't remember me, do you?

313
00:15:08,583 --> 00:15:10,375
- Of course I do.
- No, you don't.

314
00:15:10,875 --> 00:15:12,457
- Yes, I do.
- Where do you know me from?

315
00:15:12,458 --> 00:15:16,040
I was in the only movie
he directed on horseback.

316
00:15:16,041 --> 00:15:18,499
I love you both.
I think I have to go rescue Jay.

317
00:15:18,500 --> 00:15:20,415
How long do you think--

318
00:15:20,416 --> 00:15:22,582
- I got beach cleanup at 3.
- We'll get you there.

319
00:15:22,583 --> 00:15:25,374
- [Vivienne] If I'm late, it won't count.
- Just take the car.

320
00:15:25,375 --> 00:15:27,832
Not surprisingly, it was his worst film.

321
00:15:27,833 --> 00:15:30,582
- [woman] You have no idea who I am.
- I do. Yes.

322
00:15:30,583 --> 00:15:32,000
I don't believe you.

323
00:15:33,791 --> 00:15:35,458
Thanks for coming, Jay.

324
00:15:36,083 --> 00:15:37,375
I'm so sorry, Nathan.

325
00:15:37,875 --> 00:15:41,707
You know, Dad always said
how lucky he was to have found you.

326
00:15:41,708 --> 00:15:42,666
He changed my life.

327
00:15:43,375 --> 00:15:45,166
He thought the same about you.

328
00:15:45,958 --> 00:15:48,125
He wanted you to have
one of his neckerchiefs.

329
00:15:50,333 --> 00:15:53,290
I am glad we came.
It makes it all more real.

330
00:15:53,291 --> 00:15:55,499
- None of this feels real.
- I know.

331
00:15:55,500 --> 00:15:59,041
Death is always so surprising,
particularly in LA.

332
00:16:00,041 --> 00:16:01,041
I like the neckerchief.

333
00:16:01,708 --> 00:16:03,750
- You want it?
- Thank you.

334
00:16:04,250 --> 00:16:06,124
Why didn't I just do
another movie for him?

335
00:16:06,125 --> 00:16:08,290
You're feeling this way
because you're a good person.

336
00:16:08,291 --> 00:16:11,707
Just lend my name.
'Cause he just wanted my name.

337
00:16:11,708 --> 00:16:13,541
- Jay?
- Hey, man.

338
00:16:16,208 --> 00:16:17,416
- Tim?
- Yeah.

339
00:16:18,041 --> 00:16:20,165
Timothy. Hey.

340
00:16:20,166 --> 00:16:22,540
Hey. Don't worry,
I'm-I'm not stalking you.

341
00:16:22,541 --> 00:16:24,124
No, no, no, it's--

342
00:16:24,125 --> 00:16:25,874
- Hey, we just did the--
- Yeah.

343
00:16:25,875 --> 00:16:27,624
- We lost a great one there.
- Yeah, it's sad.

344
00:16:27,625 --> 00:16:30,249
- He was really special.
- We're just busy all the time,

345
00:16:30,250 --> 00:16:32,040
and then people are dying.

346
00:16:32,041 --> 00:16:34,874
Ron, this is Timothy, my old roommate.

347
00:16:34,875 --> 00:16:38,082
We were in acting class together.
My old budd-ay.

348
00:16:38,083 --> 00:16:40,540
- Budd-ay.
- Yes, yes. Tim. Nice to see you.

349
00:16:40,541 --> 00:16:43,457
Ron Sukenick, Jay's manager and friend.

350
00:16:43,458 --> 00:16:45,332
- Yeah, I've told you about him.
- Heard a lot about you.

351
00:16:45,333 --> 00:16:47,540
Really? Really, you have?

352
00:16:47,541 --> 00:16:49,500
Oh, well, all good, I hope.

353
00:16:50,250 --> 00:16:52,874
'Cause we were some
pretty bad boys back in the day.

354
00:16:52,875 --> 00:16:54,040
[laughs]

355
00:16:54,041 --> 00:16:55,124
Yeah.

356
00:16:55,125 --> 00:16:57,124
- How have you been?
- I'm good, you know.

357
00:16:57,125 --> 00:17:00,040
Living the life, you know.
How are you doing?

358
00:17:00,041 --> 00:17:02,207
Well, that's a stupid question.
You're doing great.

359
00:17:02,208 --> 00:17:04,458
I'm all right. I'm all right, you know.

360
00:17:05,125 --> 00:17:06,290
It's good to see you.

361
00:17:06,291 --> 00:17:07,749
- You too.
- Yeah.

362
00:17:07,750 --> 00:17:08,666
Man.

363
00:17:10,041 --> 00:17:11,333
Okay, well...

364
00:17:12,541 --> 00:17:13,582
See you, man.

365
00:17:13,583 --> 00:17:14,916
- All right.
- Nice to see you.

366
00:17:19,458 --> 00:17:21,333
[awkward chuckling]

367
00:17:23,750 --> 00:17:25,708
I'm not following you.
I'm parked over here.

368
00:17:27,000 --> 00:17:29,290
Maybe we should
grab a coffee or something sometime.

369
00:17:29,291 --> 00:17:32,082
Oh, man, that would be great, you know.
And how would I--

370
00:17:32,083 --> 00:17:34,207
We-- Maybe I'll contact
your office or something?

371
00:17:34,208 --> 00:17:36,124
- [Ron] Just call me.
- I'll get the message if you--

372
00:17:36,125 --> 00:17:37,666
- There you go.
- Oh. Yeah.

373
00:17:38,250 --> 00:17:39,999
Okay. Great.

374
00:17:40,000 --> 00:17:42,500
And if it's not cool,
don't feel obligated.

375
00:17:46,041 --> 00:17:47,500
Actually, I have time now.

376
00:17:50,208 --> 00:17:51,790
Oh, that's great. Hey.

377
00:17:51,791 --> 00:17:55,082
Uh, do you remember Chez Jay
by the water?

378
00:17:55,083 --> 00:17:57,040
Sure, yeah, okay. I'll meet you there.

379
00:17:57,041 --> 00:17:58,208
Budd-ay!

380
00:17:58,791 --> 00:18:00,540
[chuckles]

381
00:18:00,541 --> 00:18:03,000
- Do I follow you?
- It's all right, Silvano, you can go home.

382
00:18:03,500 --> 00:18:04,665
We're okay with this guy?

383
00:18:04,666 --> 00:18:06,665
He's an old friend.
I haven't seen him in years.

384
00:18:06,666 --> 00:18:08,374
- There will be people there.
- It's all right.

385
00:18:08,375 --> 00:18:10,082
I remember people. I'll see you tomorrow.

386
00:18:10,083 --> 00:18:12,999
No, you won't. Remember?
I have the tennis finals with Vivi.

387
00:18:13,000 --> 00:18:15,457
- That's right. Good luck.
- Take it easy on the drinks.

388
00:18:15,458 --> 00:18:17,957
- Yeah, I will.
- 'Cause it's an emotional day.

389
00:18:17,958 --> 00:18:19,125
Stick to beer.

390
00:18:27,125 --> 00:18:29,124
["Thunder Island" by Jay Ferguson playing]

391
00:18:29,125 --> 00:18:30,540
<i>♪ Doo-doo-doo-doo, doo-doo-doo ♪</i>

392
00:18:30,541 --> 00:18:32,832
[Tim] My guru says
that when someone is dying

393
00:18:32,833 --> 00:18:35,999
and getting closer
to the spiritual world-- Thank you.

394
00:18:36,000 --> 00:18:38,499
That they get less afraid of death.

395
00:18:38,500 --> 00:18:40,915
You got a guru, man. That's great.

396
00:18:40,916 --> 00:18:43,832
Death, it becomes less real.

397
00:18:43,833 --> 00:18:44,916
And...

398
00:18:45,416 --> 00:18:50,207
of course power and success
become completely unreal,

399
00:18:50,208 --> 00:18:51,999
because they're no longer relevant.

400
00:18:52,000 --> 00:18:54,916
But like Peter said, all that's left...

401
00:18:56,208 --> 00:18:57,041
is love.

402
00:18:57,833 --> 00:18:59,207
- That was beautiful.
- I know.

403
00:18:59,208 --> 00:19:00,290
[woman] Okay, I'm doing it.

404
00:19:00,291 --> 00:19:02,499
- Hi. Could I get a picture?
- Oh, yeah, sure.

405
00:19:02,500 --> 00:19:04,083
- Okay, thank you.
- Yeah, here we go.

406
00:19:04,750 --> 00:19:05,750
- Got it?
- Yep.

407
00:19:06,250 --> 00:19:07,790
Love to get your guru's number.

408
00:19:07,791 --> 00:19:10,375
Oh, yeah, he's magic. He's best by text.

409
00:19:11,833 --> 00:19:13,708
- This place is so great.
- [Tim chuckles]

410
00:19:14,208 --> 00:19:15,832
I haven't been here since...

411
00:19:15,833 --> 00:19:17,332
since we were in class.

412
00:19:17,333 --> 00:19:19,041
- Do you see anyone from class?
- No.

413
00:19:19,625 --> 00:19:21,958
- No. Do you?
- Oh, yeah. We have reunions.

414
00:19:22,625 --> 00:19:24,832
I think that you're
the only one that still works.

415
00:19:24,833 --> 00:19:27,040
Oh, Cindy does a lot of voiceovers.

416
00:19:27,041 --> 00:19:29,249
But you were the one we all looked up to.

417
00:19:29,250 --> 00:19:31,082
- Oh, no, no, no.
- Oh, yeah.

418
00:19:31,083 --> 00:19:33,457
You were the best of all of us.
You were method.

419
00:19:33,458 --> 00:19:34,541
I wasn't method.

420
00:19:35,291 --> 00:19:37,624
- You were method.
- I was method light.

421
00:19:37,625 --> 00:19:40,791
You could do anything.
I could watch you do anything.

422
00:19:41,416 --> 00:19:43,833
I could watch you read this menu.

423
00:19:45,125 --> 00:19:48,583
Do that thing. Do it.
Read the menu. Come on.

424
00:19:51,291 --> 00:19:55,000
Okay, all right. All right.
This is no emotional choice.

425
00:19:56,458 --> 00:19:58,040
Uh, truffle parmesan fries,

426
00:19:58,041 --> 00:20:01,374
Brussels sprouts with balsamic
honey glaze and bacon, 12 dollars.

427
00:20:01,375 --> 00:20:03,624
Wedge of iceberg lettuce, shrimp cocktail,

428
00:20:03,625 --> 00:20:06,124
calamari with lemon aioli sauce,
15 dollars.

429
00:20:06,125 --> 00:20:07,083
Hey...

430
00:20:08,041 --> 00:20:10,582
- Now do it with an emotional choice.
- I don't know, man.

431
00:20:10,583 --> 00:20:12,582
I don't do this anymore.
I'm a child therapist.

432
00:20:12,583 --> 00:20:14,166
[drums table] Do it.

433
00:20:15,375 --> 00:20:17,124
Jay Kelly stare.

434
00:20:17,125 --> 00:20:19,416
- And action!
- [both laugh]

435
00:20:19,916 --> 00:20:21,958
Okay. All right.

436
00:20:26,375 --> 00:20:27,874
[inhales deeply]

437
00:20:27,875 --> 00:20:29,750
[both exhale]

438
00:20:30,375 --> 00:20:32,083
Let's see. What would Larry say?

439
00:20:39,791 --> 00:20:40,625
Okay.

440
00:20:42,750 --> 00:20:46,458
Okay, I'm remembering something
that's really important to me.

441
00:20:51,375 --> 00:20:52,625
I can see him.

442
00:20:59,083 --> 00:21:02,250
[voice breaking] I can-- I can hear him.
I can talk through it.

443
00:21:02,750 --> 00:21:04,666
[gasps, sniffles]

444
00:21:06,416 --> 00:21:08,166
Truffle parmesan fries.

445
00:21:13,458 --> 00:21:14,625
[sighs]

446
00:21:15,791 --> 00:21:17,165
[sniffles]

447
00:21:17,166 --> 00:21:20,207
Brussels sprouts
with balsamic honey glaze and bacon.

448
00:21:20,208 --> 00:21:21,625
Twelve dollars.

449
00:21:25,083 --> 00:21:27,666
[laughter crumbles into sobs]

450
00:21:28,958 --> 00:21:29,790
[sniffles]

451
00:21:29,791 --> 00:21:33,416
A wedge of iceberg lettuce
and shrimp cocktail.

452
00:21:40,708 --> 00:21:42,707
[sobbing continues]

453
00:21:42,708 --> 00:21:45,833
Calamari with lemon aioli sauce
is 15 dollars.

454
00:21:46,958 --> 00:21:48,875
[muffled weeping]

455
00:21:49,375 --> 00:21:51,207
[normal voice]
That's what method acting is.

456
00:21:51,208 --> 00:21:53,415
[both laughing]

457
00:21:53,416 --> 00:21:56,458
That's amazing. Oh, my God.

458
00:21:57,791 --> 00:22:01,374
No, my problem was I was not ambitious.

459
00:22:01,375 --> 00:22:05,958
It's such a hard business.
I wouldn't wish it on anybody.

460
00:22:06,875 --> 00:22:09,332
I keep thinking I might just stop.

461
00:22:09,333 --> 00:22:12,957
No, come on.
You've done all right, Jay Kelly.

462
00:22:12,958 --> 00:22:15,499
- [chuckles]
- I made two bad decisions.

463
00:22:15,500 --> 00:22:16,749
- Oh, yeah?
- Yeah.

464
00:22:16,750 --> 00:22:20,457
You know I passed on the original <i>90210?</i>
I was doing <i>Hamlet</i> in Louisville.

465
00:22:20,458 --> 00:22:23,833
Ah, that's cool.
I haven't done a play in...

466
00:22:25,041 --> 00:22:28,416
oh, since high school.
What was the other one?

467
00:22:30,041 --> 00:22:31,875
I let you come to that audition.

468
00:22:35,958 --> 00:22:40,125
But my boys got to see me waiting
outside the school gates every day.

469
00:22:40,750 --> 00:22:42,624
I gotta think that counts for something.

470
00:22:42,625 --> 00:22:45,416
For sure it does.
It counts for everything. Everything.

471
00:22:48,208 --> 00:22:51,290
Hey, I'm sorry.
I read about your divorces,

472
00:22:51,291 --> 00:22:54,082
and your girls, they must be
full-grown people by now.

473
00:22:54,083 --> 00:22:56,165
Daisy starts school in the fall.

474
00:22:56,166 --> 00:22:58,457
Thankfully, she doesn't
give a shit about acting.

475
00:22:58,458 --> 00:23:01,375
But... I'm freaking out, I...

476
00:23:03,166 --> 00:23:05,332
Thinking about her leaving.

477
00:23:05,333 --> 00:23:07,124
I feel like I missed it.

478
00:23:07,125 --> 00:23:08,125
Hey...

479
00:23:09,041 --> 00:23:10,624
Tragedy of parenting.

480
00:23:10,625 --> 00:23:14,458
We are only successful
once we've made ourselves irrelevant.

481
00:23:15,416 --> 00:23:17,624
- That's so sad.
- Come on.

482
00:23:17,625 --> 00:23:21,416
You've made the right choices for you.

483
00:23:22,583 --> 00:23:25,165
You make movies, man.
That's what the world wants from you.

484
00:23:25,166 --> 00:23:27,124
My world is much smaller.

485
00:23:27,125 --> 00:23:31,000
I take the dogs to the park.
Being with my family and my patients.

486
00:23:38,125 --> 00:23:39,458
Nice to see you, Tim.

487
00:23:41,208 --> 00:23:43,416
And it's nice to talk about those times.

488
00:23:46,875 --> 00:23:50,375
Nice to be in touch with you and with...

489
00:23:52,791 --> 00:23:54,291
also that guy.

490
00:23:55,041 --> 00:23:56,375
Guy I was.

491
00:23:59,958 --> 00:24:01,208
Is it?

492
00:24:03,333 --> 00:24:04,583
Uh, yeah.

493
00:24:05,166 --> 00:24:06,875
I don't think you want
to meet that guy again.

494
00:24:08,750 --> 00:24:09,583
What?

495
00:24:12,916 --> 00:24:15,250
I'm gonna be honest with you.
I can't stand you.

496
00:24:16,916 --> 00:24:18,958
You kind of stole my life.

497
00:24:20,541 --> 00:24:22,166
I didn't steal anything from you.

498
00:24:23,250 --> 00:24:26,500
Really? You stole my job.
And you stole my girlfriend.

499
00:24:27,083 --> 00:24:29,208
At 23, I didn't have much more than that.

500
00:24:29,708 --> 00:24:33,124
And now, every time I pick up a magazine,
I'm forced to read about Jay Kelly

501
00:24:33,125 --> 00:24:35,832
and his amazing origin story.

502
00:24:35,833 --> 00:24:39,707
How he accompanied his friend
to an audition for Peter Schneider,

503
00:24:39,708 --> 00:24:42,374
only he got the part. Imagine that.

504
00:24:42,375 --> 00:24:46,790
But they never wonder about the friend.
The guy he took it from.

505
00:24:46,791 --> 00:24:48,582
I got Peter to cast you.

506
00:24:48,583 --> 00:24:50,624
I was a glorified extra.

507
00:24:50,625 --> 00:24:52,415
- I had one line.
- I gotta go.

508
00:24:52,416 --> 00:24:54,499
- If people knew what I do about you...
- I gotta get up early.

509
00:24:54,500 --> 00:24:56,832
- I'll get the bill.
- I got it already.

510
00:24:56,833 --> 00:24:59,791
- Hey, can you sign this for me?
- Oh, yeah, sorry.

511
00:25:01,541 --> 00:25:04,958
Hey, don't worry.
I'm not gonna tell people.

512
00:25:06,333 --> 00:25:07,665
I'm not that kind of guy.

513
00:25:07,666 --> 00:25:10,582
You know, I don't actually know
what kind of a guy you are.

514
00:25:10,583 --> 00:25:12,374
You're not that important to me.

515
00:25:12,375 --> 00:25:15,749
You're important to other people
en masse maybe, but not to me.

516
00:25:15,750 --> 00:25:18,833
Sorry you feel that way.
I always had fond thoughts of you.

517
00:25:22,125 --> 00:25:23,083
[sighs]

518
00:25:24,416 --> 00:25:27,375
I'm not the only one who feels this.
Your daughter agrees with me.

519
00:25:27,875 --> 00:25:28,791
Daisy?

520
00:25:30,583 --> 00:25:31,416
Jessica.

521
00:25:32,083 --> 00:25:33,082
We're Facebook friends.

522
00:25:33,083 --> 00:25:35,165
I recommended the therapist
for her in San Diego.

523
00:25:35,166 --> 00:25:37,415
That guy's a charl--
Don't talk to Jessica.

524
00:25:37,416 --> 00:25:39,082
You're gonna tell me
who to be friends with?

525
00:25:39,083 --> 00:25:40,582
I'm not gonna tell you
who to be friends with.

526
00:25:40,583 --> 00:25:41,875
She calls you an empty vessel.

527
00:25:45,333 --> 00:25:46,458
Maybe she's right.

528
00:25:57,333 --> 00:25:58,916
Is there a person in there?

529
00:26:01,125 --> 00:26:02,458
Maybe you...

530
00:26:03,625 --> 00:26:05,458
don't actually exist.

531
00:26:07,625 --> 00:26:08,458
[tires squeak]

532
00:26:09,000 --> 00:26:11,041
My car's here. Let's just leave it.

533
00:26:14,416 --> 00:26:15,750
[exhales]

534
00:26:16,416 --> 00:26:18,125
I've always had this fantasy
of hitting you.

535
00:26:19,541 --> 00:26:21,583
[ragged laughter]

536
00:26:24,625 --> 00:26:26,540
I should have done this years ago.

537
00:26:26,541 --> 00:26:27,458
[Jay grunts]

538
00:26:29,875 --> 00:26:30,791
Oh!

539
00:26:34,875 --> 00:26:35,708
[Tim] Come on.

540
00:26:37,083 --> 00:26:38,166
Come on.

541
00:26:40,541 --> 00:26:42,499
You were never gonna get that part.

542
00:26:42,500 --> 00:26:43,624
Never. [growls]

543
00:26:43,625 --> 00:26:44,916
[racket hits tennis ball]

544
00:26:45,500 --> 00:26:47,041
You got this, puppy.

545
00:26:47,750 --> 00:26:50,207
I know. I'm just getting
that feeling I feel.

546
00:26:50,208 --> 00:26:52,458
That's fine. Now say goodbye to that.

547
00:26:53,083 --> 00:26:54,249
I'm trying.

548
00:26:54,250 --> 00:26:55,958
[ringtone chiming]

549
00:26:59,916 --> 00:27:04,041
Sorry, Liz, can Ron call you back?
Vivienne's serving for the match.

550
00:27:04,666 --> 00:27:05,999
- [shouts] Out.
- I know.

551
00:27:06,000 --> 00:27:08,999
- I'm just saying it's out.
- But Michelle, it's the way you said it.

552
00:27:09,000 --> 00:27:10,874
- He can call you after the match.
- [Vivienne] Sorry, Dad.

553
00:27:10,875 --> 00:27:13,374
- I heard Mom and I got distracted.
- I did too. I understand.

554
00:27:13,375 --> 00:27:15,707
Sweetheart, you can't talk
while we're playing.

555
00:27:15,708 --> 00:27:18,124
I know. I'm sorry. Liz says it's urgent.

556
00:27:18,125 --> 00:27:19,833
Dad, do you know about ghosts?

557
00:27:21,041 --> 00:27:24,415
Hold on, Vivienne gets a do-over
because she was distracted.

558
00:27:24,416 --> 00:27:26,374
- Dad, I don't want a do-over.
- [Mom] Ron.

559
00:27:26,375 --> 00:27:27,665
What rules are you playing by?

560
00:27:27,666 --> 00:27:30,332
Gordon, this isn't the French Open.
Give the girl another serve.

561
00:27:30,333 --> 00:27:34,249
I give Vivienne another serve,
then why not give Michelle another serve?

562
00:27:34,250 --> 00:27:37,207
Hell, I'd like another serve too,
while we're at it. Let chaos reign.

563
00:27:37,208 --> 00:27:38,290
- [Mom] Ron.
- I don't want another serve.

564
00:27:38,291 --> 00:27:41,375
It's not another because
that one shouldn't have happened.

565
00:27:42,541 --> 00:27:44,208
Uh... Right.

566
00:27:44,916 --> 00:27:46,499
- Yes?
- [Liz] <i>You don't pick up your phone?</i>

567
00:27:46,500 --> 00:27:49,207
- We're serving for the match.
<i>- We need you now, Ron.</i>

568
00:27:49,208 --> 00:27:50,832
- Dad.
- I can't come now.

569
00:27:50,833 --> 00:27:52,499
- We're in the middle of a game.
<i>- It's Jay.</i>

570
00:27:52,500 --> 00:27:55,165
- [child] Dad.
- Jay knows I have this tournament.

571
00:27:55,166 --> 00:27:58,165
Jay's dropping out of the movie
that he starts in a week.

572
00:27:58,166 --> 00:27:59,249
The Louis Brothers movie?

573
00:27:59,250 --> 00:28:01,915
- Dad.
- David, don't put your mouth on the fence.

574
00:28:01,916 --> 00:28:03,957
I like the taste of it.

575
00:28:03,958 --> 00:28:07,249
He's not dropping out. This is Jay when
he wraps a movie. He always does this.

576
00:28:07,250 --> 00:28:09,874
Believe me, Ron. It's bad.

577
00:28:09,875 --> 00:28:11,290
It's really, really bad.

578
00:28:11,291 --> 00:28:12,791
[Gordon] Ron.

579
00:28:13,375 --> 00:28:14,999
- Today.
- He got a work call.

580
00:28:15,000 --> 00:28:16,291
[David] Dad.

581
00:28:17,041 --> 00:28:17,916
Dad.

582
00:28:19,375 --> 00:28:20,458
[Vivienne] Dad.

583
00:28:23,291 --> 00:28:25,415
Fine, I'm coming.

584
00:28:25,416 --> 00:28:28,582
- Do you know about ghosts, Dad?
- I do, David.

585
00:28:28,583 --> 00:28:33,040
Ghosts are the spirits of dead people
who come back to Earth

586
00:28:33,041 --> 00:28:35,749
- if they have unfinished business.
- [Michelle] Ad out. It's our serve.

587
00:28:35,750 --> 00:28:38,582
So change in plans.
We got to suspend the game.

588
00:28:38,583 --> 00:28:40,207
- Suspend the game?
- No. No way, Ron.

589
00:28:40,208 --> 00:28:41,665
Something's come up. I have to go.

590
00:28:41,666 --> 00:28:43,040
- Where?
- To Jay's.

591
00:28:43,041 --> 00:28:44,790
You suspend, you forfeit.

592
00:28:44,791 --> 00:28:47,540
- Says who, Gordon?
- The tournament rules.

593
00:28:47,541 --> 00:28:49,832
- What if it was raining?
- It's not raining, Ron.

594
00:28:49,833 --> 00:28:51,291
- It's not raining, Dad.
- Ron.

595
00:28:52,666 --> 00:28:55,040
I feel good. We can win.

596
00:28:55,041 --> 00:28:57,083
I know. I have to go.

597
00:29:03,041 --> 00:29:05,041
[upbeat orchestral music playing]

598
00:29:09,750 --> 00:29:11,166
They're waiting for you.

599
00:29:11,791 --> 00:29:13,375
Thank God.

600
00:29:14,250 --> 00:29:15,457
- What happened yesterday?
- [Ron] Nothing.

601
00:29:15,458 --> 00:29:18,707
We went to Peter's memorial.
He bumped into an old friend.

602
00:29:18,708 --> 00:29:20,915
- They went out for drinks.
- Something happened.

603
00:29:20,916 --> 00:29:22,249
If he pulls out, he'll be in breach.

604
00:29:22,250 --> 00:29:24,207
You're not making
quesadillas by any chance?

605
00:29:24,208 --> 00:29:25,625
[chef] I... I can.

606
00:29:26,458 --> 00:29:28,165
- Where's Jay?
- [Meg] In his bedroom.

607
00:29:28,166 --> 00:29:31,124
- He is packing.
- Packing for what?

608
00:29:31,125 --> 00:29:32,665
I don't know.

609
00:29:32,666 --> 00:29:34,249
Quitting would be financially devastating.

610
00:29:34,250 --> 00:29:36,207
Devastating on a reputation level.

611
00:29:36,208 --> 00:29:37,957
His box office is not what it was.

612
00:29:37,958 --> 00:29:39,999
- Nobody's is.
- He's not 25 anymore.

613
00:29:40,000 --> 00:29:42,582
- He's not 55 anymore.
- Okay, now the studio's calling.

614
00:29:42,583 --> 00:29:44,415
You done? Everybody done?

615
00:29:44,416 --> 00:29:46,832
No one's in breach. Jay's doing the movie.

616
00:29:46,833 --> 00:29:49,207
- That's not what he's saying.
- Well, now I'm here.

617
00:29:49,208 --> 00:29:52,165
Well, then find out
why he has a black eye.

618
00:29:52,166 --> 00:29:53,916
- He has a black eye?
- [music ends abruptly]

619
00:29:55,208 --> 00:29:56,625
Jay?

620
00:30:01,166 --> 00:30:03,124
- Hey, brother.
- Hey, puppy.

621
00:30:03,125 --> 00:30:05,665
- What's the packing?
- You just come from the game?

622
00:30:05,666 --> 00:30:06,874
How'd you and Vivienne do?

623
00:30:06,875 --> 00:30:10,415
- Well, we were up 5-4 and serving...
- I do too many movies.

624
00:30:10,416 --> 00:30:13,249
- ...but it's fine. What's the packing?
- You think I do too many movies?

625
00:30:13,250 --> 00:30:14,832
I think you do just the right amount.

626
00:30:14,833 --> 00:30:17,457
- You think I do too many movies?
- You do work a lot.

627
00:30:17,458 --> 00:30:18,999
See? Barbara tells me the truth.

628
00:30:19,000 --> 00:30:22,708
- What happened last night?
- You can't have too much underwear. Hup!

629
00:30:23,833 --> 00:30:25,790
- How'd you get the black eye?
- I'll tell you on the plane.

630
00:30:25,791 --> 00:30:26,957
What plane?

631
00:30:26,958 --> 00:30:29,374
The plane that I booked.
We're leaving in 1.

632
00:30:29,375 --> 00:30:31,124
- Where are we going?
- Meg, where are we going?

633
00:30:31,125 --> 00:30:32,957
- France.
- France.

634
00:30:32,958 --> 00:30:33,999
France?

635
00:30:34,000 --> 00:30:36,415
[Meg] I spoke
to Daisy's friend Rio's mom, Claire,

636
00:30:36,416 --> 00:30:39,874
Rio uses her mom's credit card
so Claire can see the charges online.

637
00:30:39,875 --> 00:30:41,165
[Jay] Of course she can.

638
00:30:41,166 --> 00:30:42,874
Daisy and her friends
are currently in Paris

639
00:30:42,875 --> 00:30:45,749
and due to leave for Italy
after the jazz festival on Tuesday.

640
00:30:45,750 --> 00:30:48,707
Right. You kids and your computers.
France.

641
00:30:48,708 --> 00:30:51,874
- We have a fitting on Monday.
- Not if we're in Paris, we don't.

642
00:30:51,875 --> 00:30:54,790
Both Louis brothers are gonna be there.
Marvin and Yusuf.

643
00:30:54,791 --> 00:30:58,415
If you need a couple days
to clear your head, I'll tell the studio--

644
00:30:58,416 --> 00:31:01,332
Tell them that I'm joining Daisy
and her friends

645
00:31:01,333 --> 00:31:05,665
at a jazz festival in Paris,
and then we are catching a train to Italy.

646
00:31:05,666 --> 00:31:10,457
And you're tracking her
through her friend's mother's credit card.

647
00:31:10,458 --> 00:31:15,040
It's my last chance to spend time with her
before she's gone forever.

648
00:31:15,041 --> 00:31:18,040
I'm fairly certain Daisy doesn't want you

649
00:31:18,041 --> 00:31:20,582
following her around Europe
with your entourage.

650
00:31:20,583 --> 00:31:24,749
I am the Dior ambassador,
so there's every reason to be in Paris.

651
00:31:24,750 --> 00:31:28,040
And then I'm receiving that tribute
in Tuscany.

652
00:31:28,041 --> 00:31:29,957
I said no to the tribute. You said no.

653
00:31:29,958 --> 00:31:31,957
- I told them never.
- Call and tell them yes.

654
00:31:31,958 --> 00:31:34,708
Listen, take a few days,

655
00:31:35,583 --> 00:31:36,957
drive up the coast,

656
00:31:36,958 --> 00:31:39,874
order that pinot
you liked at the Post Ranch.

657
00:31:39,875 --> 00:31:41,708
Remember the towels?

658
00:31:42,250 --> 00:31:44,291
[both laugh]

659
00:31:45,541 --> 00:31:47,208
What did that even mean?

660
00:31:47,916 --> 00:31:50,207
[Jay] I do-- [sighs]

661
00:31:50,208 --> 00:31:53,749
- How about I push the fitting to Tuesday?
- Listen.

662
00:31:53,750 --> 00:31:56,082
If you don't want to come, I'll go alone.

663
00:31:56,083 --> 00:31:59,124
You, on your own, wandering through Europe

664
00:31:59,125 --> 00:32:02,165
is like a little gazelle
alone in the Serengeti.

665
00:32:02,166 --> 00:32:05,332
But not a gazelle. A cocker spaniel.

666
00:32:05,333 --> 00:32:09,333
Well, this cocker spaniel
will take his chances.

667
00:32:09,916 --> 00:32:11,916
[determined music playing]

668
00:32:27,833 --> 00:32:31,040
Today, Daisy and her friends
were at the Louvre, Café de Flore,

669
00:32:31,041 --> 00:32:33,624
a flea market, and they're staying
at a youth hostel in the 11th.

670
00:32:33,625 --> 00:32:34,999
Now we're cooking.

671
00:32:35,000 --> 00:32:37,499
After we land,
we can surprise her at the jazz festival.

672
00:32:37,500 --> 00:32:38,582
Perfect.

673
00:32:38,583 --> 00:32:41,540
What do you mean, they're giving
the tribute to someone else?

674
00:32:41,541 --> 00:32:44,332
Some history.
When Jay passed on the tribute,

675
00:32:44,333 --> 00:32:46,415
I got them to offer it to Ben Alcock.

676
00:32:46,416 --> 00:32:48,749
You gave Jay's tribute
to another one of your clients?

677
00:32:48,750 --> 00:32:53,040
Somebody had to take it, and it's a good
piece of architecture for Ben.

678
00:32:53,041 --> 00:32:55,165
Fuck a duck. Does Jay know about this?

679
00:32:55,166 --> 00:32:57,707
I spoke to Antonio.
They're gonna do two tributes.

680
00:32:57,708 --> 00:32:59,582
But currently, there's only one trophy.

681
00:32:59,583 --> 00:33:03,207
I'm missing, like, three junkets,
a <i>Vanity Fair</i> cover shoot

682
00:33:03,208 --> 00:33:04,957
and Justin's little league whatever

683
00:33:04,958 --> 00:33:07,290
- for this cluster fuck.
- I know. But it's Jay.

684
00:33:07,291 --> 00:33:10,332
- Why does he have a black eye, Ron?
- We're getting to that.

685
00:33:10,333 --> 00:33:13,082
Uh-huh.
This is why I could never marry you.

686
00:33:13,083 --> 00:33:14,665
Why, because I'm loyal?

687
00:33:14,666 --> 00:33:17,665
[scoffs] No. Because you enable.

688
00:33:17,666 --> 00:33:20,707
[out of tune]
<i>♪ We're on the road to Paris ♪</i>

689
00:33:20,708 --> 00:33:22,874
Oh, man, now we have
to listen to him play the piano.

690
00:33:22,875 --> 00:33:24,874
<i>♪ We're going to Paris by plane ♪</i>

691
00:33:24,875 --> 00:33:26,124
Sing it, Ronnie!

692
00:33:26,125 --> 00:33:29,457
- [clunky piano continues]
<i>- ♪ An adventure to the place ♪</i>

693
00:33:29,458 --> 00:33:30,832
<i>♪ Where... ♪</i>

694
00:33:30,833 --> 00:33:33,166
- I don't know the words.
- Come on, Ronnie.

695
00:33:36,250 --> 00:33:39,707
Justin's on the B team. It's so sad.

696
00:33:39,708 --> 00:33:43,207
You guys, he doesn't know where to run.
It's so sad.

697
00:33:43,208 --> 00:33:44,999
Look. [groans]

698
00:33:45,000 --> 00:33:47,083
He's really bad at baseball.

699
00:33:48,916 --> 00:33:51,666
- Should I take a half or a whole?
- What's the dosage?

700
00:33:52,958 --> 00:33:55,957
- You forget your glasses?
- I left in a hurry.

701
00:33:55,958 --> 00:33:58,374
Can't say goodbye to David
or he has a meltdown.

702
00:33:58,375 --> 00:34:00,749
The therapist said
I should say goodbye anyway

703
00:34:00,750 --> 00:34:01,832
so he knows I'm leaving.

704
00:34:01,833 --> 00:34:03,832
- He'll be okay. He's five.
- They block it.

705
00:34:03,833 --> 00:34:06,832
He's five, but I probably
should have said goodbye.

706
00:34:06,833 --> 00:34:09,957
Take a whole. Otherwise, you'll stress out
and end up waking me up.

707
00:34:09,958 --> 00:34:11,915
So, what this man
on the podcast was saying

708
00:34:11,916 --> 00:34:14,249
is that we're always, always every age.

709
00:34:14,250 --> 00:34:16,582
- Like, literally?
- Well, I don't know literally.

710
00:34:16,583 --> 00:34:18,124
Yeah, I'll take a whole.

711
00:34:18,125 --> 00:34:21,499
[Candy] So when I'm 10,
I'm also 30, and also 80.

712
00:34:21,500 --> 00:34:22,832
And vice versa.

713
00:34:22,833 --> 00:34:24,916
Why do you have a black eye, puppy?

714
00:34:25,666 --> 00:34:27,124
I'll tell you when we get to France.

715
00:34:27,125 --> 00:34:29,541
But it's nothing
I need to know now, right?

716
00:34:30,458 --> 00:34:32,749
Are you running
to something or from something?

717
00:34:32,750 --> 00:34:35,249
- Yes.
- [Krista] When I remember kindergarten,

718
00:34:35,250 --> 00:34:37,249
I'm my age now, right?

719
00:34:37,250 --> 00:34:39,333
How would I know
how you remember yourself?

720
00:34:40,041 --> 00:34:42,166
[male voice] <i>What does it feel like
to be famous?</i>

721
00:34:45,125 --> 00:34:47,750
<i>It doesn't feel like anything,
as far as I know.</i>

722
00:34:49,875 --> 00:34:55,750
You talk about fame and success,
and this sunlit life and happiness.

723
00:34:57,708 --> 00:35:00,875
You talk about me
as if I'm some kind of a king.

724
00:35:03,416 --> 00:35:08,040
But your words are just...
sweetness that disappears in your mouth--

725
00:35:08,041 --> 00:35:09,750
[tutor] Okay, Jay, can you stop there?

726
00:35:10,750 --> 00:35:12,375
What did you feel just then?

727
00:35:12,875 --> 00:35:15,750
[young Jay] I felt conceited. Successful.

728
00:35:16,416 --> 00:35:18,875
- A star.
- You want to be a star?

729
00:35:20,250 --> 00:35:21,083
I mean...

730
00:35:22,041 --> 00:35:23,499
Yeah, sure.

731
00:35:23,500 --> 00:35:25,583
[scattered chuckles]

732
00:35:26,333 --> 00:35:28,208
[tutor] Go on. What else?

733
00:35:28,708 --> 00:35:30,915
[young Jay]
Enjoying patronizing a young girl.

734
00:35:30,916 --> 00:35:32,083
Thinking I'm a king.

735
00:35:33,125 --> 00:35:35,708
Did that seem powerful, kingly, to you?

736
00:35:36,583 --> 00:35:38,041
[student] Looked like a lot of posturing.

737
00:35:41,208 --> 00:35:42,500
[tutor] How old are you, Jay?

738
00:35:43,000 --> 00:35:44,499
Twenty-three.

739
00:35:44,500 --> 00:35:48,165
[tutor] I'm not interested in seeing you
try to be a famous writer

740
00:35:48,166 --> 00:35:49,666
in pre-revolutionary Russia.

741
00:35:50,250 --> 00:35:53,540
I want to see the hungover kid
who just got off the bus from Kentucky...

742
00:35:53,541 --> 00:35:56,332
who's trying to impress
all the cute girls in the class.

743
00:35:56,333 --> 00:35:59,040
Basically, just be myself?

744
00:35:59,041 --> 00:36:01,415
Do you know how hard it is to be yourself?

745
00:36:01,416 --> 00:36:02,915
[young Jay] Uh-huh.

746
00:36:02,916 --> 00:36:04,790
[tutor] If you're lucky enough
to act professionally

747
00:36:04,791 --> 00:36:06,374
you'll be lying for a living.

748
00:36:06,375 --> 00:36:08,582
The better you lie,
the more truthful you'll seem,

749
00:36:08,583 --> 00:36:10,874
and the more successful you'll be.

750
00:36:10,875 --> 00:36:15,250
That's confusing shit for a young man
who doesn't tend towards introspection.

751
00:36:18,208 --> 00:36:20,082
You say you want to be a star.

752
00:36:20,083 --> 00:36:21,790
Well, I've known a few of those.

753
00:36:21,791 --> 00:36:24,625
- That's a whole other layer of headfuck.
- [students titter]

754
00:36:25,583 --> 00:36:27,458
[chuckles] Now you gotta act twice.

755
00:36:28,125 --> 00:36:32,041
Once when you play the part,
and then again when you play yourself.

756
00:36:34,875 --> 00:36:37,500
You have to really want that.

757
00:36:40,041 --> 00:36:41,458
- I do.
- [whispers] I do.

758
00:36:42,916 --> 00:36:44,999
- [tutor] Hey, Tim.
- Yeah?

759
00:36:45,000 --> 00:36:46,166
[tutor] Wanna have a go?

760
00:36:46,875 --> 00:36:48,125
Sure.

761
00:36:55,958 --> 00:36:57,791
[young Jay, whispering]
Show 'em how to do it.

762
00:37:04,625 --> 00:37:06,333
What does it feel like to be famous?

763
00:37:07,625 --> 00:37:09,750
I don't feel like anything,
as far as I know.

764
00:37:10,791 --> 00:37:15,624
You talk about fame and success,
and this sunlit life and happiness.

765
00:37:15,625 --> 00:37:18,540
You talk about me
as if I'm some kind of a king.

766
00:37:18,541 --> 00:37:20,915
But your words are like a sweetness

767
00:37:20,916 --> 00:37:22,749
that disappears
in your mouth in an instant.

768
00:37:22,750 --> 00:37:25,833
I see nothing especially lovely about it.

769
00:37:26,416 --> 00:37:28,332
I must go at once and begin writing again.

770
00:37:28,333 --> 00:37:30,582
- Tim's having a panic attack.
- Why?

771
00:37:30,583 --> 00:37:32,915
I have a huge audition
for Peter Schneider.

772
00:37:32,916 --> 00:37:35,457
- Dude, that's amazing.
- Tim hates auditions.

773
00:37:35,458 --> 00:37:38,207
- I am the worst auditioner.
- I've barely ever gotten an audition.

774
00:37:38,208 --> 00:37:40,332
- It's so not a test of talent.
- It's a test of something.

775
00:37:40,333 --> 00:37:42,374
Your talent will shine through.
It always does.

776
00:37:42,375 --> 00:37:43,916
Go with him, Jay.

777
00:37:44,708 --> 00:37:46,166
You're a calming influence.

778
00:37:46,875 --> 00:37:48,708
Come by the bar after. Free drinks.

779
00:37:49,958 --> 00:37:51,165
We will.

780
00:37:51,166 --> 00:37:53,250
[overlapping monologues]

781
00:37:54,375 --> 00:37:55,791
[door creaks open]

782
00:37:57,583 --> 00:37:59,582
[monologues trail off]

783
00:37:59,583 --> 00:38:01,666
[footsteps echo]

784
00:38:04,125 --> 00:38:05,125
[door clicks closed]

785
00:38:06,708 --> 00:38:08,207
[monologues resume]

786
00:38:08,208 --> 00:38:10,750
"I used to want to die.
I'd imagine my funeral."

787
00:38:11,416 --> 00:38:13,041
I think he's from the sticks.

788
00:38:13,625 --> 00:38:15,624
"All the pretty girls crying."

789
00:38:15,625 --> 00:38:17,707
Then he goes on about the sky
and the stars.

790
00:38:17,708 --> 00:38:21,916
He's too poetic for a hick kid.
He'd be more like...

791
00:38:22,708 --> 00:38:24,583
[drawling] "There are
too many girls I ain't laid.

792
00:38:25,083 --> 00:38:27,249
Dede Duffy, for one." [chuckles]

793
00:38:27,250 --> 00:38:28,375
I don't know, um...

794
00:38:28,958 --> 00:38:31,291
Shit like, "I might even grow more."

795
00:38:31,791 --> 00:38:33,749
"There's so many things
I ain't done yet, I don't--

796
00:38:33,750 --> 00:38:35,875
I don't have the vocabulary to list them."

797
00:38:36,375 --> 00:38:39,290
- That's better. You should say that.
- I can't mess with their script.

798
00:38:39,291 --> 00:38:40,874
You're gonna do great in there.

799
00:38:40,875 --> 00:38:43,166
I just get so fucking nervous
at these things.

800
00:38:44,166 --> 00:38:45,500
Well, look at this.

801
00:38:46,083 --> 00:38:48,624
{\an8}It's a sign. You're gonna
get this, buddy, I can feel it.

802
00:38:48,625 --> 00:38:49,708
Thanks, buddy.

803
00:38:52,708 --> 00:38:53,707
Eat it, for good luck.

804
00:38:53,708 --> 00:38:55,124
- What?
- Come on. Just a corner.

805
00:38:55,125 --> 00:38:58,124
- Harness his powers.
- Stop it, man. You're freaking me out.

806
00:38:58,125 --> 00:39:00,208
- [woman] Tim Galligan.
- Uh, yeah.

807
00:39:01,125 --> 00:39:02,583
Will you read with me?

808
00:39:03,458 --> 00:39:05,041
- Yeah.
- Thanks.

809
00:39:10,000 --> 00:39:11,499
- [Tim] Hi.
- Thank you.

810
00:39:11,500 --> 00:39:12,666
Thanks.

811
00:39:13,916 --> 00:39:16,749
- Uh, who are you here to read?
- [mouth full] To read with my friend.

812
00:39:16,750 --> 00:39:18,833
[swallows] If that's okay.

813
00:39:19,791 --> 00:39:20,791
Yeah.

814
00:39:21,458 --> 00:39:22,583
Thanks.

815
00:39:26,625 --> 00:39:29,041
- [woman] I'll get you some sides.
- Oh, thanks.

816
00:39:29,708 --> 00:39:31,541
- Here you go.
- Thank you.

817
00:39:36,916 --> 00:39:38,541
[exhales shakily]

818
00:39:40,333 --> 00:39:41,500
What's your beef, Tilly?

819
00:39:42,250 --> 00:39:45,874
- I ain't got no beef.
- Yeah? But you got that look.

820
00:39:45,875 --> 00:39:49,000
That line in your forehead
that goes from here to here.

821
00:39:49,958 --> 00:39:51,625
I used to want to die.

822
00:39:53,041 --> 00:39:54,875
I'd imagine my funeral.

823
00:39:55,375 --> 00:39:57,041
All the pretty girls crying.

824
00:39:58,750 --> 00:40:01,374
But I don't want to die, now.

825
00:40:01,375 --> 00:40:03,208
I haven't seen enough.

826
00:40:05,875 --> 00:40:09,000
I never really looked at these trees.
And the sky.

827
00:40:09,583 --> 00:40:11,750
- But now that--
- [casting director] Thank you very much.

828
00:40:12,250 --> 00:40:15,124
- There's more. I didn't finish.
- [casting director] It's fine. Thank you.

829
00:40:15,125 --> 00:40:18,208
Thank you, Timothy.
Thank you so much. Very nicely done.

830
00:40:22,208 --> 00:40:23,665
[door opens]

831
00:40:23,666 --> 00:40:25,125
Would it be cool if I read too?

832
00:40:25,708 --> 00:40:26,707
No, I'm sorry.

833
00:40:26,708 --> 00:40:30,041
- If you're not on the appointment sheet--
- Yes, sweetheart, that would be fine.

834
00:40:33,250 --> 00:40:34,583
I mean, if that's okay.

835
00:40:35,166 --> 00:40:36,541
Uh, yeah.

836
00:40:37,916 --> 00:40:38,750
[door closes]

837
00:40:45,416 --> 00:40:46,791
What's your beef, Tilly?

838
00:40:49,750 --> 00:40:52,916
- [drawls] I ain't got no beef.
- Yeah? You got that look.

839
00:40:53,583 --> 00:40:56,666
That line in your forehead
that goes from here to here.

840
00:40:57,416 --> 00:40:59,041
I used to want to die.

841
00:41:00,208 --> 00:41:01,666
I'd imagine my funeral.

842
00:41:03,750 --> 00:41:05,416
All the pretty girls crying.

843
00:41:08,541 --> 00:41:09,958
But I don't want to die now.

844
00:41:10,708 --> 00:41:12,250
I haven't seen enough.

845
00:41:15,500 --> 00:41:19,499
There's too many girls I ain't laid.
Dede Duffy, for one.

846
00:41:19,500 --> 00:41:21,415
Hell, I might even grow more.

847
00:41:21,416 --> 00:41:23,582
There's so many things I ain't done.

848
00:41:23,583 --> 00:41:26,083
I don't have the vocabulary to list them.

849
00:41:27,000 --> 00:41:31,333
And I've only been as far as Archer City.
But I... I don't need to see Paris,

850
00:41:31,875 --> 00:41:34,875
or Rome, or one of them places
they got kings.

851
00:41:35,375 --> 00:41:36,958
I'm the king here.

852
00:41:38,625 --> 00:41:40,915
I'm the king of this dust cloud.

853
00:41:40,916 --> 00:41:43,458
I'm-I'm the king of my Coca-Cola.

854
00:41:46,958 --> 00:41:48,791
I'm the king of Cranberry Street.

855
00:41:49,666 --> 00:41:50,875
[woman] Thank you.

856
00:41:55,458 --> 00:41:57,583
Would it trouble you
to read another scene?

857
00:41:58,083 --> 00:41:59,250
I'd love to.

858
00:42:00,083 --> 00:42:02,082
I'm sorry about changing the lines,
by the way--

859
00:42:02,083 --> 00:42:03,749
No, dear, we liked it very much.

860
00:42:03,750 --> 00:42:05,791
[poignant piano music playing]

861
00:42:07,375 --> 00:42:09,416
[dialogue fades to whispers]

862
00:42:09,916 --> 00:42:11,208
[casting director] Thank you.

863
00:42:13,291 --> 00:42:14,458
[Jay] Yeah, okay.

864
00:42:15,708 --> 00:42:17,916
[music continues]

865
00:42:23,791 --> 00:42:25,791
- [young Jay, faintly] No, let's just...
- [door closes]

866
00:42:27,625 --> 00:42:28,666
[Candy] Does that hurt?

867
00:42:29,166 --> 00:42:30,500
[Jay] No, it's okay.

868
00:42:31,083 --> 00:42:32,250
It's fine.

869
00:42:33,875 --> 00:42:35,291
[Candy] You'd never know.

870
00:42:36,166 --> 00:42:38,166
[music continues]

871
00:43:05,291 --> 00:43:07,249
[music fades]

872
00:43:07,250 --> 00:43:08,707
My father used to say,

873
00:43:08,708 --> 00:43:11,457
"The first person you meet
when you get off a plane is you."

874
00:43:11,458 --> 00:43:14,957
- Well, it should be the greeter.
- Remember the last time we were in Paris?

875
00:43:14,958 --> 00:43:18,207
The Chanel show? It was in silence
out of respect for the war.

876
00:43:18,208 --> 00:43:20,332
I remember Gucci, but that was very loud.

877
00:43:20,333 --> 00:43:21,499
Maybe it was for peace.

878
00:43:21,500 --> 00:43:23,832
Thank you so much, Antonio.

879
00:43:23,833 --> 00:43:26,540
- They're blowing a second trophy for Jay.
- Great.

880
00:43:26,541 --> 00:43:29,290
We arrived in Paris,
and we'll be heading your way tomorrow.

881
00:43:29,291 --> 00:43:30,582
[Meg] Just getting all my texts.

882
00:43:30,583 --> 00:43:34,249
According to Rio's mom, Daisy bought
tickets for a 10 o'clock train to Italy.

883
00:43:34,250 --> 00:43:36,541
- They're not doing the jazz thing?
- Apparently not.

884
00:43:37,041 --> 00:43:39,041
All right, better head
straight to the train.

885
00:43:39,833 --> 00:43:42,332
Flag on the play!
We're catching a train to Italy.

886
00:43:42,333 --> 00:43:43,499
- A train?
- Hold on.

887
00:43:43,500 --> 00:43:45,665
We're literally standing next to a plane.

888
00:43:45,666 --> 00:43:48,499
- Why did we fly to Paris then?
- [Ron] We're coming, but by train.

889
00:43:48,500 --> 00:43:49,457
[Candy] Oh, no.

890
00:43:49,458 --> 00:43:53,957
I booked a job for this afternoon.
I'm giving Emmanuel Macron a haircut.

891
00:43:53,958 --> 00:43:57,125
- Can you cancel?
- He's my first president.

892
00:43:57,625 --> 00:43:59,624
- Oh, my God. So, yeah...
- [Meg] 10 o'clock.

893
00:43:59,625 --> 00:44:00,999
We'll be on the 10 o'clock.

894
00:44:01,000 --> 00:44:04,332
Are you fucking kidding me?
I can't put Jay Kelly on a train.

895
00:44:04,333 --> 00:44:07,582
You're right, Antonio.
It's the most romantic way to travel.

896
00:44:07,583 --> 00:44:10,791
There should be some sort
of official car or something maybe.

897
00:44:11,708 --> 00:44:13,791
With a seal, or-- I think there's--

898
00:44:15,250 --> 00:44:17,250
[bright French accordion music playing]

899
00:44:41,625 --> 00:44:44,165
I'm an atheist
who supports the established church.

900
00:44:44,166 --> 00:44:46,999
I approve of everything about it but God.

901
00:44:47,000 --> 00:44:50,416
But if there were no God,
life would be absurd.

902
00:44:50,916 --> 00:44:51,916
Well, exactly.

903
00:44:53,125 --> 00:44:55,458
Fuck. Is that Jay Kelly?

904
00:44:56,625 --> 00:44:58,374
Thank you.
All right, <i>garçons,</i> that's great.

905
00:44:58,375 --> 00:45:00,040
If he signs one, it'll be a thousand.

906
00:45:00,041 --> 00:45:02,124
- Just get him on the train.
- You're going to have a trophy.

907
00:45:02,125 --> 00:45:04,915
- So you needn't worry.
- Was there ever not going to be a trophy?

908
00:45:04,916 --> 00:45:07,707
That's what I do. I fix things
so you don't have to know about them.

909
00:45:07,708 --> 00:45:09,582
If I don't have to know,
why are you telling me?

910
00:45:09,583 --> 00:45:13,832
Because we were late with the acceptance,
and they gave Ben Alcock the award.

911
00:45:13,833 --> 00:45:15,540
- There was only--
- You gave Ben my tribute?

912
00:45:15,541 --> 00:45:17,790
- You said no, puppy!
- Then I said yes.

913
00:45:17,791 --> 00:45:19,332
I would never say this to Ben.

914
00:45:19,333 --> 00:45:21,624
This stays in the cone,
but you're the first choice.

915
00:45:21,625 --> 00:45:23,874
You're the headliner.
You know that, puppy.

916
00:45:23,875 --> 00:45:26,040
I'm so confused talking to you right now.

917
00:45:26,041 --> 00:45:28,290
[Ron] I can't believe
I'm catching shit for this.

918
00:45:28,291 --> 00:45:30,375
Daisy! Hey!

919
00:45:31,375 --> 00:45:32,333
No.

920
00:45:32,916 --> 00:45:34,165
[young woman speaking French]

921
00:45:34,166 --> 00:45:36,124
No, no, no. <i>Ce n'est pas</i> Jay Kelly.

922
00:45:36,125 --> 00:45:38,124
- [young woman speaking French]
<i>- Excusez-moi.</i>

923
00:45:38,125 --> 00:45:40,915
Seat 48.
That doesn't sound like first class.

924
00:45:40,916 --> 00:45:42,040
It isn't.

925
00:45:42,041 --> 00:45:44,332
We're putting Jay Kelly in seat 48?

926
00:45:44,333 --> 00:45:46,249
You tell me.
There were no first class tickets.

927
00:45:46,250 --> 00:45:49,040
Maybe no first class at all.
I don't know. They all speak French here.

928
00:45:49,041 --> 00:45:51,582
We have Jay Kelly
the movie actor here with us.

929
00:45:51,583 --> 00:45:53,082
Do you have a private area?

930
00:45:53,083 --> 00:45:54,665
- [speaking French]
- But...

931
00:45:54,666 --> 00:45:56,249
[speaking French]

932
00:45:56,250 --> 00:45:59,457
[in English] Fifty days after Easter.
Very busy holiday for the French.

933
00:45:59,458 --> 00:46:02,790
I don't know who to be mad at, but
I'm finding myself being mad at you, Ron.

934
00:46:02,791 --> 00:46:04,874
Be mad at me, Liz.
The train was my idea.

935
00:46:04,875 --> 00:46:07,249
That's the problem.
I'm not allowed to be mad at you.

936
00:46:07,250 --> 00:46:09,457
According to Claire,
Rio got a chai latte

937
00:46:09,458 --> 00:46:12,457
at the Starbucks
at Gare de Lyon 45 minutes ago.

938
00:46:12,458 --> 00:46:14,415
You don't go
to a train station for coffee.

939
00:46:14,416 --> 00:46:15,832
I mean, it would be weird.

940
00:46:15,833 --> 00:46:17,916
[overlapping chatter]

941
00:46:21,625 --> 00:46:23,625
[nostalgic piano music playing]

942
00:47:01,333 --> 00:47:03,332
[various voices] Jay Kelly.

943
00:47:03,333 --> 00:47:05,249
Do you think he's fallen on hard times?

944
00:47:05,250 --> 00:47:06,874
It's research for a part.

945
00:47:06,875 --> 00:47:09,957
Sorry, speak louder. I'm on a French train
on a French holiday...

946
00:47:09,958 --> 00:47:11,832
I'll have him there Monday morning.

947
00:47:11,833 --> 00:47:13,832
I don't know, the <i>Fête</i> fucking <i>Nationale.</i>

948
00:47:13,833 --> 00:47:16,624
Well, then move the fitting
to the first day of the shoot.

949
00:47:16,625 --> 00:47:18,749
Wait, what? Say that last part again?

950
00:47:18,750 --> 00:47:22,207
Can you hear me?
It's 50 days from Easter here, I'm sorry.

951
00:47:22,208 --> 00:47:23,957
One more time. I want to get this right.

952
00:47:23,958 --> 00:47:26,999
We're playing three-dimensional--
four-dimensional chess here.

953
00:47:27,000 --> 00:47:29,665
- Are you fucking kidding me?
- I know that's not what Jay says.

954
00:47:29,666 --> 00:47:31,666
It's what I say. I'll get him back.

955
00:47:32,500 --> 00:47:33,707
It's bad.

956
00:47:33,708 --> 00:47:36,249
- Hold on. Let me get somewhere...
- Let me call you back.

957
00:47:36,250 --> 00:47:37,332
[Liz] Just put him through.

958
00:47:37,333 --> 00:47:39,999
[Scotswoman] I can't believe
he's actually on this train with us.

959
00:47:40,000 --> 00:47:42,207
- Are you real?
- I believe so. Yes.

960
00:47:42,208 --> 00:47:44,749
And will you be using
the same bathroom as us?

961
00:47:44,750 --> 00:47:46,499
I'll try to remember to put the seat down.

962
00:47:46,500 --> 00:47:47,999
- [laughter]
- Nice, regular guy.

963
00:47:48,000 --> 00:47:50,165
- He's a good egg.
- A real double-yolker.

964
00:47:50,166 --> 00:47:52,582
I read that that he's never
the seducer in his films.

965
00:47:52,583 --> 00:47:54,707
I'm sorry. There's so many people here.

966
00:47:54,708 --> 00:47:57,290
I haven't been on a train in 20 years.

967
00:47:57,291 --> 00:47:58,874
- Thirty, maybe.
- [Ron] A subway.

968
00:47:58,875 --> 00:48:00,874
I can't tell you the last time
I was on a subway.

969
00:48:00,875 --> 00:48:03,249
- Oh, the Kozak picture.
- Right, the chase scene.

970
00:48:03,250 --> 00:48:05,999
It was on a stage,
but the dimensions were very accurate.

971
00:48:06,000 --> 00:48:09,207
We saw you're being honored
at a prestigious Tuscan Arts Festival.

972
00:48:09,208 --> 00:48:10,957
Aren't you too young
to be having a tribute?

973
00:48:10,958 --> 00:48:13,749
You're very kind, but I don't know
how many more movies I have in me.

974
00:48:13,750 --> 00:48:16,040
- At least one more.
- I'd like to have a tribute in Italy.

975
00:48:16,041 --> 00:48:18,082
Clive, they don't give tributes
to computer programmers

976
00:48:18,083 --> 00:48:19,499
in Italy or anywhere.

977
00:48:19,500 --> 00:48:22,665
I expect you'll get all dressed up
and invite all your friends and family.

978
00:48:22,666 --> 00:48:24,707
That's what I'd do, anyway, so...

979
00:48:24,708 --> 00:48:27,415
Clive's right. It's your career.
Let's do it up.

980
00:48:27,416 --> 00:48:29,165
Invite your kids. Invite your dad.

981
00:48:29,166 --> 00:48:31,874
- My dad?
- Well, I know, but why not?

982
00:48:31,875 --> 00:48:33,916
My kids. I don't know about my dad.

983
00:48:34,416 --> 00:48:37,250
He's your dad.
He's not gonna be here forever.

984
00:48:38,583 --> 00:48:39,540
Okay.

985
00:48:39,541 --> 00:48:41,124
All right, but you call him.

986
00:48:41,125 --> 00:48:42,875
We can send him a plane if he wants.

987
00:48:43,375 --> 00:48:44,875
- Done.
- All right.

988
00:48:45,541 --> 00:48:46,750
Oh, my--

989
00:48:47,833 --> 00:48:51,749
When I look at you,
I see my whole life. [chortles]

990
00:48:51,750 --> 00:48:53,457
I talked to Rich at the studio.

991
00:48:53,458 --> 00:48:55,082
- They'll push the fitting.
- Alan called.

992
00:48:55,083 --> 00:48:56,875
[speaking Italian]

993
00:48:57,458 --> 00:48:58,708
[woman speaking Italian]

994
00:49:01,875 --> 00:49:03,832
[whispering] Jay was in a bar fight.

995
00:49:03,833 --> 00:49:06,040
He broke a child therapist's nose.

996
00:49:06,041 --> 00:49:08,165
- He broke a child what?
- Did you know this?

997
00:49:08,166 --> 00:49:09,540
Did he say anything about this?

998
00:49:09,541 --> 00:49:12,124
- [Jay] I wanted it very badly.
- No.

999
00:49:12,125 --> 00:49:13,249
Do you like being famous?

1000
00:49:13,250 --> 00:49:16,540
You must have such
a wonderful sunlit life. You're so happy.

1001
00:49:16,541 --> 00:49:18,832
I think it'd be terrible being famous.

1002
00:49:18,833 --> 00:49:20,999
Everyone looking at you,
talking about you.

1003
00:49:21,000 --> 00:49:22,832
- It's like being crazy, isn't it?
- Yes.

1004
00:49:22,833 --> 00:49:25,332
Clearly doesn't help with travel.
Packed in with us plebs.

1005
00:49:25,333 --> 00:49:26,583
[couple giggles]

1006
00:49:27,750 --> 00:49:30,290
So what do you all do?
Where are you all going?

1007
00:49:30,291 --> 00:49:32,707
Milan. [speaks Italian]

1008
00:49:32,708 --> 00:49:34,540
- [in English] Farm equipment.
- My father was in farm equipment.

1009
00:49:34,541 --> 00:49:36,957
I go to Pisa. [speaks Italian]
[in English] I'm a fireman.

1010
00:49:36,958 --> 00:49:38,915
- I played a fireman.
- [woman] Florence!

1011
00:49:38,916 --> 00:49:41,874
- [priest] We work in the Vatican.
- [passengers all calling out]

1012
00:49:41,875 --> 00:49:43,290
Explain what is happening.

1013
00:49:43,291 --> 00:49:45,999
My thoughts are formulating
in real time here, Liz.

1014
00:49:46,000 --> 00:49:49,124
- [woman 2] We're just on a girls' trip.
- [Scotswoman] We're going to get shagged!

1015
00:49:49,125 --> 00:49:50,915
[Clive] Computers. Wedding.

1016
00:49:50,916 --> 00:49:52,540
Life coach. Also wedding.

1017
00:49:52,541 --> 00:49:56,125
- Remember the last time we were in Paris?
- I don't want to talk about it.

1018
00:49:58,250 --> 00:49:59,500
'Cause we never did...

1019
00:50:01,166 --> 00:50:02,290
talk about it.

1020
00:50:02,291 --> 00:50:06,208
Twenty years ago,
I left you up the Eiffel Tower.

1021
00:50:07,041 --> 00:50:10,499
[Ron] Nineteen years ago.
I don't want to talk about it.

1022
00:50:10,500 --> 00:50:12,749
I looked you up. You're 60.

1023
00:50:12,750 --> 00:50:14,832
- Yes.
- You can't get old.

1024
00:50:14,833 --> 00:50:17,832
- If you're getting old, that means I am.
- I'll stop if you will.

1025
00:50:17,833 --> 00:50:19,416
- [passengers laugh]
- Deal!

1026
00:50:20,666 --> 00:50:23,749
- Do you want some peanuts?
- Sure, sure!

1027
00:50:23,750 --> 00:50:26,749
What do you say to people
who say you only play yourself?

1028
00:50:26,750 --> 00:50:29,041
Do you know
how difficult it is to be yourself?

1029
00:50:29,666 --> 00:50:30,541
You try it.

1030
00:50:34,041 --> 00:50:38,250
You know, I'm having a tribute
in Tuscany on Saturday.

1031
00:50:39,583 --> 00:50:42,249
And you all should come.
All of you. Yeah!

1032
00:50:42,250 --> 00:50:44,499
Yes, just talk
to my publicist Liz right there.

1033
00:50:44,500 --> 00:50:46,583
- [Clive] What time, Jay?
- Sorry.

1034
00:50:48,375 --> 00:50:50,040
[young woman] Do you have any regrets?

1035
00:50:50,041 --> 00:50:51,791
- What's your name?
- Phoebe.

1036
00:50:53,291 --> 00:50:54,666
You're a tough one, Phoebe.

1037
00:50:56,083 --> 00:50:58,124
I'll see you all in Tuscany!

1038
00:50:58,125 --> 00:51:00,208
[cheering]

1039
00:51:01,750 --> 00:51:04,458
<i>Arrivederci!</i> [laughs]

1040
00:51:05,625 --> 00:51:08,207
Everyone is so nice.
People are so nice.

1041
00:51:08,208 --> 00:51:10,832
By the way, these are the best peanuts
I've ever had. Try one.

1042
00:51:10,833 --> 00:51:12,790
It's a good peanut. A European peanut.

1043
00:51:12,791 --> 00:51:14,790
I didn't offer you one
because I know about your allergy.

1044
00:51:14,791 --> 00:51:17,165
That's right.
My throat will close, and I will die.

1045
00:51:17,166 --> 00:51:19,957
How can I play people
when I don't see people?

1046
00:51:19,958 --> 00:51:21,374
Don't touch people?

1047
00:51:21,375 --> 00:51:23,040
Don't touch people.

1048
00:51:23,041 --> 00:51:25,082
So, puppy,
you know those times you say,

1049
00:51:25,083 --> 00:51:27,541
"Don't tell me
unless I really need to know"?

1050
00:51:28,041 --> 00:51:29,165
This isn't one of those times...

1051
00:51:29,166 --> 00:51:32,458
Why didn't you tell us you punched
a child therapist in a bar fight?

1052
00:51:35,041 --> 00:51:37,707
- I didn't think he'd--
- Sue? He's suing.

1053
00:51:37,708 --> 00:51:39,165
I know it's difficult to be honest...

1054
00:51:39,166 --> 00:51:41,415
You have to tell us everything,
or we can't do our jobs.

1055
00:51:41,416 --> 00:51:43,249
...who love you no matter what.
More difficult.

1056
00:51:43,250 --> 00:51:45,040
- Why are you saying that?
- We do. We love him.

1057
00:51:45,041 --> 00:51:46,833
You love him. I work for him.

1058
00:51:47,333 --> 00:51:48,540
You know I adore you.

1059
00:51:48,541 --> 00:51:52,790
But when the press gets ahold of this,
we need a counter-narrative.

1060
00:51:52,791 --> 00:51:56,040
He hit you first?
Is that how you got the black eye?

1061
00:51:56,041 --> 00:51:59,999
'Cause "Jay Kelly defends himself from
crazed stalker" sounds a whole lot better

1062
00:52:00,000 --> 00:52:02,332
than "Jay Kelly beats up
defenseless child therapist."

1063
00:52:02,333 --> 00:52:04,957
- That's not what happened.
- Well, how would we know that?

1064
00:52:04,958 --> 00:52:07,082
If I've made my last movie,
I'm all right with that.

1065
00:52:07,083 --> 00:52:09,165
- I had a good run.
- [Ron] You don't mean that.

1066
00:52:09,166 --> 00:52:13,082
[Liz] You broke his nose.
They're claiming this, from Alan.

1067
00:52:13,083 --> 00:52:17,082
"Multiple fractures needing surgery, plus
permanent reduction in sense of smell..."

1068
00:52:17,083 --> 00:52:18,499
He says I stole his life.

1069
00:52:18,500 --> 00:52:22,957
"...and potential deformity, can result
in compensation up to $100,000,000."

1070
00:52:22,958 --> 00:52:24,082
[lock clicks]

1071
00:52:24,083 --> 00:52:25,458
[exhales]

1072
00:52:29,583 --> 00:52:31,291
[deep sigh]

1073
00:52:34,125 --> 00:52:36,125
[indistinct train announcement]

1074
00:52:40,666 --> 00:52:41,708
Jay Kelly.

1075
00:52:47,583 --> 00:52:49,875
Jay Kelly. Jay.

1076
00:52:50,958 --> 00:52:53,375
Jay Kelly.

1077
00:52:56,333 --> 00:52:57,166
Jay.

1078
00:53:01,916 --> 00:53:02,874
Kelly.

1079
00:53:02,875 --> 00:53:05,290
- [boy speaks French]
- Come on! Quickly! We're going to miss it!

1080
00:53:05,291 --> 00:53:07,249
- Hurry up!
- [friend] Daisy, I'm coming.

1081
00:53:07,250 --> 00:53:08,375
[Jay] Jay Kelly.

1082
00:53:09,791 --> 00:53:11,165
Jay Kelly.

1083
00:53:11,166 --> 00:53:12,625
Gary Cooper.

1084
00:53:14,916 --> 00:53:16,166
Cary Grant.

1085
00:53:17,291 --> 00:53:18,124
Jay Kelly.

1086
00:53:18,125 --> 00:53:19,040
[whistle sounds]

1087
00:53:19,041 --> 00:53:20,083
Clark Gable.

1088
00:53:21,750 --> 00:53:22,791
Jay Kelly.

1089
00:53:24,916 --> 00:53:25,875
Robert De Niro.

1090
00:53:26,500 --> 00:53:28,500
[train screeching into movement]

1091
00:53:29,333 --> 00:53:30,457
Jay Kelly.

1092
00:53:30,458 --> 00:53:32,374
[train picking up speed]

1093
00:53:32,375 --> 00:53:33,541
Jay Kelly.

1094
00:53:36,333 --> 00:53:38,083
[child chattering faintly]

1095
00:53:38,958 --> 00:53:42,125
[teacher] Bye, honey. Bye, Mommy,
see you. Have a good weekend.

1096
00:53:44,875 --> 00:53:47,625
I can't believe you drove here
from LA by yourself.

1097
00:53:48,125 --> 00:53:50,125
I wanted to see you in your life.

1098
00:53:50,791 --> 00:53:53,083
I've been in San Diego for almost a year.

1099
00:53:53,708 --> 00:53:56,040
Well, my last movie went long.

1100
00:53:56,041 --> 00:53:58,957
And then I had this vodka ad in Greece,

1101
00:53:58,958 --> 00:54:01,875
- so I'm lucky to have a weekend.
- I know you're busy.

1102
00:54:02,375 --> 00:54:05,416
I jumped in the truck
and I drove all the way down here.

1103
00:54:05,916 --> 00:54:07,416
So, can you, like--

1104
00:54:08,208 --> 00:54:11,832
At this point, can you just
go into a gas station alone?

1105
00:54:11,833 --> 00:54:16,249
Yeah, I do self-serve, and then
I just put a baseball cap over my eyes.

1106
00:54:16,250 --> 00:54:17,541
What about having to pee?

1107
00:54:18,041 --> 00:54:19,082
Side of the road.

1108
00:54:19,083 --> 00:54:20,457
God, Dad.

1109
00:54:20,458 --> 00:54:21,583
[Jay chuckles]

1110
00:54:23,208 --> 00:54:25,415
I love seeing you with those kids.

1111
00:54:25,416 --> 00:54:27,165
They adore you.

1112
00:54:27,166 --> 00:54:29,958
Well, I finally found
what I really want to do.

1113
00:54:30,916 --> 00:54:33,832
It took a minute, God knows.
You know, acting really fucked me up.

1114
00:54:33,833 --> 00:54:36,750
It's really insecure-making.
I don't know how you do it.

1115
00:54:37,333 --> 00:54:39,625
- I'm insecure.
- [humorless chuckle]

1116
00:54:40,833 --> 00:54:42,457
No, but you always had it.

1117
00:54:42,458 --> 00:54:44,540
Even when you were little,
and those shows you would do

1118
00:54:44,541 --> 00:54:46,415
in the backyard with your sister.

1119
00:54:46,416 --> 00:54:48,749
[announcing, half-heartedly]
"It's... Kelly and Kelly."

1120
00:54:48,750 --> 00:54:51,666
No, it was "Kelly and Kel-ly."

1121
00:54:55,291 --> 00:54:57,000
I'm just so happy for you.

1122
00:54:57,666 --> 00:54:59,790
Listen, if I could help out with the rent

1123
00:54:59,791 --> 00:55:02,000
- or support you--
- No, that's okay, Dad.

1124
00:55:03,125 --> 00:55:04,458
I'm glad you're here, though.

1125
00:55:05,541 --> 00:55:07,041
You wanna go for a drive?

1126
00:55:07,541 --> 00:55:09,332
It's Theo's birthday next week,
by the way.

1127
00:55:09,333 --> 00:55:10,416
No, I know.

1128
00:55:11,125 --> 00:55:12,583
You don't have to remind me.

1129
00:55:13,333 --> 00:55:15,249
Right, you have people
who do that for you.

1130
00:55:15,250 --> 00:55:17,082
No, I know it's the 24th.

1131
00:55:17,083 --> 00:55:19,749
I got him a pony
that's the actual size of a pony,

1132
00:55:19,750 --> 00:55:21,290
but it's stuffed.

1133
00:55:21,291 --> 00:55:22,791
Oh, he'll love that.

1134
00:55:24,208 --> 00:55:25,333
Where are we going?

1135
00:55:26,875 --> 00:55:28,957
- I've been seeing a therapist, and...
- Hm.

1136
00:55:28,958 --> 00:55:31,541
he's become a very important
part of my life.

1137
00:55:34,500 --> 00:55:37,708
I made an appointment
for both of us with Carter.

1138
00:55:39,375 --> 00:55:40,583
Carter's the--

1139
00:55:42,708 --> 00:55:43,666
[sighs]

1140
00:55:45,083 --> 00:55:48,875
I'm hungry. Why don't we stop, get a bite
and just talk, just the two of us?

1141
00:55:50,833 --> 00:55:52,333
This is why I didn't tell you.

1142
00:55:54,916 --> 00:55:56,750
Because I knew
you wouldn't want to do it.

1143
00:56:04,458 --> 00:56:06,250
This is very important to me.

1144
00:56:11,875 --> 00:56:13,375
[engine shuts off]

1145
00:56:15,208 --> 00:56:17,207
I'm sorry about the shades.

1146
00:56:17,208 --> 00:56:20,291
I have a retinal disorder.

1147
00:56:21,000 --> 00:56:24,124
So I'm very sensitive to bright light.

1148
00:56:24,125 --> 00:56:26,207
I tell him it makes him mysterious.

1149
00:56:26,208 --> 00:56:29,083
[chuckles] You should be the one
with the dark glasses.

1150
00:56:29,583 --> 00:56:31,875
- When it's sunny, yeah.
- [Carter chuckles]

1151
00:56:32,916 --> 00:56:34,625
[sighs]

1152
00:56:35,458 --> 00:56:36,291
Do you surf?

1153
00:56:37,583 --> 00:56:39,208
A little bit. I'm not very good.

1154
00:56:40,000 --> 00:56:41,457
I'm guessing that you do.

1155
00:56:41,458 --> 00:56:44,290
Mm. Every day, until I broke my femur.

1156
00:56:44,291 --> 00:56:46,750
- Then I got my psychology degree.
- I'm sorry.

1157
00:56:47,916 --> 00:56:50,457
But... I guess good?

1158
00:56:50,458 --> 00:56:52,415
Yeah, a door and a window, right?

1159
00:56:52,416 --> 00:56:54,958
- Yeah.
- Well, thank you for coming.

1160
00:56:56,333 --> 00:56:57,500
It's very brave.

1161
00:56:58,750 --> 00:56:59,582
Okay.

1162
00:56:59,583 --> 00:57:02,041
Jessie and I have been doing
a lot of work these past weeks.

1163
00:57:03,208 --> 00:57:06,082
And Jessie wrote you a letter.

1164
00:57:06,083 --> 00:57:07,791
It's from her ten-year-old self.

1165
00:57:09,583 --> 00:57:10,708
She'd like me to read it.

1166
00:57:11,916 --> 00:57:12,999
Why don't you read it?

1167
00:57:13,000 --> 00:57:15,124
Because I can't get
through it without sobbing,

1168
00:57:15,125 --> 00:57:17,415
so we decided that Carter should read it.

1169
00:57:17,416 --> 00:57:18,333
[Jay] Oh.

1170
00:57:19,291 --> 00:57:20,875
Okay, it's-- If you--

1171
00:57:21,375 --> 00:57:22,333
[Carter] "Dear Jay,

1172
00:57:24,458 --> 00:57:26,790
- When you abandoned me--"
- Hold on, I didn't abandon you.

1173
00:57:26,791 --> 00:57:29,332
- That's your mother talking.
- Try not to comment until I finish.

1174
00:57:29,333 --> 00:57:30,915
I left her. I didn't leave you.

1175
00:57:30,916 --> 00:57:32,915
- I was with her.
- Just because I wasn't there

1176
00:57:32,916 --> 00:57:34,915
doesn't mean I stopped being your father.

1177
00:57:34,916 --> 00:57:38,499
Jessie's told me a bit about
your relationship with your own father.

1178
00:57:38,500 --> 00:57:40,082
I'm not like my father.

1179
00:57:40,083 --> 00:57:45,165
My father's a rageful, bitter egomaniac.

1180
00:57:45,166 --> 00:57:48,166
Perhaps your determination
not to be like him

1181
00:57:48,666 --> 00:57:51,291
took precedence
over being a father yourself.

1182
00:57:53,541 --> 00:57:54,708
Keep reading.

1183
00:57:59,791 --> 00:58:02,000
"You say you always want to be with me.

1184
00:58:03,250 --> 00:58:05,875
But your actions
aren't speaking the way your words are.

1185
00:58:06,750 --> 00:58:09,040
My worst day
was when my babysitter rented

1186
00:58:09,041 --> 00:58:11,291
that movie you did with Daphne Spender.

1187
00:58:12,458 --> 00:58:14,375
She couldn't believe I had never seen it.

1188
00:58:15,208 --> 00:58:16,125
And in it...

1189
00:58:19,125 --> 00:58:20,875
you were this great father...

1190
00:58:22,708 --> 00:58:24,708
and you were so sweet
with the little boy...

1191
00:58:27,125 --> 00:58:28,333
and with Daphne.

1192
00:58:29,416 --> 00:58:31,083
[voice breaking] I cried and cried.

1193
00:58:34,500 --> 00:58:36,082
It was like you had a happy family."

1194
00:58:36,083 --> 00:58:37,915
Can't do it. Can't do it.

1195
00:58:37,916 --> 00:58:40,499
- [normal voice] I'm not finished.
- You're not gonna hear the whole letter?

1196
00:58:40,500 --> 00:58:42,499
Not if Carter reads it, no.

1197
00:58:42,500 --> 00:58:45,374
I knew that you would
find a way to make this about you.

1198
00:58:45,375 --> 00:58:47,707
- Carter said you would.
- Carter is crying in there.

1199
00:58:47,708 --> 00:58:49,582
I find it interesting
that you're not crying.

1200
00:58:49,583 --> 00:58:53,124
Tell him the best way
to make an audience cry is to not cry.

1201
00:58:53,125 --> 00:58:56,083
Do you know how I know that
you didn't want to spend time with me?

1202
00:58:59,875 --> 00:59:02,083
Because you didn't spend time with me.

1203
00:59:06,458 --> 00:59:08,458
[solemn music playing]

1204
00:59:12,000 --> 00:59:13,458
[doors slams]

1205
00:59:23,958 --> 00:59:25,915
[sunny music playing]

1206
00:59:25,916 --> 00:59:28,000
[passengers chattering]

1207
00:59:33,500 --> 00:59:35,041
She's in the cafe car.

1208
00:59:37,208 --> 00:59:39,999
Explain to me, Ron.
If he doesn't care, why should we?

1209
00:59:40,000 --> 00:59:43,499
Liz, of course he cares. This is just
how he's managing his feelings.

1210
00:59:43,500 --> 00:59:45,915
"They're so nice."
Of course they're nice.

1211
00:59:45,916 --> 00:59:49,040
You've walked off a movie screen.
You think they're like this with everyone?

1212
00:59:49,041 --> 00:59:50,582
They do seem like a nice group.

1213
00:59:50,583 --> 00:59:53,165
We're in second class
on a French train to nowhere,

1214
00:59:53,166 --> 00:59:54,540
taking care of an infant.

1215
00:59:54,541 --> 00:59:56,165
Worse, an infant who hit a guy.

1216
00:59:56,166 --> 00:59:58,332
We've known him for 30 years.

1217
00:59:58,333 --> 01:00:00,166
We clearly don't know Jay.

1218
01:00:00,666 --> 01:00:02,540
And who knows what else is out there?

1219
01:00:02,541 --> 01:00:04,665
Whatever hillbilly shit
he did in Kentucky.

1220
01:00:04,666 --> 01:00:06,416
It can spiral.

1221
01:00:07,000 --> 01:00:11,582
It was different when we were young.
It was fun. Jay was our baby.

1222
01:00:11,583 --> 01:00:15,165
- We're gonna handle this.
- Acting out at 60 is a bad look.

1223
01:00:15,166 --> 01:00:18,874
We're gonna get him to the tribute.
He's going to feel the love.

1224
01:00:18,875 --> 01:00:22,082
He's behaving like he's the first person
to ever have a nervous breakdown.

1225
01:00:22,083 --> 01:00:24,499
- Remember--
- We're all having nervous breakdowns, Ron.

1226
01:00:24,500 --> 01:00:25,624
- We've got grapes.
- Want some?

1227
01:00:25,625 --> 01:00:26,874
Banana?

1228
01:00:26,875 --> 01:00:29,708
Every single fucking second.

1229
01:00:31,458 --> 01:00:33,582
- That was actually quite rude.
- [group giggling]

1230
01:00:33,583 --> 01:00:34,791
Why, Ron?

1231
01:00:35,875 --> 01:00:37,624
Why should we be
chasing around an infant

1232
01:00:37,625 --> 01:00:41,499
when we have actual living kids at home
who are aging by the minute?

1233
01:00:41,500 --> 01:00:46,457
Because we are supporting a great artist
who shares with other human beings

1234
01:00:46,458 --> 01:00:48,207
what it is to be a human being.

1235
01:00:48,208 --> 01:00:49,916
We're human too, Ron.

1236
01:00:50,708 --> 01:00:53,124
- More so, maybe.
- It's not about us.

1237
01:00:53,125 --> 01:00:58,624
Our love isn't conditional. It's--
We're like parents or imaginary friends.

1238
01:00:58,625 --> 01:01:01,249
We vanish under cloak of night,
with no trace.

1239
01:01:01,250 --> 01:01:04,082
Maybe an elegant
business card that floats--

1240
01:01:04,083 --> 01:01:06,708
What the fuck are you talking about?

1241
01:01:08,083 --> 01:01:11,040
He's not our family or our friend.

1242
01:01:11,041 --> 01:01:13,707
He was just at Vivienne's sweet 16.

1243
01:01:13,708 --> 01:01:15,333
Were you at Daisy's graduation?

1244
01:01:15,916 --> 01:01:17,540
I think-- I think it was small.

1245
01:01:17,541 --> 01:01:21,374
You weren't invited,
because it only goes one way.

1246
01:01:21,375 --> 01:01:23,791
No one wants to say it, but it does.

1247
01:01:25,583 --> 01:01:27,833
We're not to him what he is to us.

1248
01:01:30,458 --> 01:01:31,625
I disagree.

1249
01:01:34,125 --> 01:01:36,125
[no audible dialogue]

1250
01:01:38,291 --> 01:01:40,291
[gentle music playing]

1251
01:02:04,666 --> 01:02:05,957
[music stops]

1252
01:02:05,958 --> 01:02:07,250
What's wrong?

1253
01:02:10,333 --> 01:02:13,165
Okay. My father is Jay Kelly.

1254
01:02:13,166 --> 01:02:15,041
[scoffs] Like the actor?

1255
01:02:15,541 --> 01:02:18,083
Yes, like the actor,
and also is the actor.

1256
01:02:18,833 --> 01:02:22,250
The reason I'm telling you is because
he's standing right in front of us.

1257
01:02:24,083 --> 01:02:24,915
Hey!

1258
01:02:24,916 --> 01:02:26,124
Hey.

1259
01:02:26,125 --> 01:02:28,624
[Jay chuckles awkwardly]

1260
01:02:28,625 --> 01:02:31,040
I guess we're on the same train.

1261
01:02:31,041 --> 01:02:32,833
Yeah, it's crazy, isn't it?

1262
01:02:33,666 --> 01:02:36,332
- It's weird, Dad.
- Well, I had to be in Paris

1263
01:02:36,333 --> 01:02:39,624
for a Dior campaign
and other bits and bobs,

1264
01:02:39,625 --> 01:02:41,958
and then I made this train...

1265
01:02:43,041 --> 01:02:46,083
for my tribute in Tuscany.
Hey, Rio.

1266
01:02:47,750 --> 01:02:48,750
So...

1267
01:02:50,125 --> 01:02:52,040
How was the jazz festival?

1268
01:02:52,041 --> 01:02:56,415
Well... we didn't go.
Guillaume says it's all fusion now.

1269
01:02:56,416 --> 01:02:57,874
<i>Bonjour.</i> Guillaume.

1270
01:02:57,875 --> 01:03:00,250
- Guigui.
- Guigui. I'm Jay. Hi.

1271
01:03:01,708 --> 01:03:06,415
Guillaume was our waiter at Café de Flore.
He's a singer and a filmmaker.

1272
01:03:06,416 --> 01:03:08,083
No, I'm not. That's--

1273
01:03:08,916 --> 01:03:11,457
It's embarrassing to say filmmaker to you.

1274
01:03:11,458 --> 01:03:13,000
- No, it isn't.
- No, it's not.

1275
01:03:14,875 --> 01:03:20,332
Daisy, how does it feel to have the hero
of so many brilliant films of our time

1276
01:03:20,333 --> 01:03:22,749
to be your father?

1277
01:03:22,750 --> 01:03:24,332
Yes, Daisy, how does that feel?

1278
01:03:24,333 --> 01:03:26,916
[laughs]
I think I know him too well to tell.

1279
01:03:27,791 --> 01:03:30,500
Jay Kelly is a hero of cinema.

1280
01:03:31,375 --> 01:03:32,250
I like this guy.

1281
01:03:33,041 --> 01:03:36,250
- [speaks French]
- [speaks French]

1282
01:03:40,250 --> 01:03:41,291
Wow.

1283
01:03:42,750 --> 01:03:43,916
What was I gonna tell you?

1284
01:03:46,583 --> 01:03:48,582
Anyway, listen, I don't want to intrude.

1285
01:03:48,583 --> 01:03:51,457
I just wanted to invite you all

1286
01:03:51,458 --> 01:03:53,749
to my tribute on Saturday.

1287
01:03:53,750 --> 01:03:57,041
I can totally get tickets
for all five of you.

1288
01:03:57,541 --> 01:04:00,124
Since when did you care
so much about a tribute?

1289
01:04:00,125 --> 01:04:01,665
I don't know. I think I care.

1290
01:04:01,666 --> 01:04:03,207
I'm inviting Dad.

1291
01:04:03,208 --> 01:04:05,457
- I think I'd make it a family thing.
- You invited Grandpa?

1292
01:04:05,458 --> 01:04:07,540
- Do you really want him there?
- I'd like him to come.

1293
01:04:07,541 --> 01:04:09,332
And I'm inviting Jessica too.

1294
01:04:09,333 --> 01:04:10,249
- Jessie?
- Yeah.

1295
01:04:10,250 --> 01:04:13,999
It's a little more complicated with her,
'cause you and I are in the same country.

1296
01:04:14,000 --> 01:04:15,540
On the same train.

1297
01:04:15,541 --> 01:04:17,207
[chuckles]

1298
01:04:17,208 --> 01:04:20,374
Let me get back to you about it, okay?
We're on kind of a tight schedule.

1299
01:04:20,375 --> 01:04:22,999
[Guigui] We're going
to this ancient horse race.

1300
01:04:23,000 --> 01:04:24,083
It's gonna be fun.

1301
01:04:26,958 --> 01:04:27,875
Uh...

1302
01:04:28,916 --> 01:04:30,666
So, um...

1303
01:04:31,208 --> 01:04:32,416
Paris was great?

1304
01:04:33,041 --> 01:04:35,291
- It was amazing.
- All right, so tell me everything.

1305
01:04:36,833 --> 01:04:39,958
We jumped off rocks
into pools in the woods.

1306
01:04:40,541 --> 01:04:42,665
We went to this crazy bar
that David Lynch designed,

1307
01:04:42,666 --> 01:04:43,708
and I ate a brain.

1308
01:04:44,291 --> 01:04:46,958
- [camera whirring]
- We went to Delacroix's house.

1309
01:04:47,458 --> 01:04:50,041
Do you know his paintings?
They're really, really amazing.

1310
01:04:52,000 --> 01:04:53,249
Dad, are you listening to me?

1311
01:04:53,250 --> 01:04:54,165
[camera stops]

1312
01:04:54,166 --> 01:04:56,915
I'm listening to you.
This is the look of me listening.

1313
01:04:56,916 --> 01:05:00,624
- You asked me about Paris.
- Start again, just two sentences back.

1314
01:05:00,625 --> 01:05:02,874
You're so ADD.
I'm gonna go get some snacks.

1315
01:05:02,875 --> 01:05:04,915
No, don't get snacks. No, stay, come on.

1316
01:05:04,916 --> 01:05:07,749
I'm sorry. It's strange.

1317
01:05:07,750 --> 01:05:09,875
It's great, but it's--

1318
01:05:10,375 --> 01:05:13,207
It's strange hearing
about your experiences

1319
01:05:13,208 --> 01:05:15,790
and seeing you so independent.

1320
01:05:15,791 --> 01:05:17,833
I'm sorry. Okay, so tell me...

1321
01:05:18,333 --> 01:05:20,875
- Uh, you ate a brain.
- I ate a brain.

1322
01:05:21,750 --> 01:05:24,832
And we danced with these tango kids
outside of the opera house.

1323
01:05:24,833 --> 01:05:27,875
And I think I want to act.

1324
01:05:29,541 --> 01:05:30,375
Wow.

1325
01:05:32,666 --> 01:05:33,832
All right.

1326
01:05:33,833 --> 01:05:37,790
After college, if it's still something
that you feel you want to do, then...

1327
01:05:37,791 --> 01:05:40,374
I think I might not want
to go to college right now.

1328
01:05:40,375 --> 01:05:43,499
Guigui's making a film in Sicily,
and he's asked me to be in it.

1329
01:05:43,500 --> 01:05:46,749
It's just a little thing
about memories and dreams.

1330
01:05:46,750 --> 01:05:48,249
You're going to college.

1331
01:05:48,250 --> 01:05:51,165
You worked incredibly hard,
and this is an amazing opportunity.

1332
01:05:51,166 --> 01:05:53,457
- One that I never had.
- I never even allowed myself

1333
01:05:53,458 --> 01:05:56,249
to think of being an actor because of you,
but I am good.

1334
01:05:56,250 --> 01:05:58,415
I know you always thought
Jessie was the talented one.

1335
01:05:58,416 --> 01:06:00,832
You're one of the most
brilliant people I've ever met.

1336
01:06:00,833 --> 01:06:03,582
- I just don't think you want that life.
- That is so hypocritical.

1337
01:06:03,583 --> 01:06:05,790
- Acting has been your whole life.
- I know how difficult it is,

1338
01:06:05,791 --> 01:06:08,165
and how much you miss,
and how crazy it makes you,

1339
01:06:08,166 --> 01:06:09,832
and how lonely it makes you.

1340
01:06:09,833 --> 01:06:10,916
You're never alone.

1341
01:06:11,500 --> 01:06:12,915
- Thanks, Silvano.
- You're welcome.

1342
01:06:12,916 --> 01:06:15,665
Just think about the tribute.

1343
01:06:15,666 --> 01:06:19,165
'Cause I can make it work
from the horse race or wherever you are.

1344
01:06:19,166 --> 01:06:21,249
I can send a car or a helicopter.

1345
01:06:21,250 --> 01:06:23,875
There's a jet picking up your grandpa.
Whatever you need.

1346
01:06:24,666 --> 01:06:26,625
How did you end up on this train, Dad?

1347
01:06:28,708 --> 01:06:29,708
Well--

1348
01:06:35,625 --> 01:06:36,708
I knew. I...

1349
01:06:41,166 --> 01:06:42,166
I...

1350
01:06:43,875 --> 01:06:46,332
I knew, because, uh,

1351
01:06:46,333 --> 01:06:48,957
Rio is using her mom's credit card.

1352
01:06:48,958 --> 01:06:51,374
Oh, my God. That is so fucked up.

1353
01:06:51,375 --> 01:06:53,457
Rio, your mother's tracking you
on your Amex.

1354
01:06:53,458 --> 01:06:54,541
Fuck.

1355
01:06:55,500 --> 01:06:58,082
- I wanted to surprise you.
- You stalked me to Europe.

1356
01:06:58,083 --> 01:07:01,040
I'm here because you can't just leave

1357
01:07:01,041 --> 01:07:03,540
and stop being a kid.

1358
01:07:03,541 --> 01:07:06,999
- I haven't spent enough time with you.
- It's you and all your people.

1359
01:07:07,000 --> 01:07:09,790
- Come on. I'm not that guy.
- No, you're totally that guy.

1360
01:07:09,791 --> 01:07:11,957
You can't say "helicopter"
and not be that guy.

1361
01:07:11,958 --> 01:07:13,749
I'm just trying to make it easy for you...

1362
01:07:13,750 --> 01:07:17,624
I don't want a helicopter or a jet.
I just want to be on a rickety train

1363
01:07:17,625 --> 01:07:19,499
and in a youth hostel and in a tent.

1364
01:07:19,500 --> 01:07:22,333
I want to have this holiday
without you, Dad.

1365
01:07:23,916 --> 01:07:26,457
I fucking hate you, Mom.
You're worse than Russia.

1366
01:07:26,458 --> 01:07:28,041
- Forgive me.
- I will never forgive you.

1367
01:07:28,750 --> 01:07:29,749
[Rio] No!

1368
01:07:29,750 --> 01:07:31,957
- Do not cancel the card.
- Nice to meet you.

1369
01:07:31,958 --> 01:07:34,041
[train announcement in French]

1370
01:07:40,041 --> 01:07:43,083
[announcement in French continues]

1371
01:07:46,833 --> 01:07:47,875
[Ron] Don't go.

1372
01:07:48,500 --> 01:07:49,582
He needs you.

1373
01:07:49,583 --> 01:07:51,999
- I need you.
- [Krista] Tell Jay I'm sorry.

1374
01:07:52,000 --> 01:07:55,166
My dog ate a screw.
I wrote him an apology.

1375
01:07:55,666 --> 01:07:57,208
It's like we always say.

1376
01:07:57,916 --> 01:08:00,290
If it feels good, don't do it.

1377
01:08:00,291 --> 01:08:03,375
And here are the outfits for each event.
They're color coded.

1378
01:08:04,041 --> 01:08:05,083
I'm doing it.

1379
01:08:05,916 --> 01:08:08,416
You did just bolt that night.

1380
01:08:10,416 --> 01:08:11,916
Back then on the Eiffel Tower.

1381
01:08:13,458 --> 01:08:16,707
We just sat down to dinner.
I wanted to turn our phones off.

1382
01:08:16,708 --> 01:08:19,333
But you said, "Keep them on just in case."

1383
01:08:20,750 --> 01:08:22,291
And of course we got the call.

1384
01:08:23,125 --> 01:08:26,458
Jay had been photographed with
that daughter of the French ambassador.

1385
01:08:27,375 --> 01:08:28,500
One of us had to go.

1386
01:08:29,250 --> 01:08:31,125
I stayed to keep the table.

1387
01:08:33,000 --> 01:08:34,375
I was so nervous...

1388
01:08:36,208 --> 01:08:39,208
because I had
a ring planted in the ganache.

1389
01:08:42,041 --> 01:08:43,499
I never knew that part.

1390
01:08:43,500 --> 01:08:46,416
Yeah, it was like a very romantic movie.

1391
01:08:47,166 --> 01:08:50,625
But one that is not romantic at all,
in fact, because...

1392
01:08:52,125 --> 01:08:53,750
you never came back.

1393
01:08:58,208 --> 01:09:00,875
Well, I was with Jay. [sighs]

1394
01:09:01,541 --> 01:09:02,916
And you were calling.

1395
01:09:05,666 --> 01:09:08,791
Jay is always gonna come first.

1396
01:09:09,291 --> 01:09:12,750
We were never going to have
a moment that was just ours.

1397
01:09:17,708 --> 01:09:19,583
I'm sorry about the Eiffel Tower.

1398
01:09:23,541 --> 01:09:25,291
It's okay. I'm happy.

1399
01:09:26,666 --> 01:09:27,500
I know.

1400
01:09:28,500 --> 01:09:29,791
And, uh, me too.

1401
01:09:30,541 --> 01:09:32,541
[poignant music playing]

1402
01:09:34,750 --> 01:09:36,000
And also, I'm sorry.

1403
01:09:37,208 --> 01:09:38,291
Thank you.

1404
01:09:50,916 --> 01:09:51,958
Save yourself.

1405
01:09:52,958 --> 01:09:54,750
[whistle blows]

1406
01:09:55,500 --> 01:09:58,375
[conductor yelling in French and Italian]

1407
01:09:58,916 --> 01:10:00,916
[music continues]

1408
01:10:22,083 --> 01:10:26,332
[train announcement in French]

1409
01:10:26,333 --> 01:10:27,957
[group groans]

1410
01:10:27,958 --> 01:10:29,083
What did they say?

1411
01:10:29,666 --> 01:10:31,582
The bloody air conditioning is no more.

1412
01:10:31,583 --> 01:10:33,332
Oh, swell.

1413
01:10:33,333 --> 01:10:35,416
[cell phone buzzing]

1414
01:10:36,791 --> 01:10:38,915
- Hi.
<i>- Vivienne's feet are swollen</i>

1415
01:10:38,916 --> 01:10:41,915
<i>- like I have never seen swollen.</i>
- Wait, wait. Swollen how?

1416
01:10:41,916 --> 01:10:43,540
Like after the cello recital?

1417
01:10:43,541 --> 01:10:46,415
- So much worse, Ron.
- I can't get into my Jordans, Dad.

1418
01:10:46,416 --> 01:10:47,624
I had to wear Crocs.

1419
01:10:47,625 --> 01:10:51,457
- Her feet look like big blimps.
- We're on our way to Dr. Fenner's.

1420
01:10:51,458 --> 01:10:53,665
I'm doing everything I can
to keep it together.

1421
01:10:53,666 --> 01:10:56,499
It's disgusting, Dad.
Michael Bronfman said it looks deformed.

1422
01:10:56,500 --> 01:10:58,540
Michael Bronfman is an asshole.

1423
01:10:58,541 --> 01:11:00,665
- [laughing]
- [David] Dad.

1424
01:11:00,666 --> 01:11:04,040
- When did the swelling start this time?
- Right after the tennis debacle.

1425
01:11:04,041 --> 01:11:05,207
<i>- Oh, God.</i>
- Almost immediately.

1426
01:11:05,208 --> 01:11:07,040
I get it. So it's my fault?

1427
01:11:07,041 --> 01:11:10,624
- I didn't say it was your fault, Ron.
- Did the cream not work?

1428
01:11:10,625 --> 01:11:13,499
- [Vivienne] <i>The cream did nothing.</i>
- Because you really gotta slather it.

1429
01:11:13,500 --> 01:11:16,582
Ron, we slathered it,
and we did the Advil.

1430
01:11:16,583 --> 01:11:18,540
Oh, my God. I am so sorry.

1431
01:11:18,541 --> 01:11:20,374
Mom, you just totally ran a red light.

1432
01:11:20,375 --> 01:11:21,790
Oh, fuck. Sorry.

1433
01:11:21,791 --> 01:11:23,290
You're gonna get a ticket.

1434
01:11:23,291 --> 01:11:26,124
Vivi, you're going to be okay,
you hear me?

1435
01:11:26,125 --> 01:11:27,665
- [Vivienne] <i>You think?</i>
- I know.

1436
01:11:27,666 --> 01:11:29,665
Dad, am I gonna be okay?

1437
01:11:29,666 --> 01:11:31,999
You are. You're gonna be great.

1438
01:11:32,000 --> 01:11:35,082
- You too, Lois. You're my hero.
- [Lois] <i>We're turning in now, Ron.</i>

1439
01:11:35,083 --> 01:11:38,374
- We'll call you from the doctor's.
- Dad, I think I might love Mom more.

1440
01:11:38,375 --> 01:11:41,208
I love you all so much.

1441
01:11:41,708 --> 01:11:44,915
- Can you hear me, Lois?
<i>- Yes, I can hear you, you're on speaker.</i>

1442
01:11:44,916 --> 01:11:46,874
It kills me that I'm not there with you.

1443
01:11:46,875 --> 01:11:49,999
- [Lois] <i>You're breaking up, Ron. Hell...</i>
- You're all my babies.

1444
01:11:50,000 --> 01:11:51,707
- I love-- Baby?
<i>- Mom, I told you to valet.</i>

1445
01:11:51,708 --> 01:11:53,375
[line disconnects]

1446
01:11:58,416 --> 01:12:01,125
[melancholy music playing]

1447
01:12:15,875 --> 01:12:17,124
- [Carter] <i>Dear Jay.</i>
- [Jessica] <i>Dear Jay.</i>

1448
01:12:17,125 --> 01:12:20,208
<i>- You say...
- You say you always want to be with me.</i>

1449
01:12:20,833 --> 01:12:25,333
[Jessica] <i>But your actions aren't speaking
the way your words are.</i>

1450
01:12:32,500 --> 01:12:35,540
<i>My worst day was
when my babysitter rented</i>

1451
01:12:35,541 --> 01:12:38,250
<i>that movie you did with Daphne Spender.</i>

1452
01:12:47,708 --> 01:12:49,207
[director] And cut.

1453
01:12:49,208 --> 01:12:50,874
- [light switches click]
- [bell rings]

1454
01:12:50,875 --> 01:12:54,499
[background chatter]

1455
01:12:54,500 --> 01:12:55,750
[man] Check...

1456
01:12:58,000 --> 01:12:59,166
Yeah, check the switches.

1457
01:12:59,666 --> 01:13:01,832
Sorry, I feel we should've
got to know each other a bit

1458
01:13:01,833 --> 01:13:03,165
before we did this.

1459
01:13:03,166 --> 01:13:06,250
Sometimes it's better to have sex
with someone before you know them.

1460
01:13:07,000 --> 01:13:08,874
Or pretend sex. In this case.

1461
01:13:08,875 --> 01:13:11,916
[young Jay] Have you had pretend sex
with a lot of people before you knew them?

1462
01:13:12,500 --> 01:13:16,415
- A few. It's the least sexy thing ever.
- [chuckles]

1463
01:13:16,416 --> 01:13:18,500
It's so embarrassing.

1464
01:13:19,041 --> 01:13:21,249
- That hush that descends.
- Oh, yeah.

1465
01:13:21,250 --> 01:13:23,957
It's like we doing something
incredibly serious and important.

1466
01:13:23,958 --> 01:13:26,332
Well, it's more like a funeral
than a love scene.

1467
01:13:26,333 --> 01:13:27,874
- [Daphne] I know.
- [bell rings]

1468
01:13:27,875 --> 01:13:28,833
[director] Okay.

1469
01:13:29,791 --> 01:13:31,665
- We're rolling.
- Forty six, take eight.

1470
01:13:31,666 --> 01:13:32,583
[slate clicks]

1471
