- [actors inaudible]
- Man, life is so weird.

1522
01:16:31,500 --> 01:16:33,333
I wonder if you think about it like I do.

1523
01:16:38,750 --> 01:16:40,041
Anyway...

1524
01:16:41,375 --> 01:16:44,957
There were a million reasons
why we didn't stay together and...

1525
01:16:44,958 --> 01:16:46,500
[bell rings]

1526
01:16:47,166 --> 01:16:48,666
[director] We're going again.

1527
01:16:49,625 --> 01:16:51,583
And... action.

1528
01:16:56,000 --> 01:16:57,666
[Daphne] I'm so in love with you.

1529
01:17:03,583 --> 01:17:06,166
[music draws to a close]

1530
01:17:23,500 --> 01:17:25,791
Italy. What is its fatal charm?

1531
01:17:27,916 --> 01:17:30,833
I believe it is a certain permission
to be human.

1532
01:17:31,333 --> 01:17:33,540
Which other places lost too long ago.

1533
01:17:33,541 --> 01:17:35,332
[life coach] I had a dream about you.

1534
01:17:35,333 --> 01:17:38,457
I loved you in the dream
just as much as I do in real life--

1535
01:17:38,458 --> 01:17:39,540
[Clive] Really? All right?

1536
01:17:39,541 --> 01:17:41,665
I had a dream I had
a window in my chest, right?

1537
01:17:41,666 --> 01:17:44,457
But the view was the view
from our bathroom...

1538
01:17:44,458 --> 01:17:46,750
[poignant music playing]

1539
01:17:56,666 --> 01:17:59,582
I'm suddenly remembering things
I haven't thought about in a long time.

1540
01:17:59,583 --> 01:18:04,041
- My family's losing it at home.
- Like a movie where I'm playing myself.

1541
01:18:04,625 --> 01:18:06,582
- Watching myself...
- I'm sorry, go again.

1542
01:18:06,583 --> 01:18:09,999
- I didn't hear a word you said.
- I said I'm suddenly remembering things.

1543
01:18:10,000 --> 01:18:11,040
Now, what is that?

1544
01:18:11,041 --> 01:18:12,791
- Memory?
- Well, yes.

1545
01:18:13,916 --> 01:18:18,332
Maybe your memory's trying
to tell you something about your present.

1546
01:18:18,333 --> 01:18:21,249
- Like what?
- I don't know. I'm tired.

1547
01:18:21,250 --> 01:18:24,207
- I just had a fight with Daisy.
- I wish I was there to help them.

1548
01:18:24,208 --> 01:18:26,207
- What?
- What? Nothing.

1549
01:18:26,208 --> 01:18:28,040
- Ah.
- I'm just... tired...

1550
01:18:28,041 --> 01:18:31,707
I just wish I would have spent more time
with her, I was always at work.

1551
01:18:31,708 --> 01:18:35,165
Well, I always negotiated flights
on the weekends for you

1552
01:18:35,166 --> 01:18:38,040
- to go home and see the kids.
- It was very difficult to...

1553
01:18:38,041 --> 01:18:40,540
- What are you getting at?
- I'm just saying, Ben, for instance,

1554
01:18:40,541 --> 01:18:43,457
flies home every weekend
from the show to see his family.

1555
01:18:43,458 --> 01:18:45,374
- Ben? Ben Alcock?
- I'm not comparing.

1556
01:18:45,375 --> 01:18:48,290
- It's hard not to feel like you are.
- These are the decisions we make

1557
01:18:48,291 --> 01:18:50,874
- like I made to come on this trip.
- These aren't just decisions.

1558
01:18:50,875 --> 01:18:52,790
Or not kiss Liz back.
My family would rather...

1559
01:18:52,791 --> 01:18:53,915
Kiss Liz back?

1560
01:18:53,916 --> 01:18:56,208
- ...I'm home right now.
- Did you kiss Liz?

1561
01:18:56,791 --> 01:18:59,082
- No, she kissed me.
- Where is Liz?

1562
01:18:59,083 --> 01:19:02,749
Liz left. Krista, too.
Her dog ate a screw.

1563
01:19:02,750 --> 01:19:04,291
Krista's dog, not Liz's.

1564
01:19:04,958 --> 01:19:06,291
Liz was just pissed.

1565
01:19:06,875 --> 01:19:08,457
She left you this note.

1566
01:19:08,458 --> 01:19:10,125
Krista, not Liz.

1567
01:19:14,416 --> 01:19:16,875
Liz <i>leave</i> leave, like forever?

1568
01:19:18,125 --> 01:19:20,125
What is forever? I don't...

1569
01:19:21,083 --> 01:19:22,999
Does Ben Alcock really fly home
on the weekends?

1570
01:19:23,000 --> 01:19:24,957
Ben's no saint.
This was his second marriage.

1571
01:19:24,958 --> 01:19:27,833
- She was the nanny.
- You don't have to put him down.

1572
01:19:28,708 --> 01:19:31,249
Were you ever gonna let me know
what happened with Timothy?

1573
01:19:31,250 --> 01:19:33,541
- I told you I would.
- Yeah, but you didn't.

1574
01:19:36,291 --> 01:19:38,125
Think maybe you can get me a water?

1575
01:19:38,916 --> 01:19:40,000
Can't you get it?

1576
01:19:42,083 --> 01:19:45,708
[footsteps clumbering]

1577
01:19:46,333 --> 01:19:47,833
Stop! Thief!

1578
01:19:48,541 --> 01:19:50,125
He's got my handbag.

1579
01:19:51,375 --> 01:19:54,291
No. No... no.

1580
01:19:56,541 --> 01:19:59,583
[general clamor]

1581
01:20:01,291 --> 01:20:02,416
[passenger] Whoa!

1582
01:20:03,583 --> 01:20:05,457
[passengers shouting]

1583
01:20:05,458 --> 01:20:07,707
[brakes screeching]

1584
01:20:07,708 --> 01:20:09,583
[hydraulics hiss]

1585
01:20:10,083 --> 01:20:12,165
[panting]

1586
01:20:12,166 --> 01:20:14,500
[gasping]

1587
01:20:19,083 --> 01:20:20,249
[Silvano] Oh! Fuck!

1588
01:20:20,250 --> 01:20:23,832
Whoa! Whoa! Silvano! I'm-I'm going.

1589
01:20:23,833 --> 01:20:24,915
[Silvano] Oh. Oh.

1590
01:20:24,916 --> 01:20:27,207
[both panting]

1591
01:20:27,208 --> 01:20:28,958
He really is a hero.

1592
01:20:29,541 --> 01:20:31,583
[dramatic orchestral music playing]

1593
01:20:33,750 --> 01:20:35,208
[grunting]

1594
01:20:38,375 --> 01:20:40,749
- I wanna go out there.
- God, I love your attitude.

1595
01:20:40,750 --> 01:20:41,665
[people chattering]

1596
01:20:41,666 --> 01:20:42,916
I've got five.

1597
01:20:43,416 --> 01:20:45,249
- Go!
- That is so not fair.

1598
01:20:45,250 --> 01:20:46,290
[pop music blaring]

1599
01:20:46,291 --> 01:20:48,332
- This is unbelievable.
- [music resumes]

1600
01:20:48,333 --> 01:20:49,666
[panting]

1601
01:20:50,250 --> 01:20:51,833
[panting]

1602
01:20:55,041 --> 01:20:55,875
[grunts]

1603
01:21:06,791 --> 01:21:08,791
[music halts]

1604
01:21:20,625 --> 01:21:22,541
- Oh!
- Oof.

1605
01:21:24,666 --> 01:21:26,541
[Jay grunts, strains]

1606
01:21:28,083 --> 01:21:29,250
[grunts]

1607
01:21:29,958 --> 01:21:33,291
- I got you, you son of a bitch!
- [woman] You should've gone ahead, Clive.

1608
01:21:33,791 --> 01:21:35,624
- [Jay shouts out]
- [cheering]

1609
01:21:35,625 --> 01:21:36,790
[Clive] Jay captured the thief!

1610
01:21:36,791 --> 01:21:39,208
- [man] Hey, bravo!
- Shit was real.

1611
01:21:39,791 --> 01:21:42,124
- There we go.
- Thanks, love!

1612
01:21:42,125 --> 01:21:44,958
- And he gave him a black eye, the bastard.
- A real shiner.

1613
01:21:45,583 --> 01:21:46,415
[old woman] Oh.

1614
01:21:46,416 --> 01:21:48,041
- [man] Bravo, bravo!
- [Jay gasps]

1615
01:21:48,583 --> 01:21:50,250
- Okay, all right.
- Mwah!

1616
01:21:51,000 --> 01:21:53,374
- [man] Bravo.
- [old woman] Such a gentleman.

1617
01:21:53,375 --> 01:21:56,166
Stop looking at me
and talking about me all the time.

1618
01:21:59,125 --> 01:22:01,207
[cyclist] Please be kind,
he just needs his medication.

1619
01:22:01,208 --> 01:22:03,249
He's a nice guy, a real family man.

1620
01:22:03,250 --> 01:22:05,750
He has three wonderful kids.
This is not who he is.

1621
01:22:09,041 --> 01:22:10,708
[sobs]

1622
01:22:12,166 --> 01:22:13,583
You're a hero, puppy.

1623
01:22:16,500 --> 01:22:17,375
Okay?

1624
01:22:17,875 --> 01:22:18,708
[sniffs]

1625
01:22:23,375 --> 01:22:24,874
- Come on.
- Will you just...

1626
01:22:24,875 --> 01:22:26,208
get him to a doctor.

1627
01:22:26,791 --> 01:22:28,208
I'll get you that water.

1628
01:22:28,875 --> 01:22:30,041
I'll be there in a minute.

1629
01:22:50,375 --> 01:22:54,082
[Ron, softly]
"And the little tiny, tiny fur animal

1630
01:22:54,083 --> 01:22:58,124
ran down a hole into the ground." You see?

1631
01:22:58,125 --> 01:23:01,665
[David]
<i>A little cute bear putting on its coat.</i>

1632
01:23:01,666 --> 01:23:02,665
[Ron] Mm-hmm.

1633
01:23:02,666 --> 01:23:06,208
"Then sun went down beyond the river..."

1634
01:23:06,875 --> 01:23:10,250
[brakes screech]

1635
01:23:10,750 --> 01:23:11,957
[hydraulics hiss]

1636
01:23:11,958 --> 01:23:14,040
[indistinct police radio chatter]

1637
01:23:14,041 --> 01:23:15,750
I'll take care of your bike, okay?

1638
01:23:17,875 --> 01:23:19,125
[passengers chattering]

1639
01:23:22,041 --> 01:23:23,833
[Guigui] Daisy, can you please tell them?

1640
01:23:25,000 --> 01:23:27,083
- [friends chattering]
- [Jay] Daisy.

1641
01:23:27,833 --> 01:23:28,665
Daisy?

1642
01:23:28,666 --> 01:23:30,624
[Guigui]
Can you tell her that it's true?

1643
01:23:30,625 --> 01:23:32,000
[French girl] What is true?

1644
01:23:32,750 --> 01:23:34,082
[Guigui] Like the horse can win without...

1645
01:23:34,083 --> 01:23:35,165
Have fun.

1646
01:23:35,166 --> 01:23:36,290
[engine starts]

1647
01:23:36,291 --> 01:23:37,916
See you, Dad. Love you.

1648
01:23:39,208 --> 01:23:41,833
- Love you, too.
- [engine revs]

1649
01:23:48,041 --> 01:23:49,583
[Ron] It's right to let her go.

1650
01:23:52,000 --> 01:23:55,624
So, I spoke to Alan,
he's got a legal letter ready.

1651
01:23:55,625 --> 01:23:58,499
I signed off on it. We also have to have
a statement prepared

1652
01:23:58,500 --> 01:24:01,750
in case T-Timothy goes to the press.

1653
01:24:02,250 --> 01:24:06,666
I got a draft here, I need you to read it,
be okay with it.

1654
01:24:07,208 --> 01:24:08,291
These are yours.

1655
01:24:09,125 --> 01:24:12,375
I know you know what to say.
Whatever happens, happens.

1656
01:24:14,625 --> 01:24:17,000
Daisy's my friend, too,
and I betrayed her.

1657
01:24:17,583 --> 01:24:19,124
You were just doing your job.

1658
01:24:19,125 --> 01:24:22,457
That's a Nazi excuse.
I feel like such a bad person.

1659
01:24:22,458 --> 01:24:24,541
It's my fault, Meg. Listen...

1660
01:24:25,583 --> 01:24:28,415
take a break, go on a holiday in Italy.

1661
01:24:28,416 --> 01:24:30,500
I'll be fine. Is it...? Uh...

1662
01:24:31,333 --> 01:24:32,875
Ron, do you have any...? Um...

1663
01:24:37,458 --> 01:24:39,250
Thank you, Jay.

1664
01:24:40,291 --> 01:24:43,583
For the record, I'd love it
if my father chased me across Europe.

1665
01:24:46,125 --> 01:24:48,999
Oh, and Emmanuel Macron
is taking Candy to Geneva,

1666
01:24:49,000 --> 01:24:50,333
so you need another hair person.

1667
01:24:51,291 --> 01:24:53,624
I love you and congratulations.

1668
01:24:53,625 --> 01:24:55,624
[in Italian accent] Mr. Kelly! Sorry.

1669
01:24:55,625 --> 01:24:57,666
Mr. Caterpillar. Hi.

1670
01:24:58,833 --> 01:25:00,666
Hi, I'm Alba, your driver.

1671
01:25:01,250 --> 01:25:02,540
Your daddy is waiting for you

1672
01:25:02,541 --> 01:25:05,374
at the restaurant with Antonio
and host committee.

1673
01:25:05,375 --> 01:25:06,499
- My "daddy"?
- Yeah.

1674
01:25:06,500 --> 01:25:09,790
Your daddy. I called him
and sent a plane. He's very excited.

1675
01:25:09,791 --> 01:25:12,207
Shit. I didn't think he'd actually come.

1676
01:25:12,208 --> 01:25:13,415
[sighs]

1677
01:25:13,416 --> 01:25:15,583
I will bring you to your daddy.

1678
01:25:16,208 --> 01:25:17,625
[chuckles]

1679
01:25:20,250 --> 01:25:21,708
{\an8}Is this everyone?

1680
01:25:22,916 --> 01:25:24,666
- Mmm.
- Yeah? Okay.

1681
01:25:26,208 --> 01:25:27,499
[Ron] Can you take maybe one bag?

1682
01:25:27,500 --> 01:25:28,915
- You take it.
- [Ron] What?

1683
01:25:28,916 --> 01:25:30,040
Take it.

1684
01:25:30,041 --> 01:25:31,583
[Ron] Jesus Christ.

1685
01:25:37,500 --> 01:25:40,457
Ah, I forgot to give you, Mr. Kelly.

1686
01:25:40,458 --> 01:25:42,624
Mr. Caterpillar, your cheesecake.

1687
01:25:42,625 --> 01:25:45,708
- Wonderful. Thank you.
- My rider. You eat it.

1688
01:25:46,375 --> 01:25:49,291
[Alba] Here in Italy,
we like to work hard.

1689
01:25:49,875 --> 01:25:54,624
But also, when we finish our work,
we relax and we like to eat.

1690
01:25:54,625 --> 01:26:00,125
We cry sometimes, but also,
if you are funny, we might laugh.

1691
01:26:01,166 --> 01:26:02,457
Sometimes we get married...

1692
01:26:02,458 --> 01:26:05,540
Don't get mad at Candy.
We'll find you a new hair person.

1693
01:26:05,541 --> 01:26:07,540
I have too many people around me anyway.

1694
01:26:07,541 --> 01:26:09,207
You need some people, right?

1695
01:26:09,208 --> 01:26:11,375
We argue sometimes. But also...

1696
01:26:11,958 --> 01:26:14,790
- Maybe an accountant.
- A lawyer. You need Alan.

1697
01:26:14,791 --> 01:26:17,333
Who else? Publicity, chef.

1698
01:26:18,250 --> 01:26:19,666
Or me. You need me.

1699
01:26:20,916 --> 01:26:22,415
Yeah, Ron. I need you.

1700
01:26:22,416 --> 01:26:24,290
- [Alba chatters, indistinct]
- [thud]

1701
01:26:24,291 --> 01:26:27,457
Fuck. I think I just hit a rabbit.

1702
01:26:27,458 --> 01:26:30,790
Alba, is there someplace we can get a gift
or something for my dad?

1703
01:26:30,791 --> 01:26:31,832
Yeah, yeah.

1704
01:26:31,833 --> 01:26:34,665
Can you drop me
at Ristorante da Rosa, please?

1705
01:26:34,666 --> 01:26:35,665
Where you goin'?

1706
01:26:35,666 --> 01:26:38,457
Uh, I have a 5 p.m.
Just a quick drink in town.

1707
01:26:38,458 --> 01:26:40,915
I'll be back for your dinner.
Save me a tiramisu.

1708
01:26:40,916 --> 01:26:42,665
Who do you have a 5 p.m. with?

1709
01:26:42,666 --> 01:26:46,457
Uh, Ben Alcock. I just--
I gotta put a little time in with him.

1710
01:26:46,458 --> 01:26:48,374
'Cause he's also getting a tribute?

1711
01:26:48,375 --> 01:26:49,957
The second tribute, yes.

1712
01:26:49,958 --> 01:26:53,624
So you're gonna just leave me alone
with my "daddy."

1713
01:26:53,625 --> 01:26:56,374
I'm here for you. I'm always here.

1714
01:26:56,375 --> 01:26:59,249
And I'll be with you from 7
for the rest of the trip.

1715
01:26:59,250 --> 01:27:02,999
I don't care. Meet Ben Alcock.
What's in his rider?

1716
01:27:03,000 --> 01:27:05,333
Actually, Ben's rider is quite minimal.

1717
01:27:06,083 --> 01:27:06,915
Fuck off.

1718
01:27:06,916 --> 01:27:08,208
[scoffs]

1719
01:27:22,083 --> 01:27:25,458
<i>- Ciao, Signore Ron.</i>
- Thank you, Alba.

1720
01:27:26,208 --> 01:27:29,666
Try to have some fun.
Say hi to your dad for me.

1721
01:27:31,000 --> 01:27:33,749
[bell tolls]

1722
01:27:33,750 --> 01:27:37,249
[Alba] You might meet a ghost
while you sleep here.

1723
01:27:37,250 --> 01:27:42,832
The ghosts are usually little monks
who expose themselves.

1724
01:27:42,833 --> 01:27:45,332
I would have thought
they would love to meet Jay Kelly.

1725
01:27:45,333 --> 01:27:48,833
So, I stopped pumping iron,
and I took up yoga.

1726
01:27:49,333 --> 01:27:52,457
And now I'm in the best shape of my life!

1727
01:27:52,458 --> 01:27:54,374
Still slender, but taut.

1728
01:27:54,375 --> 01:27:57,915
Also keep the mental game tough.
Do a little sudoku.

1729
01:27:57,916 --> 01:27:59,291
- [all] Ah.
- [Jay] Hey.

1730
01:28:01,583 --> 01:28:04,165
- My son, the movie star.
- Hey, Studly.

1731
01:28:04,166 --> 01:28:06,125
- Oh.
- [both chuckle]

1732
01:28:06,708 --> 01:28:07,875
- Studly made it.
- Ah.

1733
01:28:08,375 --> 01:28:10,415
Uh, meet Captain Jenny and Lourdes.

1734
01:28:10,416 --> 01:28:12,749
They flew me in on that tiny plane
you got me.

1735
01:28:12,750 --> 01:28:13,707
Lady pilot.

1736
01:28:13,708 --> 01:28:16,207
Your father entertained us all the way
from Maine to Florence

1737
01:28:16,208 --> 01:28:19,457
with his wonderful,
often offensive stories.

1738
01:28:19,458 --> 01:28:21,375
What a personality.

1739
01:28:21,958 --> 01:28:26,874
Jay, the apple doesn't fall
very far from the tree.

1740
01:28:26,875 --> 01:28:27,791
Well--

1741
01:28:28,416 --> 01:28:31,957
Now, where is this famous Ron?
We expected the whole team.

1742
01:28:31,958 --> 01:28:36,582
Yes. We thought Mr. Caterpillar
would have rolled very deep.

1743
01:28:36,583 --> 01:28:38,500
No, the famous Ron had a 5 p.m.

1744
01:28:39,000 --> 01:28:41,040
Ron is very protective of you.

1745
01:28:41,041 --> 01:28:44,708
He was so worried about
the size and the shape of your trophy.

1746
01:28:45,583 --> 01:28:46,999
I'm sure I'll love it.

1747
01:28:47,000 --> 01:28:48,749
A local artisan, Giovanni,

1748
01:28:48,750 --> 01:28:54,791
did what I think you Americans call
an all-nighter, and blew it himself.

1749
01:28:55,291 --> 01:28:57,291
[speaking in Italian]

1750
01:29:04,166 --> 01:29:09,207
Giovanni regrets the mask.
He suffers from infinite COVID.

1751
01:29:09,208 --> 01:29:12,707
Jay Kelly. Your cheesecake is waiting.

1752
01:29:12,708 --> 01:29:14,040
[continues in Italian]

1753
01:29:14,041 --> 01:29:15,749
Jesus Christ.

1754
01:29:15,750 --> 01:29:17,833
Thank you. Thank you very much.
Thank you.

1755
01:29:18,958 --> 01:29:22,499
[Ron] I'm the best friend anybody has,
but you don't want me as an enemy.

1756
01:29:22,500 --> 01:29:25,124
I promise you that.
Because what you're saying--

1757
01:29:25,125 --> 01:29:27,540
Would-- I-- Let me talk!

1758
01:29:27,541 --> 01:29:31,874
Because what you're saying sounds
remarkably like a shakedown.

1759
01:29:31,875 --> 01:29:33,082
I'm happy to be wrong,

1760
01:29:33,083 --> 01:29:36,083
but if that's what we're doing,
I'm hanging up the telephone right now.

1761
01:29:37,000 --> 01:29:40,541
You do that.
Speak to Timothy, then call me back.

1762
01:29:42,000 --> 01:29:44,166
[man greets in Italian]

1763
01:29:44,916 --> 01:29:49,250
Alan, are you there? That motherfucker
was trying to shake us down.

1764
01:29:50,125 --> 01:29:52,582
It's dead.
Did we hear from the detective?

1765
01:29:52,583 --> 01:29:53,500
Like the neckerchief.

1766
01:29:54,083 --> 01:29:57,500
All right. Hold your fire.
I got a drink now with Benny boy.

1767
01:29:58,375 --> 01:30:01,540
Yeah. Yeah. Let me know.
I'll call you after.

1768
01:30:01,541 --> 01:30:02,624
Yeah. <i>Ciao.</i>

1769
01:30:02,625 --> 01:30:04,874
It's hot as hell. Jesus.

1770
01:30:04,875 --> 01:30:09,082
- What happened? What'd you say?
- Uh, I-I like the neckerchief.

1771
01:30:09,083 --> 01:30:12,207
Yeah? Yeah. Right. Ahh.

1772
01:30:12,208 --> 01:30:16,749
You look handsome, Ben Alcock
with the dreamy blue eyes.

1773
01:30:16,750 --> 01:30:17,707
[both chuckle]

1774
01:30:17,708 --> 01:30:22,124
- Flight good?
- It was a two-class plane, small first.

1775
01:30:22,125 --> 01:30:23,749
But lie-down beds, so...

1776
01:30:23,750 --> 01:30:25,666
- Happy ending.
- Yeah.

1777
01:30:26,375 --> 01:30:28,915
- Did you order a drink?
- Uh, I'm just having seltzer.

1778
01:30:28,916 --> 01:30:31,582
- Aww. Well...
- You just fly in?

1779
01:30:31,583 --> 01:30:36,582
Train. It was a whole--
But, um, it's fine. We're all good.

1780
01:30:36,583 --> 01:30:39,875
I just sent Jay to a dinner
with the festival people.

1781
01:30:40,375 --> 01:30:42,750
- Jay got a dinner?
- You got a dinner too.

1782
01:30:43,541 --> 01:30:46,749
- My schedule said "drinks."
- You don't wanna be at that dinner.

1783
01:30:46,750 --> 01:30:48,915
You brought your family.
You're a proper human.

1784
01:30:48,916 --> 01:30:51,249
Jay is single and weird
and needs to be entertained.

1785
01:30:51,250 --> 01:30:53,999
You don't have to put Jay down
to make me feel better.

1786
01:30:54,000 --> 01:30:57,165
- You do that, Ron. You know that?
- I love Jay. Been like a father to Jay.

1787
01:30:57,166 --> 01:31:00,124
But much less complicated
because I'm like a brother.

1788
01:31:00,125 --> 01:31:01,333
I could use a drink!

1789
01:31:03,958 --> 01:31:08,165
So, I-I've been thinking,
and, uh, talking to Melanie.

1790
01:31:08,166 --> 01:31:12,541
And... And I feel like I'm not
really getting enough of you.

1791
01:31:13,875 --> 01:31:17,499
Really? I'm here now, puppy.
What haven't I been there for?

1792
01:31:17,500 --> 01:31:20,415
I know you're in the Jay Kelly business,
and I can't compete with him.

1793
01:31:20,416 --> 01:31:22,540
I'm okay with that. [chuckles]

1794
01:31:22,541 --> 01:31:24,665
I mean, I know the only reason
I'm getting this tribute

1795
01:31:24,666 --> 01:31:27,124
- is because he passed on it.
- And then took it back.

1796
01:31:27,125 --> 01:31:28,915
I'm sorry that got all <i>farkakte.</i>

1797
01:31:28,916 --> 01:31:31,374
But don't worry.
You're both getting trophies.

1798
01:31:31,375 --> 01:31:32,875
But I need to get some of you.

1799
01:31:34,583 --> 01:31:38,874
Okay. Jay is one of my clients,
but he's not my only client.

1800
01:31:38,875 --> 01:31:40,291
How can I improve?

1801
01:31:42,041 --> 01:31:44,291
I'm gonna go without a manager
for a while. [voice shaking]

1802
01:31:45,166 --> 01:31:47,874
- Hold on.
- Just an attorney and an agent.

1803
01:31:47,875 --> 01:31:49,165
- And a publicist.
- All right.

1804
01:31:49,166 --> 01:31:50,540
Uh, and a business manager.

1805
01:31:50,541 --> 01:31:52,749
You're my second oldest client ever.

1806
01:31:52,750 --> 01:31:55,082
We've been together
since the Disney shows.

1807
01:31:55,083 --> 01:31:57,874
- I... I know.
- I'm having problems at home.

1808
01:31:57,875 --> 01:32:01,040
- Vivienne has anxiety and swollen feet.
- I'm sorry to hear that.

1809
01:32:01,041 --> 01:32:03,540
You're just coming off
a successful television show.

1810
01:32:03,541 --> 01:32:07,124
- That correction takes a minute.
- It's been a minute already.

1811
01:32:07,125 --> 01:32:10,540
You're in-between ages, but I really feel
like you're entering a sweet spot.

1812
01:32:10,541 --> 01:32:11,999
I-I just need to try this.

1813
01:32:12,000 --> 01:32:14,665
I was at your wedding. I gave you a toast!

1814
01:32:14,666 --> 01:32:16,915
- I know! I know!
- We're family. I love you!

1815
01:32:16,916 --> 01:32:19,708
Stop. Stop! Stop.

1816
01:32:21,583 --> 01:32:23,332
I knew it would be hard to do this.

1817
01:32:23,333 --> 01:32:25,625
[inhales]

1818
01:32:26,125 --> 01:32:28,624
I was gonna send an email
after the tribute,

1819
01:32:28,625 --> 01:32:31,124
but Melanie said I should do it in person.

1820
01:32:31,125 --> 01:32:32,250
I didn't have to.

1821
01:32:32,958 --> 01:32:37,374
There are things I do all day long
that you don't know about.

1822
01:32:37,375 --> 01:32:39,457
No, don't--
don't try to talk me out of it.

1823
01:32:39,458 --> 01:32:41,625
- [sobs]
- No, don't cry.

1824
01:32:42,625 --> 01:32:44,165
- You're crying, puppy.
- No, I know.

1825
01:32:44,166 --> 01:32:46,707
But it doesn't mean you have to cry.

1826
01:32:46,708 --> 01:32:49,500
Okay, you cry, puppy.
You were crying first.

1827
01:32:53,416 --> 01:32:54,958
[clatters]

1828
01:32:55,750 --> 01:32:58,999
I'm sorry. I'm just... [sighs]

1829
01:32:59,000 --> 01:33:03,083
I'm just jet-lagged and I'm tired
and I'm old.

1830
01:33:04,750 --> 01:33:07,625
[somber piano music playing]

1831
01:33:18,208 --> 01:33:19,624
[exhales]

1832
01:33:19,625 --> 01:33:21,874
- [drumming]
- [Lois] <i>She's okay.</i>

1833
01:33:21,875 --> 01:33:25,999
<i>Fenner says that she's picking up on
your stress, and it's affecting her feet.</i>

1834
01:33:26,000 --> 01:33:28,707
How the fuck is my stress
affecting Vivienne's feet?

1835
01:33:28,708 --> 01:33:31,082
<i>Relax, Ronnie.
It makes sense if you think about it.</i>

1836
01:33:31,083 --> 01:33:34,624
You're gonna let a foot doctor
analyze our child? What is wrong with you?

1837
01:33:34,625 --> 01:33:38,207
Don't speak to me like that.
I am single-parenting it here.

1838
01:33:38,208 --> 01:33:41,624
- And we all have David's cold.
- I'm sorry. I love you.

1839
01:33:41,625 --> 01:33:44,625
It's just... I'm havin' a bad day.

1840
01:33:45,208 --> 01:33:47,166
- Are you okay?
<i>- No.</i>

1841
01:33:48,708 --> 01:33:52,540
I was just fired, and I'm cryin'.
I'm alone in Italy, and I'm cryin'.

1842
01:33:52,541 --> 01:33:55,332
[cries]

1843
01:33:55,333 --> 01:33:59,290
I know you're mad at me.
Can I just hear "I love you" back?

1844
01:33:59,291 --> 01:34:01,124
[drumming over phone]

1845
01:34:01,125 --> 01:34:04,165
- Jay fired you?
- No. Ben.

1846
01:34:04,166 --> 01:34:06,875
- [Vivienne] Jay fired Dad?
- No, Ben. Go back inside.

1847
01:34:08,333 --> 01:34:09,957
That motherfucker.

1848
01:34:09,958 --> 01:34:12,249
And you got him this tribute
and everything.

1849
01:34:12,250 --> 01:34:13,790
<i>I know.</i>

1850
01:34:13,791 --> 01:34:15,415
You still have Jay, right?

1851
01:34:15,416 --> 01:34:17,540
Yes, yes, I still have Jay.

1852
01:34:17,541 --> 01:34:20,040
- If I ever get him back to do this movie.
- [bells tolling]

1853
01:34:20,041 --> 01:34:23,290
- Can you just say it, please?
<i>- What is that sound?</i>

1854
01:34:23,291 --> 01:34:26,000
- [bells tolling]
- The bells. It's all death and...

1855
01:34:26,541 --> 01:34:28,041
firing here!

1856
01:34:29,958 --> 01:34:33,290
Ron, I just saw the thing
on Page Six about Jay.

1857
01:34:33,291 --> 01:34:34,666
<i>Wait. What-- What thing?</i>

1858
01:34:35,250 --> 01:34:37,540
- What thing about Jay?
- [bells tolling]

1859
01:34:37,541 --> 01:34:38,790
Lois?

1860
01:34:38,791 --> 01:34:41,541
So why am I here, Studly?
Who dropped out?

1861
01:34:42,083 --> 01:34:44,165
Nobody. I invited you.

1862
01:34:44,166 --> 01:34:45,540
- Oh?
- Yes.

1863
01:34:45,541 --> 01:34:48,250
First time in years Studly's
brought me to a ratfuck.

1864
01:34:48,750 --> 01:34:51,457
He got threatened when I showed up
at the Globes in the '90s.

1865
01:34:51,458 --> 01:34:52,582
That's not true.

1866
01:34:52,583 --> 01:34:54,583
Jay's dad was his most handsome back then.

1867
01:34:55,166 --> 01:34:56,999
Susan Sarandon had a little crush on me.

1868
01:34:57,000 --> 01:34:58,082
[all coo]

1869
01:34:58,083 --> 01:34:59,749
Well, I'm glad you're here.

1870
01:34:59,750 --> 01:35:03,332
She even sent me a video of a baby
elephant reuniting with his parents.

1871
01:35:03,333 --> 01:35:05,958
- And were they happy to see him?
- That was the point.

1872
01:35:06,541 --> 01:35:08,208
Very cute. Very tender.

1873
01:35:08,791 --> 01:35:10,041
What's this for?

1874
01:35:10,708 --> 01:35:11,957
For nothin'. It's a present.

1875
01:35:11,958 --> 01:35:13,875
- Well--
- It's a sweater!

1876
01:35:14,541 --> 01:35:15,833
[Alba chuckles]

1877
01:35:19,416 --> 01:35:22,291
Nice.

1878
01:35:23,041 --> 01:35:25,875
It is a sweater. Cashmere, no less.

1879
01:35:27,666 --> 01:35:28,625
You have it.

1880
01:35:29,125 --> 01:35:32,125
- Too high a thread count for your dad.
- No, I got it for you.

1881
01:35:34,833 --> 01:35:35,833
Take the sweater.

1882
01:35:40,333 --> 01:35:41,666
Where's my granddaughter?

1883
01:35:42,250 --> 01:35:43,374
Ron said she'd be here.

1884
01:35:43,375 --> 01:35:45,582
She's doin' her own thing.
She's at that age.

1885
01:35:45,583 --> 01:35:46,832
You remember bein' 18.

1886
01:35:46,833 --> 01:35:50,207
I remember Brylcreem.
"A little dab'll do ya." Huh?

1887
01:35:50,208 --> 01:35:52,249
- [guests chuckle]
- Mr. Kelly <i>padre?</i>

1888
01:35:52,250 --> 01:35:55,665
- Hmm?
- Are you also an artist, like your son?

1889
01:35:55,666 --> 01:35:56,958
Artist? No.

1890
01:35:57,458 --> 01:35:58,957
Working stiff.

1891
01:35:58,958 --> 01:36:01,707
Worked for the John Deere corporation
for the past 35 years.

1892
01:36:01,708 --> 01:36:05,832
Retired, and all those assholes gave me
was a shitty pension and a fountain pen.

1893
01:36:05,833 --> 01:36:07,832
No trophy or cheesecake for your dad.

1894
01:36:07,833 --> 01:36:10,666
You toiled so your son
could have his dreams.

1895
01:36:11,375 --> 01:36:14,333
I like that. I like how you put that.

1896
01:36:15,208 --> 01:36:16,915
Yeah, when he was a boy,

1897
01:36:16,916 --> 01:36:20,499
I thought he'd grow up to be somebody
that I'd like to have a beer with.

1898
01:36:20,500 --> 01:36:22,874
Not, uh, Beaujolais.

1899
01:36:22,875 --> 01:36:26,000
Yeah, I played tough guys
so I didn't have to be one.

1900
01:36:26,791 --> 01:36:29,790
Action movies are bullshit. It's all fake.

1901
01:36:29,791 --> 01:36:30,749
Ah.

1902
01:36:30,750 --> 01:36:33,875
Did you always know
Jay was going to be a star?

1903
01:36:34,541 --> 01:36:37,375
Well, he barely said a word
till he was about five.

1904
01:36:37,875 --> 01:36:40,582
Then one morning, he gets up,
and he comes down to breakfast,

1905
01:36:40,583 --> 01:36:43,165
and he starts talking
in this funny southern way.

1906
01:36:43,166 --> 01:36:45,290
- [phone dings]
- And he's acting very clumsy.

1907
01:36:45,291 --> 01:36:46,332
[scattered chuckling]

1908
01:36:46,333 --> 01:36:48,582
His mom thought he'd lost his mind,
but I said,

1909
01:36:48,583 --> 01:36:51,582
"Celia, no, no. Don't worry.
He's just playing a character."

1910
01:36:51,583 --> 01:36:54,124
I was impersonating my Uncle Mark.

1911
01:36:54,125 --> 01:36:56,457
Right. He kept saying, "Seriously."

1912
01:36:56,458 --> 01:36:58,832
- Which was Uncle Mark to a fuckin' tee.
- [Alba laughs]

1913
01:36:58,833 --> 01:37:01,124
"You're a good kid. Seriously."

1914
01:37:01,125 --> 01:37:03,625
- As if he didn't mean it otherwise.
- [Jay's dad] Oh, God. I broke up.

1915
01:37:04,541 --> 01:37:07,375
I've never seen you laugh so hard.
Mom either.

1916
01:37:07,875 --> 01:37:11,666
She was always so sad when she drank.

1917
01:37:12,500 --> 01:37:15,000
- Where is Uncle Mark?
- In jail for mail fraud.

1918
01:37:15,583 --> 01:37:16,790
- "Seriously?"
- Seriously.

1919
01:37:16,791 --> 01:37:18,500
[laughter]

1920
01:37:19,083 --> 01:37:19,916
That's a...

1921
01:37:20,833 --> 01:37:22,541
- [quiet exhale]
- [laughing stops]

1922
01:37:24,333 --> 01:37:29,041
We are sorry to gawp, but
you are all over the internet right now.

1923
01:37:29,666 --> 01:37:30,958
[Antonio] There is a video.

1924
01:37:32,041 --> 01:37:34,165
- On your phone?
- On all of our phones.

1925
01:37:34,166 --> 01:37:37,750
- A dramatic altercation.
- With another man.

1926
01:37:39,500 --> 01:37:41,208
[birds chirping in distance]

1927
01:37:46,666 --> 01:37:49,915
"Actor Jay Kelly becomes real life hero

1928
01:37:49,916 --> 01:37:52,165
as he apprehends criminal

1929
01:37:52,166 --> 01:37:55,665
in dramatic fashion,
worthy of the <i>cinema."</i>

1930
01:37:55,666 --> 01:37:56,582
[laughter]

1931
01:37:56,583 --> 01:38:02,290
Look at you, running
in your fancy moccasins. Run, Jay! Run!

1932
01:38:02,291 --> 01:38:06,290
"There was no 'action' or 'cut'
as Jay Kelly leaped from the train."

1933
01:38:06,291 --> 01:38:09,415
I deplore violence. Haven't
we evolved beyond hitting and kicking?

1934
01:38:09,416 --> 01:38:11,124
But he had to defend himself.

1935
01:38:11,125 --> 01:38:16,374
It says here the man was
a crazed thief, a lunatic in Spandex.

1936
01:38:16,375 --> 01:38:17,832
He wasn't a lunatic. He was--

1937
01:38:17,833 --> 01:38:20,457
- It was perhaps a sexual threat.
- No!

1938
01:38:20,458 --> 01:38:22,040
No. No. It wasn't.

1939
01:38:22,041 --> 01:38:24,666
You finally manage
to get your trousers dirty, Studly?

1940
01:38:26,958 --> 01:38:31,790
It is now time to take our real, live hero

1941
01:38:31,791 --> 01:38:35,040
- to the real, live party.
- [Jay's dad chuckles]

1942
01:38:35,041 --> 01:38:36,125
[scattered applause]

1943
01:38:37,208 --> 01:38:39,833
[Jay's dad] You know what this countryside
reminds me of?

1944
01:38:40,333 --> 01:38:43,833
Bakersfield, California. Beautiful place.

1945
01:38:44,750 --> 01:38:48,124
But everybody's out of work there. So sad.

1946
01:38:48,125 --> 01:38:50,040
I used to do a lot of business
in Bakersfield.

1947
01:38:50,041 --> 01:38:54,041
- [dance music thumping, muffled]
- [melancholy orchestral score]

1948
01:38:58,083 --> 01:39:00,541
[orchestral score swells]

1949
01:39:01,166 --> 01:39:02,582
Fuck me.

1950
01:39:02,583 --> 01:39:04,874
- [Ron] There he is.
- [music volume normalizes]

1951
01:39:04,875 --> 01:39:06,040
He's here.

1952
01:39:06,041 --> 01:39:08,165
[guests chattering]

1953
01:39:08,166 --> 01:39:10,540
Jay Kelly, so handsome!

1954
01:39:10,541 --> 01:39:12,874
With the square-cut Superman jaw.

1955
01:39:12,875 --> 01:39:15,374
- Where were you?
- We said we'd meet at the party.

1956
01:39:15,375 --> 01:39:17,874
No, we said we'd meet at the dinner
and go to the party.

1957
01:39:17,875 --> 01:39:20,582
You said you'd go to the dinner,
and I'll go to the party.

1958
01:39:20,583 --> 01:39:22,415
You said, "Save me a tiramisu."

1959
01:39:22,416 --> 01:39:25,083
- How was the tiramisu?
- It was cheesecake.

1960
01:39:26,708 --> 01:39:30,040
- Did you see the video?
- Oh. Our friends on the train filmed it.

1961
01:39:30,041 --> 01:39:32,874
- Great result. Congratulations.
- Calling me a hero. So embarrassing.

1962
01:39:32,875 --> 01:39:34,249
You are a hero, puppy.

1963
01:39:34,250 --> 01:39:37,290
If it was the other story,
I'd be the villain, not the hero.

1964
01:39:37,291 --> 01:39:39,999
Listen, listen. Come here.
I want you to hear this.

1965
01:39:40,000 --> 01:39:41,749
- Where are you goin'?
- Come here.

1966
01:39:41,750 --> 01:39:43,499
- [phone rings]
<i>- Hello.</i>

1967
01:39:43,500 --> 01:39:47,791
Alan, you got Ron and Jay.
Sorry for the tribute noise.

1968
01:39:48,291 --> 01:39:50,874
- Tell Jay the news.
- [Alan] <i>It's been taken care of, Jay.</i>

1969
01:39:50,875 --> 01:39:53,916
- What has?
<i>- Timothy, the lawsuit, the nose.</i>

1970
01:39:54,625 --> 01:39:55,624
<i>Everything.</i>

1971
01:39:55,625 --> 01:39:56,832
It's all done.

1972
01:39:56,833 --> 01:39:59,582
We discovered a pending drug charge
from the '90s

1973
01:39:59,583 --> 01:40:00,916
that would destroy his business.

1974
01:40:01,583 --> 01:40:04,624
- It's done?
<i>- It's gone away. You're free, Jay.</i>

1975
01:40:04,625 --> 01:40:06,707
[Alba] You are too young to be his daddy.

1976
01:40:06,708 --> 01:40:08,790
- Why, thank you.
- [Alba chuckles]

1977
01:40:08,791 --> 01:40:11,665
And you're too young to be young.
[kisses loudly]

1978
01:40:11,666 --> 01:40:17,082
[dance music continues]

1979
01:40:17,083 --> 01:40:19,708
- I want to apologize.
- To who, Timothy?

1980
01:40:20,291 --> 01:40:21,541
[Alan] <i>That can't happen, Jay.</i>

1981
01:40:22,041 --> 01:40:24,582
- He's my friend.
- [Alan] <i>Not anymore.</i>

1982
01:40:24,583 --> 01:40:26,832
<i>My counsel is to let it go.</i>

1983
01:40:26,833 --> 01:40:28,207
- Yeah?
<i>- Yeah.</i>

1984
01:40:28,208 --> 01:40:30,957
<i>It's settled.
You won't hear from him again.</i>

1985
01:40:30,958 --> 01:40:33,165
<i>Enjoy your tribute, Jay. You've earned it.</i>

1986
01:40:33,166 --> 01:40:36,124
I want whiskey
and spaghetti <i>bolognese!</i>

1987
01:40:36,125 --> 01:40:39,707
[Alba] Then we will eat
<i>spaghetti alla bolognese.</i>

1988
01:40:39,708 --> 01:40:43,499
- Thanks, Alan.
- [Alan] <i>Don't thank me. It was all Ron.</i>

1989
01:40:43,500 --> 01:40:45,333
<i>He really went to war for you.</i>

1990
01:40:46,125 --> 01:40:48,165
[dance music continues]

1991
01:40:48,166 --> 01:40:49,458
Thanks, Alan.

1992
01:40:54,125 --> 01:40:57,916
You all can make up stories,
but you and I know who I am.

1993
01:40:58,708 --> 01:41:00,375
You know who I am, Ron?

1994
01:41:01,333 --> 01:41:04,624
- Who am I?
- Look at you. You're the American dream.

1995
01:41:04,625 --> 01:41:06,332
You're the last of the old movie stars--

1996
01:41:06,333 --> 01:41:08,749
- I'm down here.
- You're up there, you're down here.

1997
01:41:08,750 --> 01:41:11,915
You're in here. It's amazing.
We've accomplished so much together.

1998
01:41:11,916 --> 01:41:14,457
Everything you say makes it worse.

1999
01:41:14,458 --> 01:41:17,915
You can stop running now, puppy.
It's time to go back to work.

2000
01:41:17,916 --> 01:41:19,415
I'm going dancing.

2001
01:41:19,416 --> 01:41:22,999
Oh! The famous Ron. Later? Later.

2002
01:41:23,000 --> 01:41:24,790
You start shooting on Monday,

2003
01:41:24,791 --> 01:41:27,666
and I gave them my word
you would be there.

2004
01:41:29,416 --> 01:41:31,041
Give my part to Ben Alcock.

2005
01:41:32,916 --> 01:41:35,249
Hey. Come here. Come here.

2006
01:41:35,250 --> 01:41:37,874
Do you know what I had to go through
to get you that job?

2007
01:41:37,875 --> 01:41:39,540
I mean, you're you.

2008
01:41:39,541 --> 01:41:42,290
But I was the one who went
to the Louis Brothers' tequila bar

2009
01:41:42,291 --> 01:41:43,790
in Bushwick and smoked crack.

2010
01:41:43,791 --> 01:41:44,999
It wasn't crack.

2011
01:41:45,000 --> 01:41:47,332
I don't know what it was, but I smoked it,

2012
01:41:47,333 --> 01:41:50,207
and for three hours, I was afraid
I was going to swallow my tongue.

2013
01:41:50,208 --> 01:41:52,790
- Anyways, it got you the job.
- They offered me the job.

2014
01:41:52,791 --> 01:41:55,540
The part was written
for a 35-year-old man.

2015
01:41:55,541 --> 01:41:57,291
It took some convincing.

2016
01:41:58,500 --> 01:42:01,625
And I'd do it again,
because I think what you do is magic.

2017
01:42:02,208 --> 01:42:05,291
I'm just an actor, Ron.
An actor that got famous.

2018
01:42:08,291 --> 01:42:12,125
Does none of this mean anything to you?
'Cause it means something to me.

2019
01:42:12,708 --> 01:42:14,665
Give my tribute to Ben. I'm goin' dancing.

2020
01:42:14,666 --> 01:42:15,665
I don't understand.

2021
01:42:15,666 --> 01:42:19,540
I think I've been a good partner,
a good friend. I loved you.

2022
01:42:19,541 --> 01:42:21,707
- I love you too, Ronnie.
- But are we friends?

2023
01:42:21,708 --> 01:42:24,332
- Of course we are.
- Then be a friend to me.

2024
01:42:24,333 --> 01:42:26,083
And let's go back to work.

2025
01:42:26,625 --> 01:42:29,832
I mean, you're Jay Kelly.
But I'm Jay Kelly too.

2026
01:42:29,833 --> 01:42:33,332
We did this together.
You actually said that to me one time.

2027
01:42:33,333 --> 01:42:34,707
You forgot.

2028
01:42:34,708 --> 01:42:36,458
[patting chest]

2029
01:42:37,625 --> 01:42:39,083
I'm dancing.

2030
01:42:39,791 --> 01:42:43,499
When you fuck yourself,
you're fucking me, you understand?

2031
01:42:43,500 --> 01:42:44,415
[Jay] I'm dancing.

2032
01:42:44,416 --> 01:42:46,333
[dance music continues]

2033
01:42:47,083 --> 01:42:49,125
You don't know how to be a friend!

2034
01:42:50,375 --> 01:42:53,125
You're my friend
who takes 15% of my income.

2035
01:42:57,333 --> 01:42:59,416
If you're not on that plane tomorrow...

2036
01:43:00,000 --> 01:43:00,958
I'm dancing.

2037
01:43:01,916 --> 01:43:05,499
I wish... I wish you were the man
I thought you were.

2038
01:43:05,500 --> 01:43:07,665
["Rumore" by Andrea Lo Vecchio starts]

2039
01:43:07,666 --> 01:43:10,750
I'm a cocker spaniel
dancing in the Serengeti.

2040
01:43:18,166 --> 01:43:21,791
[crowd cheering]

2041
01:43:27,458 --> 01:43:32,833
[guests chattering]

2042
01:43:35,125 --> 01:43:38,875
["Rumore" continues]

2043
01:43:45,000 --> 01:43:46,208
[crowd] Whoo!

2044
01:43:46,708 --> 01:43:49,291
["Rumore" continues]

2045
01:43:58,916 --> 01:44:01,874
[drum beat speeds up]

2046
01:44:01,875 --> 01:44:06,000
- [women laughing]
- [singing in Italian]

2047
01:44:12,750 --> 01:44:15,958
[music slows, vocals distort]

2048
01:44:16,541 --> 01:44:17,499
[Alba, echoing] Jay!

2049
01:44:17,500 --> 01:44:18,791
Jay!

2050
01:44:19,291 --> 01:44:20,125
Jay!

2051
01:44:20,791 --> 01:44:22,582
- Alba, you're an angel.
- Jay.

2052
01:44:22,583 --> 01:44:25,458
- Dance with me.
- Come. Your daddy is sick.

2053
01:44:26,041 --> 01:44:28,999
He is in the restaurant. Come on.

2054
01:44:29,000 --> 01:44:31,958
[speaking Italian]

2055
01:44:33,833 --> 01:44:35,707
I think he drunk too much.

2056
01:44:35,708 --> 01:44:39,249
He was eating spaghetti and doing yoga,
and he lost his balance.

2057
01:44:39,250 --> 01:44:41,540
- Where is he?
- In the kitchen with the doctor.

2058
01:44:41,541 --> 01:44:42,708
Dad?

2059
01:44:47,291 --> 01:44:48,791
[exhales]

2060
01:44:49,500 --> 01:44:50,500
Hey.

2061
01:44:52,583 --> 01:44:54,083
You doing okay there, Studly?

2062
01:44:55,541 --> 01:44:57,416
Heh. I lost my balance.

2063
01:44:58,333 --> 01:45:00,833
- Is that blood?
- No. That's the <i>bolognese.</i>

2064
01:45:02,791 --> 01:45:05,333
[speaks Italian]

2065
01:45:05,958 --> 01:45:06,957
He's fine.

2066
01:45:06,958 --> 01:45:09,624
[speaks Italian]

2067
01:45:09,625 --> 01:45:11,624
- And too much wine.
- Uh-huh.

2068
01:45:11,625 --> 01:45:12,915
[speaks Italian]

2069
01:45:12,916 --> 01:45:14,249
He needs to rest.

2070
01:45:14,250 --> 01:45:16,166
- [speaks Italian]
- [replies in Italian]

2071
01:45:16,958 --> 01:45:18,958
- [doctor speaks Italian]
- [replies in Italian]

2072
01:45:20,666 --> 01:45:22,041
[Alba speaks Italian]

2073
01:45:23,708 --> 01:45:24,583
Hey.

2074
01:45:25,958 --> 01:45:27,208
It's so bright in here.

2075
01:45:29,291 --> 01:45:30,375
Can I do anything?

2076
01:45:32,333 --> 01:45:33,999
I... I wish I'd seen Daisy.

2077
01:45:34,000 --> 01:45:34,958
Yeah.

2078
01:45:35,541 --> 01:45:37,374
You remember being 18.

2079
01:45:37,375 --> 01:45:41,332
You asked me that already.
I said I remember Brylcreem.

2080
01:45:41,333 --> 01:45:42,749
Right. Sorry.

2081
01:45:42,750 --> 01:45:44,583
[Jay's dad exhales]

2082
01:45:45,291 --> 01:45:47,624
- I want to go home now.
- Just get some sleep.

2083
01:45:47,625 --> 01:45:49,165
No, I want to leave now.

2084
01:45:49,166 --> 01:45:51,708
- Stay. See Italy.
- I've seen it.

2085
01:45:52,291 --> 01:45:54,750
Audrey booked me
on the 8 a.m. flight from Pisa.

2086
01:45:57,541 --> 01:45:59,165
Are you pissed at me?

2087
01:45:59,166 --> 01:46:00,250
No.

2088
01:46:01,500 --> 01:46:04,749
I really want you to have a good time.
I want you to stay till tomorrow.

2089
01:46:04,750 --> 01:46:07,165
We never get a chance
to spend time together.

2090
01:46:07,166 --> 01:46:08,791
[door opens]

2091
01:46:09,375 --> 01:46:11,082
[inhales]

2092
01:46:11,083 --> 01:46:13,207
- The taxi is here.
- Y--

2093
01:46:13,208 --> 01:46:14,708
Stay for my tribute.

2094
01:46:20,083 --> 01:46:22,708
Come on, Dad. Please stay.

2095
01:46:25,166 --> 01:46:26,125
Where's my bag?

2096
01:46:27,000 --> 01:46:28,416
[Alba] It's in the taxi.

2097
01:46:36,625 --> 01:46:38,165
[Alba, softly] It was nice to meet you.

2098
01:46:38,166 --> 01:46:39,083
[Jay] Hey.

2099
01:46:39,583 --> 01:46:40,958
- [Jay's dad] Bye, Alba.
<i>- Ciao.</i>

2100
01:46:43,125 --> 01:46:44,000
Hey.

2101
01:46:44,833 --> 01:46:47,374
- Thanks for the party, Studly.
- Dad. Come on.

2102
01:46:47,375 --> 01:46:48,958
Hey. Wait.

2103
01:46:49,500 --> 01:46:51,500
Hey, Dad. Dad!

2104
01:46:52,000 --> 01:46:52,833
Dad!

2105
01:46:53,458 --> 01:46:56,291
- [Jay, distantly] Come on!
- [plaintive music playing]

2106
01:47:04,875 --> 01:47:06,874
[music fades]

2107
01:47:06,875 --> 01:47:10,166
[panting]

2108
01:47:12,041 --> 01:47:15,333
- [gasps]
- [vehicles rumbling]

2109
01:47:28,833 --> 01:47:30,833
[eerie music playing]

2110
01:47:38,750 --> 01:47:41,749
[brakes screech]

2111
01:47:41,750 --> 01:47:43,375
[cars whoosh]

2112
01:47:45,250 --> 01:47:46,625
[brakes squeal]

2113
01:47:49,625 --> 01:47:50,666
[door opens]

2114
01:47:51,375 --> 01:47:53,665
Is that Jay Kelly? [laughs]

2115
01:47:53,666 --> 01:47:54,583
[Jay] Hey.

2116
01:47:55,250 --> 01:47:56,749
- You okay, man?
- Yeah. Hey. Hi.

2117
01:47:56,750 --> 01:47:59,124
Ah. Proud to be
sharing a tribute with you, <i>amigo.</i>

2118
01:47:59,125 --> 01:48:00,624
- Thanks, Ben.
- [woman] Hey.

2119
01:48:00,625 --> 01:48:02,207
- You know my wife, Melanie.
- Yeah.

2120
01:48:02,208 --> 01:48:06,957
My daughters, Seraphina, Lily and Bridget,
my sons, Cassian and Cole...

2121
01:48:06,958 --> 01:48:09,874
You got Arlo over there,
the newest addition to the clan.

2122
01:48:09,875 --> 01:48:13,957
We got Nana and Nono, Terry and Ernie,
brother-in-law, Spike.

2123
01:48:13,958 --> 01:48:15,040
[Spike] Big fan.

2124
01:48:15,041 --> 01:48:18,332
My assistant, Pam.
Sorry about the clown cars.

2125
01:48:18,333 --> 01:48:20,332
Sorry I don't have anybody
to introduce you to.

2126
01:48:20,333 --> 01:48:23,790
Hey, only in Italy would they give
two middle-aged white men an award.

2127
01:48:23,791 --> 01:48:25,707
I mean, seriously, at this moment?

2128
01:48:25,708 --> 01:48:27,790
I guess we got Ron to thank for that, huh?

2129
01:48:27,791 --> 01:48:31,375
Yeah, this is awkward,
but I parted ways with Ron.

2130
01:48:33,250 --> 01:48:35,332
- When?
- A few hours ago.

2131
01:48:35,333 --> 01:48:37,707
I feel terrible. I mean, I love the guy,

2132
01:48:37,708 --> 01:48:40,249
but I just felt like
I was being looked after

2133
01:48:40,250 --> 01:48:42,458
by someone who needs looking after.

2134
01:48:43,041 --> 01:48:46,040
I mean, every time
it's his kids and inflamed feet

2135
01:48:46,041 --> 01:48:47,665
or Lois and whatever that is.

2136
01:48:47,666 --> 01:48:50,582
God bless him, but I need
someone younger, someone hungrier.

2137
01:48:50,583 --> 01:48:53,290
- Or older and more powerful.
- Right.

2138
01:48:53,291 --> 01:48:56,457
You were also getting into all that
psychodynamic stuff with him.

2139
01:48:56,458 --> 01:48:58,415
Yeah, yeah.
He's too much like my father.

2140
01:48:58,416 --> 01:49:00,249
- [Melanie] Or he wants to be.
- Yeah.

2141
01:49:00,250 --> 01:49:03,165
I have to keep saying to myself.
They are not our family.

2142
01:49:03,166 --> 01:49:04,457
- [Melanie] Or your friend.
- No!

2143
01:49:04,458 --> 01:49:06,665
We give these guys 15% of everything,

2144
01:49:06,666 --> 01:49:08,582
then they want to be treated
like our friend.

2145
01:49:08,583 --> 01:49:10,457
- Friends do not take 15%.
- No.

2146
01:49:10,458 --> 01:49:11,374
Huh.

2147
01:49:11,375 --> 01:49:15,208
- Oh. We heard about your act of bravery.
- Yeah! Nicely done, <i>amigo.</i>

2148
01:49:15,958 --> 01:49:17,915
- Ah, yeah.
- Jay Kelly for President!

2149
01:49:17,916 --> 01:49:18,832
[both laughing]

2150
01:49:18,833 --> 01:49:20,999
No, I mean, seriously.
Would you ever run?

2151
01:49:21,000 --> 01:49:22,582
No, it's just...

2152
01:49:22,583 --> 01:49:24,124
I, uh...

2153
01:49:24,125 --> 01:49:26,166
Can you excuse me for a minute?

2154
01:49:27,208 --> 01:49:31,500
Uh, actually, we need a few extra tickets
for the fam, if you have any to spare.

2155
01:49:34,250 --> 01:49:35,666
I can spare all of 'em, Ben.

2156
01:49:36,375 --> 01:49:37,625
Thanks, brother. I owe you.

2157
01:49:41,250 --> 01:49:42,583
Maybe just leave me one.

2158
01:49:43,416 --> 01:49:44,707
[Ben] Yeah, sure.

2159
01:49:44,708 --> 01:49:47,041
[family members chatter faintly]

2160
01:49:48,750 --> 01:49:50,749
[Ben] Saddle up! Let's go!

2161
01:49:50,750 --> 01:49:52,833
[cars drive away]

2162
01:50:00,291 --> 01:50:01,625
[bird hoots]

2163
01:50:04,333 --> 01:50:06,041
[hooting]

2164
01:50:11,500 --> 01:50:13,333
[phone line rings]

2165
01:50:16,208 --> 01:50:19,291
- [Jessica] <i>Hello?</i>
- Hey, Jess, it's Dad.

2166
01:50:19,791 --> 01:50:22,750
<i>- Hi.</i>
- Hey, uh, is this a good time to talk?

2167
01:50:23,458 --> 01:50:26,915
<i>- What's up?</i>
- Well, I'm in Italy. [chuckles]

2168
01:50:26,916 --> 01:50:31,749
<i>- I read about your real-life heroics.</i>
- Ah, it's a news story. It's not true.

2169
01:50:31,750 --> 01:50:34,625
<i>- Yeah, well, you fooled them again.</i>
- Yeah.

2170
01:50:35,250 --> 01:50:37,541
<i>- So why are you calling?</i>
- Well, listen.

2171
01:50:38,583 --> 01:50:41,040
I'm feelin' bad about
the last time we were together.

2172
01:50:41,041 --> 01:50:42,625
Sorry about that.

2173
01:50:43,666 --> 01:50:47,290
I just couldn't take that guy.
Are you still seeing him?

2174
01:50:47,291 --> 01:50:48,541
Yes.

2175
01:50:49,375 --> 01:50:52,165
Well, I wanna hear you out, so...

2176
01:50:52,166 --> 01:50:54,915
- if that's what you need to happen, and--
- Uh-huh.

2177
01:50:54,916 --> 01:50:59,665
Listen, I have this tribute here
in Tuscany. I'd love for you to come.

2178
01:50:59,666 --> 01:51:02,499
- Since when do you care about a tribute?
- Well...

2179
01:51:02,500 --> 01:51:04,541
Good question. I...

2180
01:51:05,583 --> 01:51:07,416
I did make those movies.

2181
01:51:08,666 --> 01:51:12,957
So you think that if I go
and I celebrate your career,

2182
01:51:12,958 --> 01:51:15,249
that your brilliance
is gonna make me forgive you?

2183
01:51:15,250 --> 01:51:17,707
- No. No.
- Maybe yes, Jay.

2184
01:51:17,708 --> 01:51:19,833
Well... Maybe yes.

2185
01:51:20,583 --> 01:51:22,458
It's 35 years of my life.

2186
01:51:24,416 --> 01:51:27,833
- I'm 34.
- I just want you to come with me.

2187
01:51:28,541 --> 01:51:31,582
To see what I did.
To be there to celebrate.

2188
01:51:31,583 --> 01:51:33,416
It's got to have meant something.

2189
01:51:36,791 --> 01:51:38,166
What if it didn't?

2190
01:51:44,791 --> 01:51:47,791
I could've been a very good dad
to you, Jess.

2191
01:51:49,750 --> 01:51:51,416
I wanted to, you know.

2192
01:51:52,875 --> 01:51:56,665
It's just things with your mother
and distance,

2193
01:51:56,666 --> 01:52:00,332
and I didn't execute it
the way I planned it.

2194
01:52:00,333 --> 01:52:02,833
- That's just--
- Just be honest with me, Jay.

2195
01:52:03,333 --> 01:52:07,082
[voice breaking] Stop rationalizing
and trying to defend yourself.

2196
01:52:07,083 --> 01:52:08,583
Just stop.

2197
01:52:14,250 --> 01:52:17,207
I was young.
And I wanted something very badly,

2198
01:52:17,208 --> 01:52:20,874
and I was afraid that if I took
my eye off of it, I couldn't have it.

2199
01:52:20,875 --> 01:52:22,375
And I was right.

2200
01:52:23,125 --> 01:52:24,708
There was no other way to do it.

2201
01:52:27,958 --> 01:52:28,790
[Jessica sniffles]

2202
01:52:28,791 --> 01:52:30,416
And it meant choosing...

2203
01:52:31,833 --> 01:52:33,041
it over you.

2204
01:52:34,458 --> 01:52:36,000
But it was supposed to be temporary.

2205
01:52:37,333 --> 01:52:38,375
Just...

2206
01:52:40,250 --> 01:52:42,041
until I had what I wanted. And--

2207
01:52:45,000 --> 01:52:46,416
But then I had to keep it.

2208
01:52:49,666 --> 01:52:52,375
My ten-year-old self
is giving you the finger.

2209
01:52:53,666 --> 01:52:55,208
What about you now?

2210
01:52:57,375 --> 01:52:59,124
You don't have to worry about me, Dad.

2211
01:52:59,125 --> 01:53:02,582
I'm okay. I love what I do.
I have friends.

2212
01:53:02,583 --> 01:53:05,125
I'm gonna have a good life,
just not with you.

2213
01:53:06,458 --> 01:53:08,582
And you're okay too, you know?

2214
01:53:08,583 --> 01:53:10,957
You're--
You're a good movie star, you know?

2215
01:53:10,958 --> 01:53:12,665
You make a lot of people happy.

2216
01:53:12,666 --> 01:53:14,750
[sorrowful piano music playing]

2217
01:53:16,958 --> 01:53:18,999
I think I'm gonna quit acting.

2218
01:53:19,000 --> 01:53:22,249
I need you to sign a photo
for Theo's teacher. She's a big fan.

2219
01:53:22,250 --> 01:53:23,374
What? Oh.

2220
01:53:23,375 --> 01:53:25,582
Okay. Jess, it'd mean so much to me...

2221
01:53:25,583 --> 01:53:26,915
- For Helen.
- What?

2222
01:53:26,916 --> 01:53:29,625
- That's her name. Helen.
- Okay. Helen.

2223
01:53:30,125 --> 01:53:31,415
- I'm sorry, Dad.
- Please, Jess--

2224
01:53:31,416 --> 01:53:34,291
Theo's calling,
and I hope you have a good tribute.

2225
01:53:34,791 --> 01:53:35,875
[on phone] <i>Good-bye, Jay.</i>

2226
01:53:36,375 --> 01:53:37,290
Jess!

2227
01:53:37,291 --> 01:53:39,375
[piano music grows louder]

2228
01:54:09,291 --> 01:54:12,375
[soft strings join with the piano]

2229
01:54:25,708 --> 01:54:27,874
[strings swell and then fade]

2230
01:54:27,875 --> 01:54:29,957
[gasps]

2231
01:54:29,958 --> 01:54:32,041
[solo piano continues]

2232
01:54:41,541 --> 01:54:43,540
[...then fades]

2233
01:54:43,541 --> 01:54:47,875
[birds tweeting]

2234
01:54:52,333 --> 01:54:55,375
[suitcase rolling]

2235
01:55:01,458 --> 01:55:03,541
[approaching voices, speaking Italian]

2236
01:55:06,833 --> 01:55:11,250
Oh! The famous Ron!
Have you seen Jay Kelly?

2237
01:55:11,875 --> 01:55:15,416
- [Ron] Not since last night.
- [woman exclaims in Italian]

2238
01:55:16,000 --> 01:55:21,124
- See you later.
- The tribute is at 5. Precise!

2239
01:55:21,125 --> 01:55:22,208
[Ron] <i>Grazie.</i>

2240
01:55:50,541 --> 01:55:54,458
Ron! Hey! Ron.

2241
01:55:55,833 --> 01:55:56,665
Hey.

2242
01:55:56,666 --> 01:56:00,083
[driver speaking Italian]

2243
01:56:03,125 --> 01:56:05,290
[driver continues in Italian]

2244
01:56:05,291 --> 01:56:09,125
- Pull over. Stop, stop, stop.
- Okay. [speaks Italian]

2245
01:56:13,500 --> 01:56:15,624
[Jay panting]

2246
01:56:15,625 --> 01:56:17,166
Are you okay?

2247
01:56:18,208 --> 01:56:20,165
[panting heavily]

2248
01:56:20,166 --> 01:56:21,583
Take a second.

2249
01:56:23,916 --> 01:56:24,833
It's okay.

2250
01:56:25,500 --> 01:56:27,500
[Jay continues panting]

2251
01:56:35,791 --> 01:56:38,625
Look, I'm sorry about... [panting]

2252
01:56:42,125 --> 01:56:43,291
I'm sorry.

2253
01:56:45,500 --> 01:56:47,040
Um...

2254
01:56:47,041 --> 01:56:48,458
I appreciate it.

2255
01:56:52,291 --> 01:56:53,833
But you got me thinking.

2256
01:56:55,291 --> 01:56:59,125
I was up all last night, talkin' to Lois.

2257
01:57:00,125 --> 01:57:01,916
And I think you have it right.

2258
01:57:03,416 --> 01:57:05,750
There comes a point
when you have to reassess.

2259
01:57:10,208 --> 01:57:12,666
I love you. I really do.

2260
01:57:15,583 --> 01:57:17,499
And I appreciate the apology.

2261
01:57:17,500 --> 01:57:18,541
But I...

2262
01:57:19,541 --> 01:57:21,250
I can't work with you anymore.

2263
01:57:23,166 --> 01:57:24,833
It's not good for me.

2264
01:57:28,458 --> 01:57:29,957
The Italians are lookin' for you.

2265
01:57:29,958 --> 01:57:32,416
You have a tribute starting
in a couple of hours.

2266
01:57:34,916 --> 01:57:37,541
I gotta make a plane,
but try and go, okay?

2267
01:57:40,125 --> 01:57:42,000
I mean, you came all this way.

2268
01:57:46,041 --> 01:57:47,458
Hey, Ron?

2269
01:57:54,208 --> 01:57:57,291
Come to the tribute with me.
As my friend.

2270
01:58:01,375 --> 01:58:02,666
I mean...

2271
01:58:04,958 --> 01:58:06,375
we did this together.

2272
01:58:14,125 --> 01:58:16,125
You're the one I want there most of all.

2273
01:58:22,666 --> 01:58:24,500
I'm the only one who is here.

2274
01:58:25,291 --> 01:58:28,541
[somber music playing]

2275
01:58:41,125 --> 01:58:44,375
[somber music continues]

2276
01:59:02,458 --> 01:59:05,708
[somber music continues]

2277
01:59:35,833 --> 01:59:39,541
[somber music continues]

2278
02:00:03,916 --> 02:00:06,457
[somber music continues]

2279
02:00:06,458 --> 02:00:07,541
[phone chimes]

2280
02:00:13,291 --> 02:00:15,041
{\an8}[firework sound effects popping]

2281
02:00:24,291 --> 02:00:26,291
[firework sound effects popping]

2282
02:00:28,041 --> 02:00:30,333
[somber music continues]

2283
02:00:38,375 --> 02:00:39,833
[metallic ringing]

2284
02:00:41,750 --> 02:00:43,583
[indistinct chatter]

2285
02:00:44,750 --> 02:00:46,750
[metallic ringing]

2286
02:00:51,958 --> 02:00:53,625
[overlapping chatter]

2287
02:00:55,625 --> 02:00:57,000
Look at this here.

2288
02:00:58,666 --> 02:00:59,541
They came.

2289
02:01:04,458 --> 02:01:05,958
That's great.

2290
02:01:08,541 --> 02:01:10,166
[exhales]

2291
02:01:15,541 --> 02:01:17,790
[chatter silences]

2292
02:01:17,791 --> 02:01:20,041
WINNER OF THE STRAWBERRY TREE AWARD
JAY KELLY

2293
02:01:21,125 --> 02:01:24,166
[orchestral music playing]

2294
02:01:35,041 --> 02:01:36,416
<i>Well, hello.</i>

2295
02:01:41,500 --> 02:01:44,707
[orchestral music continues]

2296
02:01:44,708 --> 02:01:46,000
<i>Who the hell is this?</i>

2297
02:01:48,541 --> 02:01:49,541
<i>Here we go.</i>

2298
02:01:52,583 --> 02:01:54,415
<i>I prefer to think of myself
as a family man,</i>

2299
02:01:54,416 --> 02:01:56,708
<i>and that's what we all are here,
whether we like it or not.</i>

2300
02:01:58,041 --> 02:01:59,499
<i>We are a family.</i>

2301
02:01:59,500 --> 02:02:03,041
<i>That doesn't matter now, 'cause
you got about two fuckin' seconds to live!</i>

2302
02:02:06,083 --> 02:02:08,791
<i>Now you really didn't think
I was gonna sit this one out, did ya?</i>

2303
02:02:11,500 --> 02:02:14,874
<i>The way this works is, you do
the thing you're scared shitless of,</i>

2304
02:02:14,875 --> 02:02:16,750
<i>and you get the courage after you do it.</i>

2305
02:02:18,333 --> 02:02:19,208
<i>I won't let you down, sir.</i>

2306
02:02:19,916 --> 02:02:22,500
[orchestral music continues]

2307
02:02:28,833 --> 02:02:29,875
<i>So what's it gonna be?</i>

2308
02:02:30,625 --> 02:02:32,083
<i>Yes or no answer.</i>

2309
02:02:33,166 --> 02:02:35,041
<i>That's what I call a fucking show!</i>

2310
02:02:41,583 --> 02:02:42,708
<i>I stand before you...</i>

2311
02:02:44,916 --> 02:02:45,750
<i>naked.</i>

2312
02:02:52,583 --> 02:02:55,333
[soft piano music playing]

2313
02:03:08,125 --> 02:03:10,125
[soft piano music continues]

2314
02:03:26,875 --> 02:03:30,083
[soft piano music continues]

2315
02:03:51,583 --> 02:03:54,416
[music slows and fades to soft strings]

2316
02:04:00,791 --> 02:04:02,624
[girls giggling]

2317
02:04:02,625 --> 02:04:05,540
[Jess] <i>Dad, it's not over yet.
It's</i> The...

2318
02:04:05,541 --> 02:04:07,415
[Jess and Daisy]
Kelly and Kelly Show!

2319
02:04:07,416 --> 02:04:11,708
<i>- Starring Kelly!
- And Kelly!</i>

2320
02:04:12,750 --> 02:04:18,708
<i>And now it's time for
Daisy Genevieve Kelly's famous front roll!</i>

2321
02:04:21,291 --> 02:04:23,083
[giggling]

2322
02:04:24,125 --> 02:04:26,207
- [Daisy] Dad! It's not over!
- [Jess] And Jessica...

2323
02:04:26,208 --> 02:04:29,540
Hilary Kelly will do
her more famous cartwheel.

2324
02:04:29,541 --> 02:04:31,999
[grunts and giggles]

2325
02:04:32,000 --> 02:04:35,458
[Jess] And now for some magic.
Dad! It's not over.

2326
02:04:36,083 --> 02:04:39,499
[girls laughing]

2327
02:04:39,500 --> 02:04:41,708
- What do we do now?
- Kelly!

2328
02:04:42,708 --> 02:04:45,165
[Jess] And now...
Wait, Dad! You're missing it!

2329
02:04:45,166 --> 02:04:47,833
For Daisy's--
Dad, you're gonna miss it!

2330
02:04:48,416 --> 02:04:52,833
Now, for Daisy's
Hollywood-renowned Charleston.

2331
02:04:55,458 --> 02:04:56,874
[girls laughing]

2332
02:04:56,875 --> 02:04:58,958
[piano resumes]

2333
02:05:02,208 --> 02:05:04,208
[girls laughing]

2334
02:05:06,166 --> 02:05:07,416
Okay, there we are.

2335
02:05:07,916 --> 02:05:10,958
And Jessica's California-renowned tap.

2336
02:05:15,166 --> 02:05:17,500
Kelly! [laughs]

2337
02:05:18,875 --> 02:05:19,832
Sorry.

2338
02:05:19,833 --> 02:05:22,665
- Kelly and Kelly!
- No, it's Kelly and Kelly.

2339
02:05:22,666 --> 02:05:26,915
<i>- No, it's Kelly and Kelly.
- No, it's Kelly and Kelly.</i>

2340
02:05:26,916 --> 02:05:30,415
<i>- No, it's Kelly and Kel-ly.
- It's Kelly and Kelly.</i>

2341
02:05:30,416 --> 02:05:32,500
<i>Watch the telly, smelly Kelly.</i>

2342
02:05:33,541 --> 02:05:36,416
[soft piano and string music continues]

2343
02:05:48,625 --> 02:05:52,041
[applause]

2344
02:06:08,500 --> 02:06:10,165
Can I go again?

2345
02:06:10,166 --> 02:06:12,791
[applause fades]

2346
02:06:15,000 --> 02:06:16,833
I'd like another one.

2347
02:06:20,166 --> 02:06:24,208
[orchestral music continues]

2348
02:06:52,625 --> 02:06:56,666
[orchestral music playing]

2349
02:07:23,000 --> 02:07:27,041
[orchestral music continues]

2350
02:08:17,000 --> 02:08:19,000
[soft piano music continues]

2351
02:08:44,916 --> 02:08:46,916
[soft piano music playing]

2352
02:08:52,291 --> 02:08:57,916
[upbeat orchestral music playing]

2353
02:09:32,750 --> 02:09:38,375
[upbeat orchestral music continues]

2354
02:10:12,000 --> 02:10:14,000
[soft orchestral music playing]

2355
02:10:21,500 --> 02:10:23,374
[orchestral music swells]

2356
02:10:23,375 --> 02:10:25,458
[sweeping orchestral music playing]

2357
02:10:52,833 --> 02:10:54,833
[sweeping orchestral music continues]

2358
02:11:09,291 --> 02:11:11,291
[orchestral music swells]

2359
02:11:15,458 --> 02:11:17,458
[orchestral music stops]

